cess}}\n|-\n|60\n|September 22, 2019<br />21:10\n|LA-2, XSLC\n|3B/E  + [[Yuanzheng-1|YZ-1]]\n|[[BeiDou Navigation Satellite System|BeiDou]]-3 [[List of BeiDou satellites|M23]] <br /> [[BeiDou Navigation Satellite System|BeiDou]]-3 [[List of BeiDou satellites|M24]] \n|[[Medium Earth orbit|MEO]]\n|{{Success}}\n|-\n|61\n|October 17, 2019<br />15:21\n|LA-3, XSLC\n|3B/E\n|[[TJSW-4]]\n|[[Geosynchronous transfer orbit|GTO]]\n|{{Success}}\n|-\n|62\n|November 4, 2019<br />17:43\n|LA-2, XSLC\n|3B/E\n|[[BeiDou Navigation Satellite System|BeiDou]]-3 [[List of BeiDou satellites|I3]]\n|[[Geosynchronous transfer orbit|GTO]]\n|{{Success}}\n|-\n|63\n|November 23, 2019<br />00:55\n|LA-3, XSLC\n|3B/E  + [[Yuanzheng-1|YZ-1]]\n|[[BeiDou Navigation Satellite System|BeiDou]]-3 [[List of BeiDou satellites|M21]] <br /> [[BeiDou Navigation Satellite System|BeiDou]]-3 [[List of BeiDou satellites|M22]] \n|[[Medium Earth orbit|MEO]]\n|{{Success}}\n|-\n|64\n|December 16, 2019<br />07:22\n|LA-3, XSLC\n|3B/E  + [[Yuanzheng-1|YZ-1]]\n|[[BeiDou Navigation Satellite System|BeiDou]]-3 [[List of BeiDou satellites|M19]] <br /> [[BeiDou Navigation Satellite System|BeiDou]]-3 [[List of BeiDou satellites|M20]] \n|[[Medium Earth orbit|MEO]]\n|{{Success}}\n|-\n|65\n|January 7, 2020<br />15:20\n|LA-2, XSLC\n|3B/E\n|[[TJSW-5]]\n|[[Geosynchronous transfer orbit|GTO]]\n|{{Success}}\n|-\n|66\n|March 9, 2020<br />11:55\n|LA-2, XSLC\n|3B/E\n|[[BeiDou Navigation Satellite System|BeiDou]]-3 [[List of BeiDou satellites|G2]]\n|[[Geosynchronous transfer orbit|GTO]]\n|{{Success}}\n|-\n|67\n|April 9, 2020<br />11:46\n|LA-2, XSLC\n|3B/E\n|[[Palapa|Palapa-N1 (Nusantara Dua)]] \n|[[Geosynchronous transfer orbit|GTO]]\n|{{Failure}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/2020-04/09/c_1125834989.htm|title=PALAPA-N1\u536b\u661f\u53d1\u5c04\u5931\u5229|last=Jing|first=Zhan|date=9 April 2020|website=Xinhua|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Flight mishaps ==\n\n=== Intelsat 708 launch failure ===\nOn 14 February 1996, the launch of the first Long March 3B with [[Intelsat 708]] failed just after liftoff when the launch vehicle veered off course and exploded when it hit the ground at T+23 seconds. One person on the ground was killed by the explosion (the total number of casualties is unknown). The cause of the accident was traced to short-circuiting of the vehicle's guidance platform at liftoff.<ref name=\"cnn1999\">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/resources/1999/coxreport/satellite/pg1.html|title=Satellite Launches in the PRC: Loral|work=CNN|accessdate= 8 August 2018|date=25 May 1999}}</ref> The number of casualties is debated and unclear even decades after the accident. The Chinese official death toll is usually of the order of few casualties, whereas some estimates place the number of people dead to a few hundred (see [[Intelsat 708]]-article).\n\nThe participation of [[Space Systems/Loral]] in the accident investigation caused great political controversy in the United States since the information provided during the accident investigation would help China improve its rockets and ballistic missiles. The U.S. Congress reclassified satellite technology as a [[Ammunition|munition]] and placed it back under the restrictive [[International Traffic in Arms Regulations]] in 1998.<ref name=\"zenio2006\">{{cite news|last1=Zelnio|first1=Ryan|title=A short history of export control policy|url=http://www.thespacereview.com/article/528/1|work=The Space Review |date=January 9, 2006}}</ref> No license to launch U.S. spacecraft on Chinese rockets has been approved by the [[United States Department of State|U.S. State Department]] since then, and an official at the [[Bureau of Industry and Security]] emphasized in 2016 that \"no U.S.-origin content, regardless of significance, regardless of whether it's incorporated into a foreign-made item, can go to China\".<ref name=\"selding2016\">{{cite news|last1=de Selding|first1=Peter B.|title=U.S. ITAR satellite export regime's effects still strong in Europe|url=http://spacenews.com/u-s-itar-satellite-export-regimes-effects-still-strong-in-europe/|work=SpaceNews|date=April 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Palapa-D partial launch failure ===\nOn 31 August 2009, during the launch of [[Palapa-D]], the third stage engine under-performed and placed the satellite into a lower than planned orbit. The satellite was able to make up the performance shortfall using its own engine and reach geosynchronous orbit, but with its lifetime shortened to 10.5 years from the originally projected 15-16 years. The investigation found that the failure was due to burn-through of the engine's gas generator, and that \"the most likely cause of the burn-through was a foreign matter or humidity-caused icing in the engine's liquid-hydrogen injectors\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=de Selding|first1=Peter B.|title=Burn-through Blamed in China Long March Mishap|url=http://spacenews.com/burn-through-blamed-china-long-march-mishap/|publisher=SpaceNews|date=19 November 2009 |accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== ChinaSat-9A partial launch failure ===\nOn 19 June 2017, a Long March 3B/E mission carrying [[ChinaSat_9A|ChinaSat-9A]] ended in partial failure. Officials did not release details regarding the status of the mission for at least 4 hours after liftoff.<ref>http://spaceflight101.com/long-march-3b-zhongxing-9a-launch/</ref> Two weeks later, on 7 July 2017, officials confirmed that the mission had been anomalous, with Space Daily reporting that \"an anomaly was found on the carrier rocket's rolling control thruster, part of the attitude control engine, during the third gliding phase\". The failure in the rocket's third stage left the payload in a lower than intended orbit, and the payload was forced to spend two weeks reaching its intended orbit under its own power.<ref>http://www.spacedaily.com/reports/Chinese_satellite_Zhongxing_9A_enters_preset_orbit_999.html</ref>\n\n=== Palapa-N1 (Nusantara Dua) launch failure ===\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight|China}}\n*[http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/library/report/1999/3b.htm LM-3B User's Manual] at GlobalSecurity.org\n*[http://www.calt.com/english/ps/index.html Long March-3B (LM-3B)] at the China Academy of Launch Vehicle Technology\n\n{{Long March rockets}}\n{{Expendable launch systems}}\n{{CLEP}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Long March 3b}}\n[[Category:Long March (rocket family)]]\n[[Category:Vehicles introduced in 1996]]\n", "name_user": "CRS-20", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePalapa-N1 (Nusantara Dua) launch failure", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_March_3B"}
{"title_page": "Billy Gilmour (footballer)", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{about|the Scottish footballer|the former Canadian ice hockey player|Billy Gilmour (ice hockey)}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Billy Gilmour\n| image = File:Chelsea 7 Grimsby 1 (48798190337).jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = Gilmour in 2019\n| fullname = Billy Clifford Gilmour<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/612828 |title=Updated squads for 2017/18 Premier League confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=2 February 2018 |accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2001|6|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| height = {{convert|1.68|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/billy-gilmour-inside-the-rise-of-chelsea-and-scotlands-new/1wjg5pl8jnznw17twvg3xbs7xq |title=Billy Gilmour: Inside the rise of Chelsea and Scotland's 'new Modric' |publisher=Goal |accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref>\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]\n| clubnumber = 47\n| youthyears1 = 2009\u20132017\n| youthclubs1 = [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]]\n| youthyears2 = 2017\u2013\n| youthclubs2 = [[Chelsea F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Chelsea]]\n| years1 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]\n| caps1 = 3\n| goals1 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2015\u20132016\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national under-16 football team|Scotland U15]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2016\u20132017\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scotland national under-16 football team|Scotland U16]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2017\u20132018\n| nationalteam3 = [[Scotland national under-17 football team|Scotland U17]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 7\n| nationalgoals3 = 2\n| nationalyears4 = 2017\u20132019\n| nationalteam4 = [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland U19]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 7\n| nationalgoals4 = 3\n| nationalyears5 = 2018\u2013\n| nationalteam5 = [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 12\n| nationalgoals5 = 1\n| club-update =  15:49, 8 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 15 November 2019\n}}\n'''Billy Clifford Gilmour''' (born 11 June 2001) is a Scottish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Premier League]] club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2020/02/11/billy-gilmour-on-moving-up-to-the-senior-squad-permanently|title=Billy Gilmour on moving up to the senior squad permanently {{!}} Official Site {{!}} Chelsea Football Club|website=ChelseaFC|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> He is so good at football it\u2019s a crime and was convicted for sending Fabinho to the shops during a 2-0 win over Liverpool and was previously with [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], where he developed through the club's [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|academy]] and trained with the first team squad at the age of 15. He joined Chelsea in 2017 after turning down a professional contract with Rangers. He has represented Scotland at [[Scotland national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[Scotland national under-17 football team|under-17]] and [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21]] levels.\n\n==Early life==\nGilmour was born on 11 June 2001 in [[Glasgow]] and resided in [[Ardrossan]], [[North Ayrshire]]. His father served with the Royal Navy and played [[Scottish Junior Football Association|junior football]] for [[Ardrossan Winton Rovers F.C.|Ardrossan Winton Rovers]]. Gilmour attended Stanley Primary School in Ardrossan and [[Grange Academy, Kilmarnock|Grange Academy]] in [[Kilmarnock]], where he was part of the [[Scottish Football Association]] (SFA) Performance School programme.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/scotland-and-chelseas-billy-gilmour-ahead-of-plan-but-remains-rooted-in-reality-zpvgw38cd |title=Scotland and Chelsea\u2019s Billy Gilmour \u2018ahead of plan\u2019 but remains rooted in reality |first=Mark |last=Walker |newspaper=The Times |publisher= |date=16 October 2019 |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Rangers===\nGilmour developed his career as part of [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers Academy]]. His progress saw him fast-tracked towards the first team, making his debut for the under-20 development team in December 2016 at the age of 15 and being invited to train with the first team squad the following month by manager [[Mark Warburton]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bairner |first1=Robin |title=Meet Rangers wonderkid Billy Gilmour: The starlet Chelsea have beaten Arsenal and Manchester United to |url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/meet-rangers-wonderkid-billy-gilmour-the-starlet-chelsea/a29cvw6htgq312yqnx019a5d1 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=Goal.com |date=9 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Billy Gilmour shares his delight after training with Rangers first team squad |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/rangers-youngster-billy-gilmour-shares-9687629 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=Daily Record |date=25 January 2017 |location=Glasgow}}</ref> Gilmour was given a squad number and, following Warburton's departure from the club, was twice included in the provisional squad for [[Scottish Cup]] matches by [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] caretaker manager [[Graeme Murty]].<ref>https://www.glasgowtimes.co.uk/sport/15198720.graeme-murty-hopes-rangers-can-fend-off-interest-from-chelsea-in-midfield-star-billy-gilmour/</ref>\n\nThe next Rangers manager, [[Pedro Caixinha]], described Gilmour as a player with a \"bright future\" and held talks with the player's family in an attempt to persuade him to stay with the club.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Newport |first1=Andy |title=Caixinha reveals he's met Billy Gilmour's parents in bid to keep ace at Rangers |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/rangers-boss-pedro-caixinha-reveals-10127591 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=Daily Record |date=30 March 2017 |location=Glasgow}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Gilmour set for Chelsea move \u2013 unless Gers succeed in last-ditch talks |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/transfers/rangers-hold-talks-with-billy-gilmour-chelsea-transfer-wonderkid-a7658371.html |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=The Independent |date=30 March 2017 |location=London}}</ref> Rangers, however, announced in May 2017 that they had reached an agreement for Gilmour to join [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] for a \"significant fee\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Rangers: Youth prospect Billy Gilmour opts for summer switch to Chelsea |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39858879 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=BBC Sport |date=9 May 2017}}</ref> Reports suggested that Chelsea would pay an initial development fee of around \u00a3500,000, with potential further payments dependent on his progress.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yew |first1=Oliver |title=Who is Chelsea new-boy Billy Gilmour? |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11096/10871035/who-is-chelsea-new-boy-billy-gilmour |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=Sky Sports |date=10 May 2017 |language=en}}</ref> SFA Performance Director [[Malky Mackay]] had advised Gilmour and his family that he should stay at Rangers, as he would have had more chance of gaining first team experience. Mackay said, \"I really hope he goes out on loan quickly to someone and keeps progressing\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Malky Mackay: 'Billy Gilmour could have emulated Barry Ferguson at Rangers' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40927422 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=BBC Sport |date=14 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Chelsea===\nGilmour became officially contracted to Chelsea in July 2017, following his 16th birthday.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Amako |first1=Uche |title=Billy Gilmour signs Chelsea contract two months after agreeing to leave Rangers |url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/824767/Chelsea-Transfer-News-Billy-Gilmour-professional-contract-Rangers-gossip-rumours |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=Daily Express |date=4 July 2017 |location=London}}</ref> He joined the club's [[Chelsea F.C. Under-23s and Academy|under-18 squad]], making a goalscoring debut in an [[Professional Development League#Under-18 level|Under-18 Premier League]] match against [[Arsenal F.C. Academy|Arsenal]] during September 2017,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Forbes |first1=Craig |title=Billy Gilmour impresses in goalscoring Chelsea debut |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/billy-gilmour-impresses-in-goalscoring-chelsea-debut-1-4556555 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=The Scotsman |date=11 September 2017 |location=Edinburgh}}</ref> and going on to score in each of his first three appearances.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McDougall |first1=Mark |title=Former Rangers kid Billy Gilmour scores third goal in three games for Chelsea |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/former-rangers-kid-billy-gilmour-11264590 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=Daily Record |date=30 September 2017 |location=Glasgow}}</ref> In July 2018, after turning 17, Gilmour signed his first professional contract with Chelsea.<ref>{{cite news |title=Billy Gilmour: Former Rangers youth signs first professional contract at Chelsea |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44723798 |accessdate=7 August 2018 |work=BBC Sport |date=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Chelsea 2 Sheffield Utd 2 (48655103818).jpg|150px|thumb|left|Gilmour (right) playing for Chelsea with teammate [[C\u00e9sar Azpilicueta]]]]\nNewly-appointed Chelsea manager [[Frank Lampard]] gave Gilmour his senior debut on 10 July 2019, in a pre-season friendly against [[Bohemian F.C.|Bohemians]] in Dublin.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bryce |first1=Liam |title=Billy Gilmour makes Chelsea debut as ex-Rangers prospect given the nod |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/billy-gilmour-makes-chelsea-debut-17846062 |accessdate=10 July 2019 |work=Daily Record |date=10 July 2019 |location=Glasgow}}</ref> His first appearance in a competitive matchday squad for the first team came in the [[2019 UEFA Super Cup]] against [[Liverpool FC|Liverpool]], when he was an unused substitute.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\nHe made his Premier League debut on 31 August against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], coming on in the 84th minute for [[Tammy Abraham]]. He made his full debut on 25 September, playing the full 90 minutes in a 7\u20131 [[EFL Cup]] win against [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49736854|title=Chelsea 7\u20131 Grimsby Town: Reece James impresses on debut|date=2019-09-25|access-date=2019-09-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> Gilmour was added to the Chelsea first-team squad on a permanent basis in February 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51466510 |title=Billy Gilmour: Chelsea midfielder now with first team full time |website=BBC Sport |publisher= |date=11 February 2020 |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> He was widely praised for his performance in a 2&ndash;0 win against Liverpool in an [[FA Cup]] tie on 3 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51728140 |title=Billy Gilmour: Chelsea's Scottish teenager 'incredible' in Liverpool win |first=Thomas |last=Duncan |website=BBC Sport |date=4 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nGilmour was selected in the [[Scotland national under-16 football team|Scotland under-16 squad]] for the 2016 [[Victory Shield]] tournament.<ref>{{cite news |title=Under-16 Victory Shield squad announced |url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_fa_news.cfm?page=1848&newsID=16580 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |publisher=Scottish FA |date=20 October 2016 |language=en}}</ref> He made his [[Scotland national under-17 football team|Scotland under-17]] debut against [[Italy national under-17 football team|Italy]] in August 2017, and scored his first international goal in a 2\u20131 defeat against [[England national under-17 football team|England]] two days later.<ref>{{cite news |title=Billy Gilmour \u2013 U17 squad matches |url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=1848&playerID=224107&squadID=13 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |publisher=Scottish FA}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ex-Rangers wonderkid Billy Gilmour scores as Scotland U17s are beaten by England |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-match-reports/former-rangers-youngster-billy-gilmour-11022741 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=Daily Record |date=20 August 2017 |location=Glasgow}}</ref>\n\nHe made his [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21]] debut in the [[2018 Toulon Tournament]], in a 1\u20130 win against [[France national under-21 football team|France]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/scotland-stun-hosts-france-to-record-toulon-win/?rid=13925 |title=Scotland stun hosts France to record Toulon win |publisher=Scottish Football Association |date=30 May 2018 |accessdate=31 May 2018}}</ref> going on to win the \"Revelation of the Tournament\" after helping Scotland to a fourth-placed finish.<ref>{{cite news |title=Individual awards for Billy Gilmour and Michael Johnston seal successful Toulon trip |url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/individual-awards-for-billy-gilmour-and-michael-johnston-seal-successful-toulon-trip/?rid=14258 |accessdate=10 June 2018 |publisher=Scottish Football Association |date=10 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 8 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|[[FA Cup|National Cup]]\n!colspan=2|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=2|[[UEFA competitions#For clubs|Europe]]\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]\n|[[2019\u201320 Chelsea F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref name=\"2019-20\">[https://us.soccerway.com/players/billy-gilmour/486637/matches/ \"Games played by Billy Gilmour in 2019/2020\"]. ''Soccerbase.'' Centurycomm. Retrieved 08 March 2020.</ref>\n|[[Premier League]]\n|3||0||2||0||2||0||0||0|| colspan=\"2\" |\u2014||7||0\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total\n!3||0||2||0||2||0||0||0||0||0||7||0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Chelsea Youth'''\n*[[Professional Development League|U18 Premier League]]: [http://thechels.info/wiki/2017-18_Premier_Academy_League 2017\u201318]<ref name=\"Billy Gilmour\"></ref>\n*[[FA Youth Cup]]: [[2017\u201318 FA Youth Cup|2017\u201318]]<ref name=\"Billy Gilmour\">{{cite web|url=http://thechels.info/wiki/Billy_Gilmour|title=Billy Gilmour |website=thechels.info |accessdate=31 August 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Sports links}}\n*{{Soccerbase|114323|Billy Gilmour}}\n*[https://twitter.com/billygilmourrr?lang=en Billy Gilmour on Twitter]\n*[http://www.uefa.com/uefayouthleague/season=2018/clubs/player=250107117/index.html Billy Gilmour] profile at UEFA Youth League\n*[https://www.chelseafc.com/en/teams/academy/billy-gilmour Billy Gilmour] profile at Chelsea F.C.\n\n{{Chelsea F.C. squad}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gilmour, Billy}}\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Grange Academy, Kilmarnock]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from North Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chelsea F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scotland youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland under-21 international footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{about|the Scottish footballer|the former Canadian ice hockey player|Billy Gilmour (ice hockey)}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Billy Gilmour\n| image = File:Chelsea 7 Grimsby 1 (48798190337).jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = Gilmour in 2019\n| fullname = Billy Clifford Gilmour<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/612828 |title=Updated squads for 2017/18 Premier League confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=2 February 2018 |accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2001|6|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| height = {{convert|1.68|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/billy-gilmour-inside-the-rise-of-chelsea-and-scotlands-new/1wjg5pl8jnznw17twvg3xbs7xq |title=Billy Gilmour: Inside the rise of Chelsea and Scotland's 'new Modric' |publisher=Goal |accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref>\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]\n| clubnumber = 47\n| youthyears1 = 2009\u20132017\n| youthclubs1 = [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]]\n| youthyears2 = 2017\u2013\n| youthclubs2 = [[Chelsea F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Chelsea]]\n| years1 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]\n| caps1 = 3\n| goals1 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2015\u20132016\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national under-16 football team|Scotland U15]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2016\u20132017\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scotland national under-16 football team|Scotland U16]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2017\u20132018\n| nationalteam3 = [[Scotland national under-17 football team|Scotland U17]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 7\n| nationalgoals3 = 2\n| nationalyears4 = 2017\u20132019\n| nationalteam4 = [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland U19]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 7\n| nationalgoals4 = 3\n| nationalyears5 = 2018\u2013\n| nationalteam5 = [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 12\n| nationalgoals5 = 1\n| club-update =  15:49, 8 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 15 November 2019\n}}\n'''Billy Clifford Gilmour''' (born 11 June 2001) is a Scottish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Premier League]] club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2020/02/11/billy-gilmour-on-moving-up-to-the-senior-squad-permanently|title=Billy Gilmour on moving up to the senior squad permanently {{!}} Official Site {{!}} Chelsea Football Club|website=ChelseaFC|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> He was previously with [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], where he developed through the club's [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|academy]] and trained with the first team squad at the age of 15. He joined Chelsea in 2017 after turning down a professional contract with Rangers. He has represented Scotland at [[Scotland national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[Scotland national under-17 football team|under-17]] and [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21]] levels.\n\n==Early life==\nGilmour was born on 11 June 2001 in [[Glasgow]] and resided in [[Ardrossan]], [[North Ayrshire]]. His father served with the Royal Navy and played [[Scottish Junior Football Association|junior football]] for [[Ardrossan Winton Rovers F.C.|Ardrossan Winton Rovers]]. Gilmour attended Stanley Primary School in Ardrossan and [[Grange Academy, Kilmarnock|Grange Academy]] in [[Kilmarnock]], where he was part of the [[Scottish Football Association]] (SFA) Performance School programme.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/scotland-and-chelseas-billy-gilmour-ahead-of-plan-but-remains-rooted-in-reality-zpvgw38cd |title=Scotland and Chelsea\u2019s Billy Gilmour \u2018ahead of plan\u2019 but remains rooted in reality |first=Mark |last=Walker |newspaper=The Times |publisher= |date=16 October 2019 |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Rangers===\nGilmour developed his career as part of [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers Academy]]. His progress saw him fast-tracked towards the first team, making his debut for the under-20 development team in December 2016 at the age of 15 and being invited to train with the first team squad the following month by manager [[Mark Warburton]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bairner |first1=Robin |title=Meet Rangers wonderkid Billy Gilmour: The starlet Chelsea have beaten Arsenal and Manchester United to |url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/meet-rangers-wonderkid-billy-gilmour-the-starlet-chelsea/a29cvw6htgq312yqnx019a5d1 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=Goal.com |date=9 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Billy Gilmour shares his delight after training with Rangers first team squad |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/rangers-youngster-billy-gilmour-shares-9687629 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=Daily Record |date=25 January 2017 |location=Glasgow}}</ref> Gilmour was given a squad number and, following Warburton's departure from the club, was twice included in the provisional squad for [[Scottish Cup]] matches by [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] caretaker manager [[Graeme Murty]].<ref>https://www.glasgowtimes.co.uk/sport/15198720.graeme-murty-hopes-rangers-can-fend-off-interest-from-chelsea-in-midfield-star-billy-gilmour/</ref>\n\nThe next Rangers manager, [[Pedro Caixinha]], described Gilmour as a player with a \"bright future\" and held talks with the player's family in an attempt to persuade him to stay with the club.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Newport |first1=Andy |title=Caixinha reveals he's met Billy Gilmour's parents in bid to keep ace at Rangers |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/rangers-boss-pedro-caixinha-reveals-10127591 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=Daily Record |date=30 March 2017 |location=Glasgow}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Gilmour set for Chelsea move \u2013 unless Gers succeed in last-ditch talks |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/transfers/rangers-hold-talks-with-billy-gilmour-chelsea-transfer-wonderkid-a7658371.html |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=The Independent |date=30 March 2017 |location=London}}</ref> Rangers, however, announced in May 2017 that they had reached an agreement for Gilmour to join [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] for a \"significant fee\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Rangers: Youth prospect Billy Gilmour opts for summer switch to Chelsea |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39858879 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=BBC Sport |date=9 May 2017}}</ref> Reports suggested that Chelsea would pay an initial development fee of around \u00a3500,000, with potential further payments dependent on his progress.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yew |first1=Oliver |title=Who is Chelsea new-boy Billy Gilmour? |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11096/10871035/who-is-chelsea-new-boy-billy-gilmour |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=Sky Sports |date=10 May 2017 |language=en}}</ref> SFA Performance Director [[Malky Mackay]] had advised Gilmour and his family that he should stay at Rangers, as he would have had more chance of gaining first team experience. Mackay said, \"I really hope he goes out on loan quickly to someone and keeps progressing\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Malky Mackay: 'Billy Gilmour could have emulated Barry Ferguson at Rangers' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40927422 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=BBC Sport |date=14 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Chelsea===\nGilmour became officially contracted to Chelsea in July 2017, following his 16th birthday.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Amako |first1=Uche |title=Billy Gilmour signs Chelsea contract two months after agreeing to leave Rangers |url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/824767/Chelsea-Transfer-News-Billy-Gilmour-professional-contract-Rangers-gossip-rumours |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=Daily Express |date=4 July 2017 |location=London}}</ref> He joined the club's [[Chelsea F.C. Under-23s and Academy|under-18 squad]], making a goalscoring debut in an [[Professional Development League#Under-18 level|Under-18 Premier League]] match against [[Arsenal F.C. Academy|Arsenal]] during September 2017,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Forbes |first1=Craig |title=Billy Gilmour impresses in goalscoring Chelsea debut |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/billy-gilmour-impresses-in-goalscoring-chelsea-debut-1-4556555 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=The Scotsman |date=11 September 2017 |location=Edinburgh}}</ref> and going on to score in each of his first three appearances.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McDougall |first1=Mark |title=Former Rangers kid Billy Gilmour scores third goal in three games for Chelsea |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/former-rangers-kid-billy-gilmour-11264590 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=Daily Record |date=30 September 2017 |location=Glasgow}}</ref> In July 2018, after turning 17, Gilmour signed his first professional contract with Chelsea.<ref>{{cite news |title=Billy Gilmour: Former Rangers youth signs first professional contract at Chelsea |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44723798 |accessdate=7 August 2018 |work=BBC Sport |date=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Chelsea 2 Sheffield Utd 2 (48655103818).jpg|150px|thumb|left|Gilmour (right) playing for Chelsea with teammate [[C\u00e9sar Azpilicueta]]]]\nNewly-appointed Chelsea manager [[Frank Lampard]] gave Gilmour his senior debut on 10 July 2019, in a pre-season friendly against [[Bohemian F.C.|Bohemians]] in Dublin.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bryce |first1=Liam |title=Billy Gilmour makes Chelsea debut as ex-Rangers prospect given the nod |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/billy-gilmour-makes-chelsea-debut-17846062 |accessdate=10 July 2019 |work=Daily Record |date=10 July 2019 |location=Glasgow}}</ref> His first appearance in a competitive matchday squad for the first team came in the [[2019 UEFA Super Cup]] against [[Liverpool FC|Liverpool]], when he was an unused substitute.{{fact|date=November 2019}}\n\nHe made his Premier League debut on 31 August against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], coming on in the 84th minute for [[Tammy Abraham]]. He made his full debut on 25 September, playing the full 90 minutes in a 7\u20131 [[EFL Cup]] win against [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49736854|title=Chelsea 7\u20131 Grimsby Town: Reece James impresses on debut|date=2019-09-25|access-date=2019-09-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> Gilmour was added to the Chelsea first-team squad on a permanent basis in February 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51466510 |title=Billy Gilmour: Chelsea midfielder now with first team full time |website=BBC Sport |publisher= |date=11 February 2020 |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> He was widely praised for his performance in a 2&ndash;0 win against Liverpool in an [[FA Cup]] tie on 3 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51728140 |title=Billy Gilmour: Chelsea's Scottish teenager 'incredible' in Liverpool win |first=Thomas |last=Duncan |website=BBC Sport |date=4 March 2020 |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nGilmour was selected in the [[Scotland national under-16 football team|Scotland under-16 squad]] for the 2016 [[Victory Shield]] tournament.<ref>{{cite news |title=Under-16 Victory Shield squad announced |url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_fa_news.cfm?page=1848&newsID=16580 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |publisher=Scottish FA |date=20 October 2016 |language=en}}</ref> He made his [[Scotland national under-17 football team|Scotland under-17]] debut against [[Italy national under-17 football team|Italy]] in August 2017, and scored his first international goal in a 2\u20131 defeat against [[England national under-17 football team|England]] two days later.<ref>{{cite news |title=Billy Gilmour \u2013 U17 squad matches |url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=1848&playerID=224107&squadID=13 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |publisher=Scottish FA}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ex-Rangers wonderkid Billy Gilmour scores as Scotland U17s are beaten by England |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-match-reports/former-rangers-youngster-billy-gilmour-11022741 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |work=Daily Record |date=20 August 2017 |location=Glasgow}}</ref>\n\nHe made his [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21]] debut in the [[2018 Toulon Tournament]], in a 1\u20130 win against [[France national under-21 football team|France]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/scotland-stun-hosts-france-to-record-toulon-win/?rid=13925 |title=Scotland stun hosts France to record Toulon win |publisher=Scottish Football Association |date=30 May 2018 |accessdate=31 May 2018}}</ref> going on to win the \"Revelation of the Tournament\" after helping Scotland to a fourth-placed finish.<ref>{{cite news |title=Individual awards for Billy Gilmour and Michael Johnston seal successful Toulon trip |url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/individual-awards-for-billy-gilmour-and-michael-johnston-seal-successful-toulon-trip/?rid=14258 |accessdate=10 June 2018 |publisher=Scottish Football Association |date=10 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 8 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|[[FA Cup|National Cup]]\n!colspan=2|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=2|[[UEFA competitions#For clubs|Europe]]\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]\n|[[2019\u201320 Chelsea F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref name=\"2019-20\">[https://us.soccerway.com/players/billy-gilmour/486637/matches/ \"Games played by Billy Gilmour in 2019/2020\"]. ''Soccerbase.'' Centurycomm. Retrieved 08 March 2020.</ref>\n|[[Premier League]]\n|3||0||2||0||2||0||0||0|| colspan=\"2\" |\u2014||7||0\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total\n!3||0||2||0||2||0||0||0||0||0||7||0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Chelsea Youth'''\n*[[Professional Development League|U18 Premier League]]: [http://thechels.info/wiki/2017-18_Premier_Academy_League 2017\u201318]<ref name=\"Billy Gilmour\"></ref>\n*[[FA Youth Cup]]: [[2017\u201318 FA Youth Cup|2017\u201318]]<ref name=\"Billy Gilmour\">{{cite web|url=http://thechels.info/wiki/Billy_Gilmour|title=Billy Gilmour |website=thechels.info |accessdate=31 August 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Sports links}}\n*{{Soccerbase|114323|Billy Gilmour}}\n*[https://twitter.com/billygilmourrr?lang=en Billy Gilmour on Twitter]\n*[http://www.uefa.com/uefayouthleague/season=2018/clubs/player=250107117/index.html Billy Gilmour] profile at UEFA Youth League\n*[https://www.chelseafc.com/en/teams/academy/billy-gilmour Billy Gilmour] profile at Chelsea F.C.\n\n{{Chelsea F.C. squad}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gilmour, Billy}}\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Grange Academy, Kilmarnock]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from North Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chelsea F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scotland youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland under-21 international footballers]]\n", "name_user": "82.20.254.14", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Gilmour_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Baron Raimund von Stillfried", "text_new": "[[File:Baron Stillfried Verso 1883.jpg|thumb|upright]]\n'''Baron Raimund von Stillfried''', also known as '''Baron Raimund von Stillfried-Rathenitz''' (6 August 1839, in [[Komotau]] &nbsp;\u2013  12 August 1911, in [[Vienna]]), was an [[Austria]]n [[photographer]].\n\n== Biography ==\nHe was son of [[Baron]] (''Freiherr'') August Wilhelm Stillfried von Rathenitz (d. 1806) and [[Countess]] Maria Anna Johanna Theresia Walburge [[Clam-Martinitz]] (1802\u20131874).\n\nAfter leaving his military career, Stillfried moved to [[Yokohama]], Japan and opened a [[photographic studio]] called ''Stillfried & Co.'' which operated until 1875. In 1875, Stillfried formed a partnership with [[Hermann Andersen]] and the studio was renamed, ''[[Stillfried & Andersen]]'' (also known as the ''Japan Photographic Association''). This studio operated until 1885. In 1877, ''Stillfried & Andersen'' bought the studio and stock of [[Felice Beato]]. In the late 1870s, Stillfried visited and photographed in [[Dalmatia]], [[Bosnia (region)|Bosnia]], and [[Greece]]. In addition to his own photographic endeavours, Stillfried trained many Japanese photographers. In 1886, Stillfried sold the majority of his stock to his prot\u00e9g\u00e9, the Japanese photographer [[Kusakabe Kimbei]], he then left Japan. \n\nHe left Japan forever in 1881. After travelling to [[Vladivostock]], [[Hong Kong]] and [[Bangkok]], he eventually settled in Vienna in 1883.<ref>https://www.1843magazine.com/culture/the-daily/postcards-from-a-pictureperfect-japan</ref> He also received an [[Imperial and Royal Warrant of Appointment]] as photographer (''k.u.k. Hof-Photograph''). \n\n==Selected works==\n<gallery>\nFile:Hodo Falls at Nikko by Raimund von Stillfried.jpg\nFile:Japanese woman on her head by Baron von Stillfried.jpg\nFile:Portrait of an Admiral by Baron von Stillfried.jpg\nFile:Stillfried - Samurai.jpg\nFile:Two monks with rosary by Raimund von Stillfried.jpg\nFile:Japanese Tattoo by Kimbei or Stillfried.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n* [http://www.artnet.com/artist/552570/raimund-von-baron-stillfried.html Artnet, s.v. \"Raimund von (Baron) Stillfried\"]. Accessed 11 December 2006.\n* [https://www.cca.qc.ca/fr/recherche?page=0&query=+Raimund+von+Stillfried&_=1586467391183 Canadian Centre for Architecture; Collections Online, s.v. \"Baron Raimund von Stillfried\"]. Accessed 09 April 2020.\n*Gartlan, Luke.  ''A Career of Japan: Baron Raimund von Stillfried and Early Yokohama Photography''.  Brill: Photography in Asia, Vol 1. Leiden and Boston: Brill, 2016, 384 pp., 163 illus. {{ISBN|978-90-04-28932-1}}.\n* [http://oldphoto.lb.nagasaki-u.ac.jp/en/list.php?req=1&target=Stillfried Nagasaki University Library; Japanese Old Photographs in Bakumatsu-Meiji Period, s.v. \"Stillfried\"]. Accessed 12 February 2007.\n* [http://www.getty.edu/vow/ULANFullDisplay?find=Stillfried%2C+Raimund%2C+Baron+von&role=&nation=&prev_page=1&subjectid=5000371574 Union List of Artists Names, s.v. \"Stillfried-Rathenitz, Raimund von, Baron\"]. Accessed 11 December 2006.\n\n;Specific\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Raimund von Stillfried}}\n*[http://collections.si.edu/search/results.htm?tag.cstype=all&q=stillfried%2C+raimund&start=20 Stillfried collection] at [[Smithsonian Institution]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stillfried, Raimund, Baron von}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1911 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Austrian people]]\n[[Category:19th-century photographers]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:Austrian people of German Bohemian descent]]\n[[Category:Austrian photographers]]\n[[Category:Barons of Austria]]\n[[Category:People from Chomutov]]\n[[Category:Photography in Greece]]\n[[Category:Photography in Japan]]\n[[Category:Pioneers of photography]]\n[[Category:Purveyors to the Imperial and Royal Court]]\n\n\n{{Austria-artist-stub}}\n{{Austria-hist-stub}}\n{{Europe-photographer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Baron Stillfried Verso 1883.jpg|thumb|upright]]\n'''Baron Raimund von Stillfried''', also known as '''Baron Raimund von Stillfried-Rathenitz''' (6 August 1839, in [[Komotau]] &nbsp;\u2013  12 August 1911, in [[Vienna]]), was an [[Austria]]n [[photographer]].\n\n== Biography ==\nHe was son of [[Baron]] (''Freiherr'') August Wilhelm Stillfried von Rathenitz (d. 1806) and [[Countess]] Maria Anna Johanna Theresia Walburge [[Clam-Martinitz]] (1802\u20131874).\n\nAfter leaving his military career, Stillfried moved to [[Yokohama]], Japan and opened a [[photographic studio]] called ''Stillfried & Co.'' which operated until 1875. In 1875, Stillfried formed a partnership with [[Hermann Andersen]] and the studio was renamed, ''[[Stillfried & Andersen]]'' (also known as the ''Japan Photographic Association''). This studio operated until 1885. In 1877, ''Stillfried & Andersen'' bought the studio and stock of [[Felice Beato]]. In the late 1870s, Stillfried visited and photographed in [[Dalmatia]], [[Bosnia (region)|Bosnia]], and [[Greece]]. In addition to his own photographic endeavours, Stillfried trained many Japanese photographers. In 1886, Stillfried sold the majority of his stock to his prot\u00e9g\u00e9, the Japanese photographer [[Kusakabe Kimbei]], he then left Japan. \n\nHe left Japan forever in 1881. After travelling to [[Vladivostock]], [[Hong Kong]] and [[Bangkok]], he eventually settled in Vienna in 1883.<ref>https://www.1843magazine.com/culture/the-daily/postcards-from-a-pictureperfect-japan</ref> He also received an [[Imperial and Royal Warrant of Appointment]] as photographer (''k.u.k. Hof-Photograph''). \n\n==Selected works==\n<gallery>\nFile:Hodo Falls at Nikko by Raimund von Stillfried.jpg\nFile:Japanese woman on her head by Baron von Stillfried.jpg\nFile:Portrait of an Admiral by Baron von Stillfried.jpg\nFile:Stillfried - Samurai.jpg\nFile:Two monks with rosary by Raimund von Stillfried.jpg\nFile:Japanese Tattoo by Kimbei or Stillfried.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n* [http://www.artnet.com/artist/552570/raimund-von-baron-stillfried.html Artnet, s.v. \"Raimund von (Baron) Stillfried\"]. Accessed 11 December 2006.\n* [http://cel.cca.qc.ca/bs.aspx?langID=1#s=Baron%20Raimund%20von%20Stillfried&p=1&a=kw&nr=1&nq=1 Canadian Centre for Architecture; Collections Online, s.v. \"Baron Raimund von Stillfried\"]. Accessed 14 April 2011.\n*Gartlan, Luke.  ''A Career of Japan: Baron Raimund von Stillfried and Early Yokohama Photography''.  Brill: Photography in Asia, Vol 1. Leiden and Boston: Brill, 2016, 384 pp., 163 illus. {{ISBN|978-90-04-28932-1}}.\n* [http://oldphoto.lb.nagasaki-u.ac.jp/en/list.php?req=1&target=Stillfried Nagasaki University Library; Japanese Old Photographs in Bakumatsu-Meiji Period, s.v. \"Stillfried\"]. Accessed 12 February 2007.\n* [http://www.getty.edu/vow/ULANFullDisplay?find=Stillfried%2C+Raimund%2C+Baron+von&role=&nation=&prev_page=1&subjectid=5000371574 Union List of Artists Names, s.v. \"Stillfried-Rathenitz, Raimund von, Baron\"]. Accessed 11 December 2006.\n\n;Specific\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Raimund von Stillfried}}\n*[http://collections.si.edu/search/results.htm?tag.cstype=all&q=stillfried%2C+raimund&start=20 Stillfried collection] at [[Smithsonian Institution]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stillfried, Raimund, Baron von}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1911 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Austrian people]]\n[[Category:19th-century photographers]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:Austrian people of German Bohemian descent]]\n[[Category:Austrian photographers]]\n[[Category:Barons of Austria]]\n[[Category:People from Chomutov]]\n[[Category:Photography in Greece]]\n[[Category:Photography in Japan]]\n[[Category:Pioneers of photography]]\n[[Category:Purveyors to the Imperial and Royal Court]]\n\n\n{{Austria-artist-stub}}\n{{Austria-hist-stub}}\n{{Europe-photographer-stub}}\n", "name