{"title_page": "Silesaurus", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| name = ''Silesaurus''\n| display_parents = 3\n| taxon = Silesaurus\n| authority = [[Jerzy Dzik|Dzik]], [[2003 in paleontology|2003]]\n| fossil_range = [[Late Triassic]], {{fossilrange|230}}\n| image = Silesaurus szkielet.JPG\n| image_caption = Reconstructed skeleton\n| subdivision_ranks = [[Species]]\n| subdivision =\n* '''''S. opolensis''''' <small>Dzik, 2003 ([[Type species|type]])</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Silesaurus''''' is a [[genus]] of [[Silesauridae|silesaurid]] [[dinosauriformes|dinosauriform]] from the [[Late Triassic]], approximately 230&nbsp;million years ago in the [[Carnian]] [[faunal stage]] of what is now [[Poland]]. Fossilized remains of ''Silesaurus'' have been found in the [[Keuper Claystone]] in [[Krasiej\u00f3w]] near [[Opole]], [[Silesia]], Poland, which is also the origin of its name. The [[type species]], ''Silesaurus opolensis'', was described by [[Jerzy Dzik]] in 2003. It is known from some 20 skeletons, making it one of the best-represented of the early dinosauriformes.<ref name=\"dzik03\" />\n\n==Description==\n[[Image:Silesaurus opolensis.jpg|thumb|left|Size compared to a human]] \n''Silesaurus'' measured approximately {{convert|2.3|m|ft|abbr=off|sp=us}} in length. Lightly built, it was probably a fast and agile animal with an active lifestyle. The snout was narrow with forward-pointing nostrils, and the large orbits likely provided ''Silesaurus'' with acute vision.\n\nInitially, ''Silesaurus'' was thought to be strictly [[Herbivore|herbivorous]], but later research on [[coprolite]] contents indicates that it may have been insectivorous.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal |author1=Martin Qvarnstr\u00f6m |author2=Joel Vikberg Wernstr\u00f6m |author3=Rafa\u0142 Piechowski |author4=Mateusz Ta\u0142anda |author5=Per E. Ahlberg |author6=Grzegorz Nied\u017awiedzki |year=2019 |title=Beetle-bearing coprolites possibly reveal the diet of a Late Triassic dinosauriform |journal=Royal Society Open Science |volume=6 |issue=3 |pages=Article ID 181042 |doi=10.1098/rsos.181042 |pmc=6458417 |pmid=31031991}}</ref> The teeth of the animal were small, conical, and serrated, and were distributed irregularly in its jaws. The tip of the [[Mandible#In other vertebrates|dentary]] had no teeth, and evidence suggests that it was  covered by a keratinous [[beak]].<ref name=dzik03/>\n\n==Classification==\n[[File:Silesaurus1.jpg|thumb|''S. opolensis'' restored without feather-like filaments]] \nScientists think that ''Silesaurus'' was not a [[dinosaur]], but rather a [[dinosauriform]]. Dinosaurian features lacking in ''Silesaurus'' include an enlarged deltopectoral crest (a muscle attachment on the [[humerus]]), and [[epipophyses]] (enlarged [[tendon]] attachment above the [[Articular processes|postzygapophysis]]) on the [[cervical vertebrae]].\n\nHowever, ''Silesaurus'' has some dinosaurian characteristics as well:\n* a [[Ilium (bone)#In dinosaurs|brevis shelf]] (a bone surface on the [[Ilium (bone)|ilium]] that functions as an attachment site for tail muscles)\n* [[ischium]] with a slender shaft\n* [[femur]] with a reduced tuberosity that borders the [[ligament]] of the [[femoral head]]\n* a prominent [[lesser trochanter]]\n* an overlap of the ascending process of the [[talus bone|astragalus]] with the [[tibia]]\n* a concave proximal articular surface for the reception of the distal end of the [[fibula]] on the [[calcaneum]]\n[[File:Silesaurus opolensis by Szymon G\u00f3rnicki.jpg|thumb|Silesaurus opolensis by Szymon G\u00f3rnicki]]\nAs a result, alternative hypotheses place ''Silesaurus'' at or near the base of the [[ornithischia]]n dinosaurs. Other scientists propose a basal link between the basal [[sauropodomorph]]s and ornithischians.<ref name=\"dzik03\">{{cite journal|author=Dzik J|first=|date=|year=2003|title=A beaked herbivorous archosaur with dinosaur affinities from the early Late Triassic of Poland|url=http://www.keuper.us.edu.pl/02_Keuper-literature/Dzik%202003JVP.pdf|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume=23|issue=3|pages=556\u2013574|doi=10.1671/a1097|via=}}</ref>\n\nSystematic position after [[Sterling Nesbitt|Nesbitt]] (2011):<ref name=\"Nesbitt11\">{{cite journal|last=Nesbitt|first=Sterling J.|date=2011|title=The Early Evolution of Archosaurs: Relationships and the Origin of Major Clades|url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/dspace/bitstream/2246/6112/1/B352.pdf|journal=[[Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History]]|volume=352|pages=1\u2013292|doi=10.1206/352.1|hdl=2246/6112}}</ref>\n\n{{clade| style=font-size:90%;line-height:85%\n|label1=[[Ornithodira]]&nbsp;  \n|1={{clade\n   |label1=&nbsp;[[Pterosauromorpha]]&nbsp;\n   |1={{clade\n      |1=''[[Scleromochlus]]''\n      |2=[[Pterosauria]]}} \n   |label2=&nbsp;[[Dinosauromorpha]]&nbsp;\n   |2={{clade\n      |label1=&nbsp;[[Lagerpetonidae]]&nbsp;\n      |1={{Clade\n         |1=''[[Lagerpeton]]''\n         |2=''[[Dromomeron]]''\n}}\n      |label2=&nbsp;[[Dinosauriformes]]&nbsp;\n      |2={{clade\n         |1=''[[Marasuchus]]''\n         |2={{Clade\n            |label1=&nbsp;[[Silesauridae]]&nbsp;\n            |1={{clade\n               |1=''[[Lewisuchus]]''/''[[Pseudolagosuchus]]''\n               |2={{clade\n                  |1=''[[Asilisaurus]]''\n                  |2={{clade\n                     |1=''[[Eucoelophysis]]''\n                     |2={{clade\n                        |1=''[[Sacisaurus]]''\n                        |2='''''Silesaurus'''''\n}} }} }} }} \n            |label2=&nbsp;[[Dinosauria]]&nbsp;\n            |2={{clade\n                     |label1=&nbsp;[[Saurischia]]&nbsp;\n                     |1={{clade\n                        |1=[[Theropoda]]\n                        |2=[[Sauropodomorpha]]}}\n                     |2=[[Ornithischia]]\n}} }} }} }} }} }}\n\n== Palaeobiology ==\n[[Image:MEPAN silezaur rauizuch.jpg|thumb|''Silesaurus opolensis'' and ''[[Polonosuchus silesiacus]]'' models in Poland]] \nBeetle [[Elytron|elytra]] and other arthropod remains have been found in [[Coprolite|coprolites]]  which have been recovered in the vicinity of ''Silesaurus'' fossil occurrences. The size and shape of the coprolites combined with the peculiar beaked architecture of ''Silesaurus'''s skull may suggest that this animal produced the coprolites and that it could have been wholly or partially insectivorous. It might have fed on insects and other small arthropods by [[pecking]], using the beak-like tip of the snout to accurately target prey in a way similar to modern birds. If so, this would represent the earliest known occurrence of this highly derived mode of feeding and have implications for the understanding of  the evolutionary adaptations that would eventually lead up to the [[Dinosaur#Origins_and_early_evolution|origin of dinosaurs]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Palaeoecology==\n''Silesaurus'' lived in a subtropical environment similar to the modern [[Mediterranean basin]] with alternating summer monsoons and dry winters. The animal shared its environment of extensive swamplands and [[Fern|fern]] vegetation with a wealth of [[Invertebrate|invertebrates]] as well as [[Lungfish|dipnoan]] and ganoid fishes, [[Temnospondyli|temnospondyls]], [[Phytosaur|phytosaurs]] and early [[Pterosaur|pterosaurs]].<ref>John W. M. Jagt, Grzegorz Hebda, S\u0142awomir Mitrus, Elena Jagt-Yazykova, Adam Bodzioch, Dorota Konietzko-Meier, Klaudia Kardyna\u0142, Kamil Gruntmejer. 2015. Field Guide, Conference Paper, European Association of Vertebrate Palaeontologists XIII Annual Meeting.</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ornithodira|D.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2322754}}\n\n[[Category:Silesaurids]]\n[[Category:Opole County]]\n[[Category:Late Triassic dinosauriforms]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 2003]]\n[[Category:Late Triassic reptiles of Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| name = ''Silesaurus''\n| display_parents = 3\n| taxon = Silesaurus\n| authority = [[Jerzy Dzik|Dzik]], [[2003 in paleontology|2003]]\n| fossil_range = [[Late Triassic]], {{fossilrange|230}}\n| image = Silesaurus szkielet.JPG\n| image_caption = Reconstructed skeleton\n| subdivision_ranks = [[Species]]\n| subdivision =\n* '''''S. opolensis''''' <small>Dzik, 2003 ([[Type species|type]])</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Silesaurus''''' is a [[genus]] of [[Silesauridae|silesaurid]] [[dinosauriformes|dinosauriform]] from the [[Late Triassic]], approximately 230&nbsp;million years ago in the [[Carnian]] [[faunal stage]] of what is now [[Poland]]. Fossilized remains of ''Silesaurus'' have been found in the [[Keuper Claystone]] in [[Krasiej\u00f3w]] near [[Opole]], [[Silesia]], Poland, which is also the origin of its name. The [[type species]], ''Silesaurus opolensis'', was described by [[Jerzy Dzik]] in 2003. It is known from some 20 skeletons, making it one of the best-represented of the early dinosauriformes.<ref name=\"dzik03\" />\n\n==Description==\n[[Image:Silesaurus opolensis.jpg|thumb|left|Size compared to a human]] \n''Silesaurus'' measured approximately {{convert|2.3|m|ft|abbr=off|sp=us}} in length. Lightly built, it was probably a fast and agile animal with an active lifestyle. The snout was narrow with forward-pointing nostrils, and the large orbits likely provided ''Silesaurus'' with acute vision.\n\nInitially, ''Silesaurus'' was thought to be strictly [[Herbivore|herbivorous]], but later research on [[coprolite]] contents indicates that it may have been insectivorous.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal |author1=Martin Qvarnstr\u00f6m |author2=Joel Vikberg Wernstr\u00f6m |author3=Rafa\u0142 Piechowski |author4=Mateusz Ta\u0142anda |author5=Per E. Ahlberg |author6=Grzegorz Nied\u017awiedzki |year=2019 |title=Beetle-bearing coprolites possibly reveal the diet of a Late Triassic dinosauriform |journal=Royal Society Open Science |volume=6 |issue=3 |pages=Article ID 181042 |doi=10.1098/rsos.181042 |pmc=6458417 |pmid=31031991}}</ref> The teeth of the animal were small, conical, and serrated, and were distributed irregularly in its jaws. The tip of the [[Mandible#In other vertebrates|dentary]] had no teeth, and evidence suggests that it was  covered by a keratinous [[beak]].<ref name=dzik03/>\n\n==Classification==\n[[File:Silesaurus1.jpg|thumb|''S. opolensis'' restored without feather-like filaments]] \nScientists think that ''Silesaurus'' was not a [[dinosaur]], but rather a [[dinosauriform]]. Dinosaurian features lacking in ''Silesaurus'' include an enlarged deltopectoral crest (a muscle attachment on the [[humerus]]), and [[epipophyses]] (enlarged [[tendon]] attachment above the [[Articular processes|postzygapophysis]]) on the [[cervical vertebrae]].\n\nHowever, ''Silesaurus'' has some dinosaurian characteristics as well:\n* a [[Ilium (bone)#In dinosaurs|brevis shelf]] (a bone surface on the [[Ilium (bone)|ilium]] that functions as an attachment site for tail muscles)\n* [[ischium]] with a slender shaft\n* [[femur]] with a reduced tuberosity that borders the [[ligament]] of the [[femoral head]]\n* a prominent [[lesser trochanter]]\n* an overlap of the ascending process of the [[talus bone|astragalus]] with the [[tibia]]\n* a concave proximal articular surface for the reception of the distal end of the [[fibula]] on the [[calcaneum]]\n\nAs a result, alternative hypotheses place ''Silesaurus'' at or near the base of the [[ornithischia]]n dinosaurs. Other scientists propose a basal link between the basal [[sauropodomorph]]s and ornithischians.<ref name=\"dzik03\">{{cite journal|author=Dzik J|first=|date=|year=2003|title=A beaked herbivorous archosaur with dinosaur affinities from the early Late Triassic of Poland|url=http://www.keuper.us.edu.pl/02_Keuper-literature/Dzik%202003JVP.pdf|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume=23|issue=3|pages=556\u2013574|doi=10.1671/a1097|via=}}</ref>\n\nSystematic position after [[Sterling Nesbitt|Nesbitt]] (2011):<ref name=\"Nesbitt11\">{{cite journal|last=Nesbitt|first=Sterling J.|date=2011|title=The Early Evolution of Archosaurs: Relationships and the Origin of Major Clades|url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/dspace/bitstream/2246/6112/1/B352.pdf|journal=[[Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History]]|volume=352|pages=1\u2013292|doi=10.1206/352.1|hdl=2246/6112}}</ref>\n\n{{clade| style=font-size:90%;line-height:85%\n|label1=[[Ornithodira]]&nbsp;  \n|1={{clade\n   |label1=&nbsp;[[Pterosauromorpha]]&nbsp;\n   |1={{clade\n      |1=''[[Scleromochlus]]''\n      |2=[[Pterosauria]]}} \n   |label2=&nbsp;[[Dinosauromorpha]]&nbsp;\n   |2={{clade\n      |label1=&nbsp;[[Lagerpetonidae]]&nbsp;\n      |1={{Clade\n         |1=''[[Lagerpeton]]''\n         |2=''[[Dromomeron]]''\n}}\n      |label2=&nbsp;[[Dinosauriformes]]&nbsp;\n      |2={{clade\n         |1=''[[Marasuchus]]''\n         |2={{Clade\n            |label1=&nbsp;[[Silesauridae]]&nbsp;\n            |1={{clade\n               |1=''[[Lewisuchus]]''/''[[Pseudolagosuchus]]''\n               |2={{clade\n                  |1=''[[Asilisaurus]]''\n                  |2={{clade\n                     |1=''[[Eucoelophysis]]''\n                     |2={{clade\n                        |1=''[[Sacisaurus]]''\n                        |2='''''Silesaurus'''''\n}} }} }} }} \n            |label2=&nbsp;[[Dinosauria]]&nbsp;\n            |2={{clade\n                     |label1=&nbsp;[[Saurischia]]&nbsp;\n                     |1={{clade\n                        |1=[[Theropoda]]\n                        |2=[[Sauropodomorpha]]}}\n                     |2=[[Ornithischia]]\n}} }} }} }} }} }}\n\n== Palaeobiology ==\n[[Image:MEPAN silezaur rauizuch.jpg|thumb|''Silesaurus opolensis'' and ''[[Polonosuchus silesiacus]]'' models in Poland]] \nBeetle [[Elytron|elytra]] and other arthropod remains have been found in [[Coprolite|coprolites]]  which have been recovered in the vicinity of ''Silesaurus'' fossil occurrences. The size and shape of the coprolites combined with the peculiar beaked architecture of ''Silesaurus'''s skull may suggest that this animal produced the coprolites and that it could have been wholly or partially insectivorous. It might have fed on insects and other small arthropods by [[pecking]], using the beak-like tip of the snout to accurately target prey in a way similar to modern birds. If so, this would represent the earliest known occurrence of this highly derived mode of feeding and have implications for the understanding of  the evolutionary adaptations that would eventually lead up to the [[Dinosaur#Origins_and_early_evolution|origin of dinosaurs]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Palaeoecology==\n''Silesaurus'' lived in a subtropical environment similar to the modern [[Mediterranean basin]] with alternating summer monsoons and dry winters. The animal shared its environment of extensive swamplands and [[Fern|fern]] vegetation with a wealth of [[Invertebrate|invertebrates]] as well as [[Lungfish|dipnoan]] and ganoid fishes, [[Temnospondyli|temnospondyls]], [[Phytosaur|phytosaurs]] and early [[Pterosaur|pterosaurs]].<ref>John W. M. Jagt, Grzegorz Hebda, S\u0142awomir Mitrus, Elena Jagt-Yazykova, Adam Bodzioch, Dorota Konietzko-Meier, Klaudia Kardyna\u0142, Kamil Gruntmejer. 2015. Field Guide, Conference Paper, European Association of Vertebrate Palaeontologists XIII Annual Meeting.</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ornithodira|D.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2322754}}\n\n[[Category:Silesaurids]]\n[[Category:Opole County]]\n[[Category:Late Triassic dinosauriforms]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 2003]]\n[[Category:Late Triassic reptiles of Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Szymon G\u00f3rnicki", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silesaurus"}
{"title_page": "Military dictatorship of Chile (1973\u20131990)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Former Country\n|native_name          = ''Rep\u00fablica de Chile''\n|conventional_long_name = Republic of Chile\n|common_name          = Chile\n|era                  = Cold War\n|event_start          = [[1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat|Coup d'et\u00e1t]]\n|year_start           = 1973\n|date_start           = September 11,\n|event1               = [[Constitution of Chile|Constitution]]\n|date_event1          = March 11, 1981\n|event2               = [[1988 Chilean national plebiscite|Plebiscite]]\n|date_event2          = October 5, 1988\n|event_end            = [[Chilean transition to democracy|Transition to democracy]]\n|year_end             = 1990\n|date_end             = March 11,\n|p1                   = Presidential Republic (1925\u201373)\n|flag_p1              = Flag of Chile.svg\n|s1                   = Chilean transition to democracy\n|flag_s1              = Flag of Chile.svg\n|image_flag           = Flag of Chile.svg\n|image_coat           = Coat of arms of Chile.svg\n|image_map            = CHL_orthographic_(%2Ball_claims).svg\n|national_motto       = ''[[List of national mottos|Por la raz\u00f3n o la fuerza]]''<br />{{small|(\"Through Reason Or By Force\")}}\n|national_anthem      = ''[[Himno Nacional de Chile]]''<br />{{small|(\"National Anthem of Chile\")}}\n|common_languages     = [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n|government_type      = [[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[Authoritarianism|authoritarian]] [[military dictatorship]]\n|capital              = [[Santiago]]\n|leader1              = [[Augusto Pinochet]]\n|year_leader1         = 1974\u201390\n|title_leader         = [[President of Chile|President]]\n|representative1      = [[Augusto Pinochet]]\n|representative2      = [[Jose Toribio Merino]]\n|year_representative1 = 1974\u201381\n|year_representative2 = 1981\u201390\n|title_representative = [[Government Junta of Chile (1973)|President of the Junta]]\n|legislature          = [[Government Junta of Chile (1973)|Government Junta]]\n|stat_pop1            = 10,095,485\n|stat_year1           = 1973\n|stat_pop2            = 11,178,817\n|stat_year2           = 1980\n|stat_pop3            = 13,187,821\n|stat_year3           = 1990\n|currency             = {{nowrap|[[Chilean escudo]] {{small|(1973\u201375)}}<br />[[Chilean peso]] {{small|(1975\u201390)}}}}\n|demonym=|area_km2=756,096.3|area_rank=37th|GDP_PPP=|GDP_PPP_year=|HDI=0.640|HDI_year=1980}}\n{{History of Chile}}\nThe '''military dictatorship of Chile''' ({{lang-es|dictadura militar de Chile}}) was an authoritarian military regime that ruled [[Chile]] for seventeen years, between September 11, 1973 and March 11, 1990. The dictatorship was established after the [[Presidency of Salvador Allende|democratically-elected socialist government]] of [[Salvador Allende]] was overthrown in a [[1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]] on 11 September 1973. During this time, the country was ruled by a [[Government Junta of Chile (1973)|military junta]] headed by General [[Augusto Pinochet]]. The military used the alleged breakdown of democracy and the economic crisis that took place during Allende's presidency to justify its seizure of power. The dictatorship presented its mission as a \"national reconstruction.\" The coup was the result of multiple forces, including pressure from conservative and women\u2019s groups, certain political parties, union strikes and other domestic unrest, as well as international factors. According to an article written by lifelong CIA operative [[Jack Devine]], although it was widely reported that the CIA was directly involved in orchestrating and carrying out the coup, subsequently released sources suggest a much reduced role of the US government.<ref>Jack Devine & Peter Kornbluh, 'Showdown in Santiago: What Really Happened in Chile?', Foreign Affairs 93 (2014), 168-174.</ref>\n\nThe regime was characterized by the systematic suppression of political parties and the persecution of dissidents to an extent unprecedented in the [[history of Chile]]. Overall, the regime left over 3,000 dead or missing, tortured tens of thousands of prisoners,<ref name=\"BBC-Chile\">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/country_profiles/1222764.stm |title=Country profile: Chile |work=BBC News |date=16 December 2009 |accessdate=31 December 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114035710/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/country_profiles/1222764.stm |archivedate=14 January 2010 }}</ref> and drove an estimated 200,000 Chileans into exile.<ref>{{Citation\n| last1            = Wright\n| first1           = T.C.\n| last2            = O\u00f1ate\n| first2           = R.\n| contribution     = Chilean Diaspora\n| editor-last1     = Ember\n| editor-first1    = M.\n| editor-last2     = Ember\n| editor-first2    = C.R.\n| editor-last3     = Skoggard\n| editor-first3    = I.\n| title            = Encyclopedia of Diasporas: Immigrant and Refugee Cultures Around the World\n| volume           = II\n| pages            = 57\u201365\n| place            = \n| date = 2005\n| contribution-url = \n}}</ref> The dictatorship's effects on Chilean political and economic life continue to be felt. Two years after its ascension radical [[neoliberal]] economic reforms were implemented, in sharp contrast to Allende's leftist policies, advised by a team of free-market economists educated in US universities known as the [[Chicago Boys]]. Later, in 1980, the regime replaced the [[Chilean Constitution of 1925]] with a [[Constitution of Chile|new constitution]]. This established a series of provisions that would eventually lead to the [[1988 Chilean national plebiscite]] on October 5 of that year.\n\nIn that referendum, the Chilean people denied Pinochet a new mandate, opening the way for the [[Chilean transition to democracy|reestablishment of democracy in 1990]]. Consequently, democratic presidential elections were held the following year. The military dictatorship ended in 1990 with the election of [[Christian Democratic Party (Chile)|Christian-Democrat]] candidate [[Patricio Aylwin]]. However, the military remained out of civilian control for several years after the junta itself had lost power.<ref name=AngellPollack1990>{{cite journal |last=Angell |first=Alan |last2=Pollack |first2=Benny |date=1990 |title=The Chilean Elections of 1989 |journal=[[Bulletin of Latin American Research]] |publisher=Society for Latin American Studies |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201323 |doi= 10.2307/3338214|jstor=3338214 }}</ref>\n\n==Rise to power==\n{{main|1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat}}\n\nThere has been a large amount of debate over the extent of US government involvement in destabilising the Allende government.<ref>{{Citation|last=Harmer|first=Tanya|chapter=Rebellion|date=2011-10-10|pages=73\u2013106|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|isbn=9780807834954|doi=10.5149/9780807869246_harmer.8|title=Allende's Chile and the Inter-American Cold War}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=The Pinochet File: A Declassified Dossier on Atrocity and Accountability|doi = 10.1163/2468-1733_shafr_sim180020010}}</ref> Recently declassified documents show evidence of communication between the Chilean military and US officials, suggesting covert US involvement in assisting the military\u2019s rise to power. Some key figures in the [[Presidency of Richard Nixon|Nixon administration]], such as [[Henry Kissinger]], used the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) to mount a major destabilization campaign.<ref name=autogenerated1>Citation error. See inline comment how to fix. {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/888821672 by a bug in VisualEditor and later identified by a bot. The original cite can be found around Special:Permalink/888821482 (or in a rev close to it) as cite #6 - find and verify the cite and replace this template with it (2). [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> As the CIA revealed in 2000, \"In the 1960s and the early 1970s, as part of the US Government policy to try to influence events in Chile, the CIA undertook specific covert action projects in Chile ... to discredit Marxist-leaning political leaders, especially Dr. Salvador Allende, and to strengthen and encourage their civilian and military opponents to prevent them from assuming power.\"<ref>Citation error. See inline comment how to fix. {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/888821672 by a bug in VisualEditor and later identified by a bot. The original cite can be found around Special:Permalink/888821482 (or in a rev close to it) as cite #7 - find and verify the cite and replace this template with it (2). [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> The CIA worked with right-wing Chilean politicians, military personnel, and journalists to undermine socialism in Chile.<ref>Citation error. See inline comment how to fix. {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/888821672 by a bug in VisualEditor and later identified by a bot. The original cite can be found around Special:Permalink/888821482 (or in a rev close to it) as cite #8 - find and verify the cite and replace this template with it (2). [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> One reason for this was financial, as many US businesses had investments in Chile, and Allende\u2019s socialist policies included the nationalisation of Chile\u2019s major industries. Another reason was the propagandized fear of the spread of communism, which was particularly important in the context of the Cold War. The rationale was that US feared that Allende would promote the spreading of Soviet influence in their \u2018backyard\u2019.<ref>{{Citation|last=Harmer|first=Tanya|chapter=Rebellion|date=2011-10-10|volume=|pages=258\u2013259|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|isbn=9780807834954|doi=10.5149/9780807869246_harmer.8|title=Allende's Chile and the Inter-American Cold War}}</ref> However, the fact that Allende's peaceful path was toward Socialism\u2014not Communism\u2014and because of the vested interests of the U.S. copper industry in Chile, the rationale had more to do with U.S. financial interests. As early as 1963, the U.S. via the CIA and U.S. multinationals such as ITT intervened in Chilean politics using a variety of tactics and millions of dollars to interfere with elections, ultimately helping plan the coup against Allende.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nieto |first1=Clara |title=Masters of War: Latin America and U.S. Aggression |date=2003 |publisher=Seven Stories Press |location=New York |pages=295\u2013299}}</ref><ref name=\"Kornbluh\">{{cite book |last1=Kornbluh |first1=Peter |title=The Pinochet File: A Declassified Dossier on Atrocity and Accountability |date=2013 |publisher=The New Press |location=New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Walkowitz |first1=Daniel J. |title=\"Foreign Policy Failures and Dilemmas\" in Social History of the United States |publisher=ABC-CLIO |pages=364\u2013381}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April 1973, workers from the [[El Teniente]] mining camp had ceased working, demanding higher wages. The strike lasted 76 days and cost the government severely in lost revenues. One of the strikers, Luis Bravo Morales, was shot dead in [[Rancagua]] city. On June 29, the Blindados No. 2 tank regiment under the command of Colonel [[Roberto Souper]], attacked [[La Moneda]], Chile's presidential palace. Instigated by the anti-Marxist militia [[Patria y Libertad]] (\"''country and freedom''\"), the armoured cavalry soldiers hoped other units would be inspired to join them. Instead, armed units led by generals [[Carlos Prats]] and [[Augusto Pinochet]] quickly put down the coup attempt. In late July, 40,000 truckers, squeezed by price controls and rising costs, tied up transportation in a nationwide strike that lasted 37 days, costing the government $6 million USD a day.<ref>''Historical Dictionary of Chile'', Salvatore Bizzarro, p. 34, Scarecrow Press, 2005</ref> Two weeks before the coup, public dissatisfaction with rising prices and food shortages led to protests like the one at the Plaza de la Constituci\u00f3n which had been dispersed with tear gas.<ref>\"[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,907929-8,00.html The Bloody End of a Marxist Dream] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111111142339/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,907929-8,00.html |date=2011-11-11 }}\". ''Time Magazine''. 24 September 1973.</ref> Allende also clashed with Chile's largest circulation newspaper ''[[El Mercurio]]''. Tax-evasion charges were trumped up against the newspaper and its director arrested.<ref>''Authoritarian Regimes in Latin America: Dictators, Despots, and Tyrants'', Paul H. Lewis, p. 204, Rowman & Littlefield, 2006</ref> The Allende government found it impossible to control inflation, which grew to more than 300 percent by September,<ref>''Latin America in the Era of the Cuban Revolution'', Thomas C. Wright, p. 139, Greenwood Publishing Group, 2001</ref> further dividing Chileans over the Allende government and its policies.\n\nUpper- and middle-class right-wing women also played an important role in destabilising the Allende government. They co-ordinated two prominent opposition groups called ''[[:es:Poder Femenino|El Poder Feminino]]'' (\"''female power''\"), and ''Solidaridad, Orden y Liberdad'' (\"''solidarity, order, and freedom''\").<ref>{{Cite journal|last=de los Angeles Crummett|first=Mar\u00eda|date=October 1977|title=El Poder Feminino: the Mobilization of Women Against Socialism in Chile|journal=Latin American Perspectives|volume=4|issue=4|pages=103\u2013113|doi=10.1177/0094582x7700400407|issn=0094-582X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|date=October 2003|title=<sc>Margaret Power</sc>. <italic>Right-Wing Women in Chile: Feminine Power and the Struggle against Allende 1964\u20131973</italic>. University Park, Penn.: Pennsylvania State University Press. 2002. Pp. xxii, 311. Cloth $65.00, paper $25.00|journal=The American Historical Review|doi=10.1086/ahr/108.4.1192|issn=1937-5239}}</ref> These women who opposed Allende felt as though their fundamental values of family and motherhood were being threatened by Marxism. Furthermore, the economic chaos that Allende\u2019s regime was seeing meant that there were struggles to buy food and thus look after their families. Allende\u2019s regime therefore threatened the most important aspect of a woman\u2019s role. These women used many tactics to destabilise the Allende regime. They carried out the \u2018[https://www.encyclopedia.com/humanities/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/march-empty-pots March of the Empty Pots and Pans]\u2019 in December 1971, and emasculated the military. These women criticised the military for being \u2018cowards\u2019 for not getting rid of Allende, arguing that they were not carrying out their role of protecting Chilean women.\n\nOn August 22, 1973, the [[Chamber of Deputies of Chile|Chamber of Deputies]] passed, by a vote of 81 to 47, a resolution calling for President Allende to respect the constitution. The measure failed to obtain the two-thirds majority in the [[Senate of Chile|Senate]] constitutionally required to convict the president of abuse of power, but the resolution still represented a challenge to Allende's legitimacy. The military were staunch supporters of the constitution and therefore believed that Allende had lost legitimacy as Chile\u2019s leader.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=PASSMORE|first=LEITH|date=August 2018|title=John R. Bawden, The Pinochet Generation: The Chilean Military in the Twentieth Century (Tuscaloosa, AL: University of Alabama Press, 2016), pp. x + 288, $49.95, $49.95 E-book|journal=Journal of Latin American Studies|volume=50|issue=3|pages=746\u2013747|doi=10.1017/s0022216x18000469|issn=0022-216X}}</ref> As a result, reacting to widespread public demand for intervention, the military began planning for a military coup which would ultimately take place on September 11, 1973. Contrary to popular belief, Pinochet was not the mastermind behind the coup. It was, in fact, naval officers who first decided that military intervention was necessary to remove President Allende from power.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Chile: The Pinochet Decade|last=O\u2019Brien|first=Phillip|last2=Roddick|first2=Jacqueline|date=January 1983|publisher=Latin America Bureau|isbn=9780906156186|location=Rugby, Warwickshire, United Kingdom|doi=10.3362/9781909013599|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/chilepinochetdec0000obri}}</ref> Army generals were unsure of Pinochet\u2019s allegiances, as he had given no prior indication of disloyalty to Allende, and thus was only informed of these plans on the evening of 8 September, just three days before the coup took place.<ref>{{Citation|last=O\u2019Shaugnessy|first=Hugh|chapter=3. Treason and Terror|date=January 2000|pages=49\u2013118|publisher=Latin America Bureau|isbn=9781899365418|doi=10.3362/9781909013384.003|title=Pinochet}}</ref> On 11 September 1973, the military launched a coup, with troops surrounding La Moneda Palace. Allende died that day of [[Death of Salvador Allende|suspected suicide]].\n\nThe military installed themselves in power as a [[Government Junta of Chile (1973)|Military Government Junta]], composed of the heads of the Army, Navy, Air Force and Carabineros (police). Once the Junta was in power, General [[Augusto Pinochet]] soon consolidated his control over the government. Since he was the commander-in-chief of the oldest branch of the military forces (the Army), he was made the titular head of the junta, and soon after [[President of Chile]]. Once the junta had taken over, the United States immediately recognized the new regime and helped it consolidate power.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n==Dictatorship violence==\n\n===Suppression of political activity===\n[[Image:Quema de libros.jpg|thumb|[[Book burnings in Chile|Book burning in Chile]] following the [[1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat|1973 coup]] that installed the Pinochet regime.]]\n\nOn September 13, the junta dissolved the Congress and outlawed or suspended all political activities in addition to suspending the [[Chilean Constitution of 1925|1925 constitution]]. All political activity was declared \"in recess\". The Government Junta immediately banned the socialist, Marxist and other [[left-wing politics|leftist]] parties that had constituted former President Allende's [[Popular Unity (Chile)|Popular Unity]] coalition<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leychile.cl/Navegar?idNorma=5730|title=DL-77 13-OCT-1973 Ministerio del Interior |publisher= Ley Chile \u2013 Biblioteca del Congreso Nacional|work=leychile.cl|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029200802/http://www.leychile.cl/Navegar?idNorma=5730|archivedate=2013-10-29|date=1973-10-13 }}</ref> and began a systemic campaign of imprisonment, torture, harassment and/or murder against the perceived opposition. [[Eduardo Frei Montalva|Eduardo Frei]], Allende's predecessor as president, initially supported the coup along with his Christian Democratic colleagues. However, they later assumed the role of a loyal opposition to the military rulers. Though they soon lost most of their influence they were subjected to the same treatment that the UP members had been before them.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}} During 1976-77, this repression even reached independent and Christian Democrat labour leaders who had supported the coup, several were exiled.<ref>{{Citation|chapter=Introduction|date=2004|pages=1\u201313|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0-8223-3309-8|doi=10.1215/9780822385851-001|title=Victims of the Chilean Miracle}}</ref> Christian Democrats like [[Radomiro Tomic]] were jailed or forced into exile.<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/666903512.html?dids=666903512:666903512&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&date=Dec+12%2C+1982&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Pinochet+Forms+Panel+to+Consider+Return+of+Chileans+Sent+Into+Exile&pqatl=google] Pinochet Forms Panel to Consider Return of Chileans Sent Into Exile</ref><ref>[http://www.elpais.com/articulo/agenda/CHILE/Radomiro/Tomic/politico/chileno/elpepigen/19920104elpepiage_1/Tes] Radomiro Tomic, pol\u00edtico chileno</ref>  Retired military personnel were named rectors of universities and they carried out vast purges of suspected left-wing sympathisers.<ref>{{Citation|last=Power|first=Jonathan|title=Ending War Crimes, Chasing the War Criminals|chapter=The Pinochet Case|date=2017-01-01|publisher=Brill {{!}} Nijhoff|isbn=978-90-04-34634-5|doi=10.1163/9789004346345_010}}</ref> With such strong repression, the Catholic church became the only public voice allowed within Chile. By 1974, the Commission of Peace had established a large network to provide information to numerous organisations regarding human rights abuses in Chile. As a result of this, Manuel Contreras, Director of DINA, threatened Cardinal Silva Henriquez that his safety could be at risk if the Church continued to interfere which in turn resulted in death threats and intimidation from agents of the regime.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aguilar|first=Mario I.|date=2003|title=Cardinal Raul Silva Henriquez, the Catholic Church, and the Pinochet Regime, 1973-1980: Public Responses to a National Security State|journal=The Catholic Historical Review|volume=89|issue=4|pages=712\u2013731|doi=10.1353/cat.2003.0183|issn=1534-0708}}</ref>  \n\nA key provision of the new constitution of 1980 aimed at eliminating leftist factions, \u201coutlawed the propagation of doctrines that attack the family or put forward a concept of society based on the class struggle\u201d. Pinochet maintained strict command over the armed forces thus he could depend on them to censor the media, arrest opposition leaders and repress demonstrations. This was accompanied by a complete shutting down of civil society with curfews, prohibition of public assembly, press blackouts, draconian censorship and universities were purged.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pratt|first=M. L.|date=1996-01-01|title=Overwriting Pinochet: Undoing the Culture of Fear in Chile|journal=Modern Language Quarterly|volume=57|issue=2|pages=151\u2013163|doi=10.1215/00267929-57-2-151|issn=0026-7929}}</ref> \n\n===Human rights violations===\n{{Further|Human rights in Chile|Human rights violations in Pinochet's Chile}}\n\nThe military rule was characterized by systematic suppression of all political dissidence. Scholars later described this as a \"[[politicide]]\" (or \"political genocide\").<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=xzW2-dMwfCMC&pg=PA303&lpg=PA303&dq=Sznajder,+1996+chile&source=bl&ots=cbMoAau_kv&sig=cgl1Tmvq9pffECAO1zlujDv5Z7I&hl=en&ei=1entSdbaIo-SMuLC8QM&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1] The legacy of human-rights violations in the Southern Cone</ref> Steve J. Stern spoke of a politicide to describe \"a systematic project to destroy an entire way of doing and understanding politics and governance.\"<ref name=Stern>{{cite book\n  | last = Stern\n  | first = Steve J.\n  | title = Remembering Pinochet's Chile\n  | publisher = Duke University Press\n  | year = 2004\n  | pages = 32, 90, 101, 180\u2013181\n  | isbn = 978-0822333548}}</ref>\n\nEstimates of figures for victims of state violence vary and are highly contested. [[Rudolph Rummel]] estimates 10,000 killed during Pinochet's regime, with 30,000 being the highest possible number.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mega.nu:8080/ampp/rummel/postwwii.tab.gif|title=Table 4: Democide Rank Ordered (1970\u20131979)|last=RJ|first=Rummel|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215847/http://www.mega.nu:8080/ampp/rummel/postwwii.tab.gif|archivedate=2013-10-04|url-status=live}}</ref> Rummel notes an estimate by Sivard that 3,000 miners were killed by the Chilean army in a dispute in 1987.<ref>[http://www.hawaii.edu/powerkills/SOD.TAB15.1A.GIF Table 15.1A] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005061447/http://www.hawaii.edu/powerkills/SOD.TAB15.1A.GIF|date=2012-10-05}} in {{cite book|url=http://www.hawaii.edu/powerkills/NOTE5.HTM|title=Statistics of Democide|last=Rummel|first=RJ|publisher=School of Law, University of Virginia|year=1997|location=Charlottesville|accessdate=23 March 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313062609/http://www.hawaii.edu/powerkills/NOTE5.HTM|archivedate=13 March 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Other sources place the number of all the victims of the dictatorship as high as 15,000 killed and 2,000 disappeared.<ref>Graham, 1990; cited in Johnson 2006, p. 85</ref> In 1996, human rights activists announced they had presented another 899 cases of people who had disappeared or been killed during the dictatorship, taking the total of known victims to 3,197, of whom 2,095 were reported killed and 1,102 missing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sun_sentinel/doc/388555201.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug%2023,%201996&author=Sun-Sentinel%20wire%20services&pub=South%20Florida%20Sun%20-%20Sentinel&edition=&startpage=&desc=GUNMEN%20THREATEN%20MEDIA|title=Gunmen Threaten Media|publisher=Sun-Sentinel (Archives)|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225224936/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sun_sentinel/doc/388555201.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug%2023,%201996&author=Sun-Sentinel%20wire%20services&pub=South%20Florida%20Sun%20-%20Sentinel&edition=&startpage=&desc=GUNMEN%20THREATEN%20MEDIA|archivedate=25 February 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=25 February 2015}}</ref> Following the return to democracy with the Concertacion government, the [[Rettig Commission]], a multipartisan effort by the Aylwin administration to discover the truth about the human-rights violations, listed a number of torture and detention centers (such as [[Colonia Dignidad]], [[Esmeralda (BE-43)|the ship ''Esmeralda'']] or [[V\u00edctor Jara Stadium]]), and found that at least 3,200 people were killed or disappeared by the regime. Later, the 2004 [[Valech Report]] confirmed the figure of 3,200 deaths but reduced the estimated number of disappearances. It tells of some 28,000 arrests in which the majority of those detained were incarcerated and in a great many cases tortured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minvu.cl/ingles/opensite_20070320074217.aspx|title=Valech Report |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322143320/http://www.minvu.cl/ingles/opensite_20070320074217.aspx|archivedate=2015-03-22|url-status=live|accessdate=2014-08-26}}</ref> In 2011, the Chilean government officially recognized 36,948 survivors of torture and political imprisonment, as well as 3,095 people killed or disappeared at the hands of the military government.<ref>[http://www.omaha.com/article/20110818/AP15/308189901 Controversial victims on Chile's official list, by Eva Vergara, Omaha World-Herald, August 18, 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20131002040217/http://www.omaha.com/article/20110818/AP15/308189901|date=October 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe worst violence occurred within the first three months of the coup, with the number of suspected leftists killed or \"[[Forced disappearance|disappeared]]\" (''desaparecidos'') reaching several thousand.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/1109861.stm|title=Finding Chile's disappeared|date=2001-01-10|accessdate=2010-01-05|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217123536/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/1109861.stm|archivedate=2009-02-17|url-status=live}} BBC: Finding Chile's disappeared</ref> In the days immediately following the coup, the Assistant Secretary of State for Inter-American Affairs informed [[Henry Kissinger]] that the [[Estadio Nacional de Chile|National Stadium]] was being used to hold 5,000 prisoners. Between the day of the coup and November 1973, as many as 40,000 political prisoners were held there<ref>{{cite journal|last=G\u00f3mez-Barris|first=Macarena|year=2010|title=Witness Citizenship: The Place of Villa Grimaldi in Chilean Memory|journal=Sociological Forum|volume=25|issue=1|page=34|doi=10.1111/j.1573-7861.2009.01155.x}}</ref><ref name=\"ElPaisStadium\">{{cite news|url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/deportes/campo/concentracion/Pinochet/cumple/anos/elpepudep/20081203elpepudep_19/Tes|title=El campo de concentraci\u00f3n de Pinochet cumple 70 a\u00f1os|author=|date=3 December 2008|newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]]}}</ref> and as late as 1975, the CIA was still reporting that up to 3,811 were imprisoned there.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4-RfeEIeKRkC&pg=PA38&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Thinking about Terrorism|last1=Tigar|first1=Michael E.|year=2007|isbn=9781590318423|accessdate=25 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225182326/http://books.google.es/books?id=4-RfeEIeKRkC&pg=PA38&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|archivedate=25 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> 1,850 of them were killed, another 1,300 are still missing to this day.<ref name=\"ElPaisStadium\" /> Some of the most famous cases of ''desaparecidos'' are [[Charles Horman]], a U.S. citizen who was killed during the coup itself,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB33/index.html|title=New Information on the Murders of U.S. Citizens Charles Horman and Frank Teruggi by the Chilean Military|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111019205138/http://www.gwu.edu/%7Ensarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB33/index.html|archivedate=2011-10-19|url-status=live|accessdate=2011-11-19}} New Information on the Murders of U.S. Citizens Charles Horman and Frank Teruggi by the Chilean Military</ref> Chilean songwriter [[V\u00edctor Jara]], and the October 1973 [[Caravan of Death]] (''Caravana de la Muerte'') where at least 70 persons were killed.\n\nLeftist guerrilla groups and their sympathizers were also hit hard during the military regime. The MIR commander, [[Andr\u00e9s Pascal Allende]], has stated that the Marxist guerrillas lost 1,500\u20132,000 fighters killed or disappeared.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bJ2-wUrZn8IC&pg=PA155&dq=|title=Los Allende|last1=Wessel|first1=G\u00fcnther|year=2004|isbn=9788473602020|accessdate=25 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130915020906/http://books.google.es/books?id=bJ2-wUrZn8IC&pg=PA155&dq=|archivedate=15 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Among the killed and disappeared during the military regime were at least 663 MIR guerrillas.<ref name=\"archivochile.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.archivochile.com/Derechos_humanos/doc_gen_ddhh/hhdddocgen0002.pdf|title=Caidos del Mir en Diferente Periodis|author=Centro de Estuiios Miguel Enriquez (CEME)|website=archivochile.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413053224/http://www.archivochile.com/Derechos_humanos/doc_gen_ddhh/hhdddocgen0002.pdf|archivedate=13 April 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref> The Manuel Rodr\u00edguez Patriotic Front stated that 49 FPMR guerrillas were killed and hundreds tortured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fpmr.org/heroes8.html|title=Frente Patri\u00f3tico Manuel Rodr\u00edguez|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051104044728/http://fpmr.org/heroes8.html|archivedate=4 November 2005|url-status=dead|accessdate=25 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Latin American Institute on Mental Health and Human Rights, 200,000 people were affected by \"extreme trauma\"; this figure includes individuals executed, tortured, forcibly exiled, or having their immediate relatives put under detention.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Vasallo|first=Mark|year=2002|title=Truth and Reconciliation Commissions: General Considerations and a Critical Comparison of the Commissions of Chile and El Salvador|journal=The University of Miami Inter-American Law Review|volume=33|issue=1|page=163}}</ref> 316 women have reported to have subject to rape by soldiers and agents of the dictatorship, however the number is believed to much larger due to the preference of many women to avoid talking about this. Twenty pregnant women have declared to have suffered abortion due to torture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radio.uchile.cl/2013/09/03/violencia-sexual-contra-mujeres-en-dictadura-un-crimen-invisibilizado|title=Violencia sexual contra mujeres en dictadura: un crimen invisibilizado \u00ab Diario y Radio U Chile|website=radio.uchile.cl|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008103150/http://radio.uchile.cl/2013/09/03/violencia-sexual-contra-mujeres-en-dictadura-un-crimen-invisibilizado|archivedate=8 October 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref> In the words of [[Alejandra Matus]] detained women were doubly punished, first for being \"leftists\" and second for not conforming to their ideal of women usually being called \"perra\" (lit. \"bitch\").<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tVjdRz8LevE Cultura Verdadera Programa Completo del Lunes 14 de Diciembre de 2015] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202023740/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tVjdRz8LevE|date=2017-02-02}}, minute 3:20.</ref>\n\nIn addition to the violence experienced within Chile, many people fled the regime; some 30,000 Chileans were exiled,<ref>Augusto Pinochet's Chile, Diana Childress, p. 92, Twenty First century Books, 2009</ref><ref name=\"Jaime Gazmuri p. 121\">Chile en el umbral de los noventa: quince a\u00f1os que condicionan el futuro, Jaime Gazmuri & Felipe Ag\u00fcero, p. 121, Planeta, 1988</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|date=22 August 1983|title=Chile: One Carrot, Many Sticks|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,926095,00.html|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828011629/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,926095,00.html|archivedate=28 August 2013|accessdate=25 February 2015|magazine=Time.com}}</ref> particularly to [[Argentina]], however, [[Operation Condor]], which linked South American dictatorships together against political opponents, meant that even these exiles could be subject to violence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB125/index.htm|title=Lifting of Pinochet's Immunity Renews Focus on Operation Condor|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140919124055/http://www2.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB125/index.htm|archivedate=2014-09-19|url-status=live|accessdate=2014-08-26}}</ref> Some 20,000\u201340,000 Chilean exiles were holders of passports stamped with the letter \"L\" (which stood for ''lista nacional''), identifying them as ''persona non grata'' and had to seek permission before entering the country.<ref>\"Chile since the coup: ten years of repression\", Cynthia G. Brown, pp. 88\u201389, ''Americas Watch'', 1983.</ref> According to a study in [[Latin American Perspectives]],<ref name=\"ExileStudy\">{{cite journal|last1=Wright|first1=Thomas C.|last2=O\u00f1ate Z\u00fa\u00f1iga|first2=Rody|year=2007|title=Chilean political exile|journal=[[Latin American Perspectives]]|volume=34|issue=4|page=31|doi=10.1177/0094582x07302902}}</ref> at least 200,000 Chileans (about 2% of Chile's 1973 population) were forced into exile. Additionally, hundreds of thousands left the country in the wake of the economic crises that followed the military coup during the 1970s and 1980s.<ref name=\"ExileStudy\" /> In 2003, an article published by the [[International Committee of the Fourth International]] claimed that \"Of a population of barely 11 million, more than 4,000 were executed or 'disappeared,' hundreds of thousands were detained and tortured, and almost a million fled the country.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2003/09/chil-s17.html|title=The lessons of Chile \u2013 30 years on|author=Mauricio Saavedra|date=17 September 2003|publisher=World Socialist Web Site|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226001119/http://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2003/09/chil-s17.html|archivedate=26 February 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=25 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box |quote   =He shut down parliament, suffocated political life, banned trade unions, and made Chile his sultanate. His government disappeared 3,200 opponents, arrested 30,000 (torturing thousands of them) ... Pinochet's name will forever be linked to the [[Forced disappearance|''Desaparecidos'']], the [[Caravan of Death]], and the institutionalized torture that took place in the [[Villa Grimaldi]] complex.| [[Thor Halvorssen Mendoza|Thor Halvorssen]], president of the [[Human Rights Foundation]], ''[[National Review]]''<ref>[http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=NDQxNTJlM2M4OTRhOGJhNTMzNTkyNDQ2YmYzMTU3ZTU= Pinochet is history: But how will it remember him?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070615015027/http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=NDQxNTJlM2M4OTRhOGJhNTMzNTkyNDQ2YmYzMTU3ZTU%3D |date=2007-06-15 }} ''[[National Review]]'' Symposium, December 11, 2006</ref>}}\n\n<br />\n\n[[File:Casa de detenci\u00f3n clandestina en Jos\u00e9 Domingo Ca\u00f1as 01.JPG|thumb|[[Direcci\u00f3n de Inteligencia Nacional|DINA]]'s torture center at Jos\u00e9 Domingo Ca\u00f1as 1367]]\nThere were also internal exiles who due to a lack of resources could not escape abroad.<ref name=marin>{{cite journal |last1=Mar\u00edn Lleuc\u00fan |first1=Alejandro |date=2015 |title= Puerto Gala y Puerto Gaviota (1985-1993): Una mirada desde el tri\u00e1ngulo de la violencia|trans-title=Port of Gala and Port of Gaviota (1985-1993): A look from the triangle of violence |url=https://scielo.conicyt.cl/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&pid=S0718-22442015000200004 |journal=[[Magallania]] |volume=43 |issue=2 |pages= |doi= |access-date=January 10, 2019|language=Spanish }}</ref> In the 1980s a few left-wing sympathisers hid in [[Puerto Gala]] and [[Puerto Gaviota]], Patagonian fishing communities with a reputation of lawlessness. There they were joined by delinquents who feared torture or death by the authorities.<ref name=marin/>\n\n[[File:Ejecutados pinochet.jpg|thumb|left|Some funeral urns of political activists executed by the Chilean military dictatorship, from 1973 to 1990, in the cemetery of Santiago]]Several scholars including Paul Zwier,<ref name=\"Zwier2013\">{{cite book|last=Zwier|first=Paul J.|title=Principled Negotiation and Mediation in the International Arena: Talking with Evil|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W57hIyEOSUsC&pg=PA235|accessdate=22 March 2014|year=2013|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1107026872|pages=235\u2013}}</ref> Peter Winn<ref>[https://books.google.cl/books?id=YLBVjRCW6uMC&pg=PA14&lpg=PA14&dq=estado+policial+pinochet&source=bl&ots=eaFke6YsUG&sig=qZVQuZ7JPFtsxhrrcL_HScUe6No&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HXGdVN-xF4LYgwT8h4LIAw&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=estado%20policial%20pinochet&f=false] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225225310/https://books.google.cl/books?id=YLBVjRCW6uMC&pg=PA14&lpg=PA14&dq=estado+policial+pinochet&source=bl&ots=eaFke6YsUG&sig=qZVQuZ7JPFtsxhrrcL_HScUe6No&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HXGdVN-xF4LYgwT8h4LIAw&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBw |date=2015-02-25 }}</ref> and human rights organizations<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmostrador.cl/pais/2008/08/06/organismos-de-ddhh-denuncian-un-estado-policial-similar-al-de-pinochet/|title=Organismos de DDHH denuncian un estado policial 'similar' al de Pinochet|work=El Mostrador|accessdate=25 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225182240/http://www.elmostrador.cl/pais/2008/08/06/organismos-de-ddhh-denuncian-un-estado-policial-similar-al-de-pinochet/|archivedate=25 February 2015|date=2008-08-06}}</ref> have characterized the dictatorship as a [[police state]] exhibiting \"repression of public liberties, the elimination of political exchange, limiting freedom of speech, abolishing the right to strike, freezing wages.\"<ref name=\"Casanova1993\">{{cite book|last=Casanova|first=Pablo Gonz\u00e1lez|title=Latin America Today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VNUNB2s5pcoC&pg=PA233|accessdate=22 March 2014|year=1993|publisher=United Nations University Press|isbn=9789280808193|pages=233\u2013}}</ref>\n\n===Fake combats===\nStarting in the late 1970s the regime began to use a tactic of faking combats, usually known by its Spanish name: \"falsos enfrentamientos\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://resumen.cl/2015/02/nuevos-condenados-por-falso-enfrentamiento-en-dictadura/|title=Nuevos condenados por falso enfrentamiento en dictadura |website=resumen.cl|accessdate=1 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201081335/https://resumen.cl/2015/02/nuevos-condenados-por-falso-enfrentamiento-en-dictadura/|archivedate=1 December 2017}}</ref> This meant that dissidents who were murdered outright had their deaths reported in media as if they had occurred in a mutual exchange of gunfire. This was done with support of journalists who \"reported\" the supposed events; in some cases, the fake combats were also staged. The faked combat tactic ameliorated criticism of the regime implicitly putting culpability on the victim. It is thought that the killing of the [[Revolutionary Left Movement (Chile)|MIR]] leader [[Miguel Enr\u00edquez (politician)|Miguel Enr\u00edquez]] in 1974 could be an early case of a faked combat. The faked combats reinforced the dictatorship narrative on the existence of an \"internal war\" which it used to justify its existence.<ref>{{cite thesis |last=Silva Hidalgo |first=Robinson Humberto |date=2014 |title=Resistencia pol\u00edtica y origen del movimiento social anti dictatorial en Chile (1973\u20131988) |type=Ph.D. |publisher=[[Universitat de Barcelona]] |url=http://diposit.ub.edu/dspace/bitstream/2445/55488/1/RHSH_TESIS.pdf |page=341\u2013349 |language=Spanish |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216184935/http://diposit.ub.edu/dspace/bitstream/2445/55488/1/RHSH_TESIS.pdf |archivedate=2016-02-16 }}</ref> A particular fake combat event, lasting from September 8 to 9 1983, occurred when forces of the CNI lobbed grenades into a house, detonating the structure and killing the two men and a woman who were in the building. The agents would later state, with help from the Chilean press, that the people in the house had fired on them previously from their cars and had escaped to the house. The official story became that the three suspects had caused the explosion themselves by trying to burn and destroy incriminating evidence. Such actions had the effect of justifying the existence of heavily armed forces in Chile. And by extension, justified the dictatorship's conduct against such \"violent\" offenders.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.archivochile.com/Derechos_humanos/janefuenove/ddhhjanefuov0001.pdf |title=Los Muertos en Falsos Enfrentamientos: Janequeo y Fuenteovejuna |accessdate=2017-11-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060507125801/http://www.archivochile.com/Derechos_humanos/janefuenove/ddhhjanefuov0001.pdf |archivedate=2006-05-07 }}</ref>\n\n==Politics and power within the dictatorship==\n\n===Pinochet\u2013Leigh conflict===\nIn the 1970s junta members [[Gustavo Leigh]] and Augusto Pinochet clashed on several occasions beginning in the day of the [[1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat]]. Leigh criticized Pinochet for having joined the coup very late and then pretending to keep all power for himself. In December 1974 Leigh opposed the proposal to name Pinochet president of Chile. Leigh recalls about that moment that, \"Pinochet was furious, he hit the board, broke the glass, injured his hand a little and bled. Then, Merino and Mendoza told me I should sign, because if not the junta would split. I signed.\". Leigh's primary concern was Pinochet's consolidating of the legislative and executive branches of government under the new government. In particular, Pinochet's decision to enact a plebiscite without formally alerting the other junta members.<ref name=\"auto1\">Ensalaco, Mark. 2000. Chile Under Pinochet : Recovering the Truth. Pennsylvania Studies in Human Rights. Philadelphia: University of Pennsylvania Press.</ref> Leigh, although a fervent supporter of the regime and hater of marxist ideology, had already taken steps to separate the executive and legislative branches. Pinochet is said to have been angered by Leigh's continued founding of a structure to divide the executive and legislative branches, eventually leading to Pinochet consolidating power and Leigh being dumped from the regime.<ref>Barros, Robert. La Junta militar: Pinochet y la Constituci\u00f3n de 1980. Sudamericana, 2005.</ref> Leigh tried to fight his dismissal from the military and government junta but on July 24, 1978 his office was blocked by paratroopers. In accordance with legal rights established by the junta government, its members could not be dismissed without evidence of impairment. So the Pinochet and junta members had Leigh declared unfit.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>\nCarmen Gardeweg: ''El general Leigh: pensamiento y sentimiento 48 horas despu\u00e9s de ser destituido en 1978''. La Segunda, 30 de septiembre de 1999, p\u00e1gina 8.</ref> Airforce General [[Fernando Matthei]] replaced Leigh as junta member.<ref name=newsbank>[http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BG&p_theme=bg&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EADED93AF54A141&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM 25 Chilean Soldiers Arrested in Burning of US Resident]</ref>\n\nAnother dictatorship member critical of Pinochet, [[Arturo Yovane]], was removed from his post as [[Ministry of Mining (Chile)|minister of mining]] in 1974 and appointed ambassador at the new Chilean embassy in [[Tehran]].<ref name=Gonzalez2009>{{cite web |url=http://ciperchile.cl/2009/08/06/el-dia-en-que-manuel-contreras-le-ofrecio-al-sha-de-iran-matar-a-%E2%80%9Cel-chacal%E2%80%9D/ |title=El d\u00eda en que Manuel Contreras le ofreci\u00f3 al Sha de Ir\u00e1n matar a \"Carlos, El Chacal\" |last1=Gonz\u00e1lez |first1=M\u00f3nica |date=August 6, 2009 |website=ciperchile.cl |publisher=CIPER |access-date=August 11, 2015 |language=Spanish |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909054340/http://ciperchile.cl/2009/08/06/el-dia-en-que-manuel-contreras-le-ofrecio-al-sha-de-iran-matar-a-%E2%80%9Cel-chacal%E2%80%9D/ |archivedate=September 9, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Civilian collaborators===\nOver time the dictatorship incorporated civilians into the government. Many of the [[Chicago boys]] joined the government, and Pinochet was largely sympathetic to them. This sympathy, scholar Peter Winn explains, was indebted to the fact that the Chicago boys were [[technocrat]]s and thus fitted Pinochet's self-image of being \"above politics\".<ref name=Winn2627>Winn, Peter (ed.). ''Victims of the Chilean miracle'', pp. 26\u201327.</ref> Pinochet was impressed by their assertiveness as well as by their links to the financial world of the United States.<ref name=Winn2627/>\n\nAnother group of civilians that collaborated extensively with the regime were the [[Gremialismo|Gremialists]], whose movement started in 1966 in the [[Pontifical Catholic University of Chile]].<ref name=Huneeus2000>{{cite journal |last=Huneeus |first=Carlos |date=2000 |title=Technocrats and politicians in an authoritarian regime. The 'ODEPLAN Boys' and the 'Gremialists' in Pinochet's Chile |jstor=158572 |journal=[[Journal of Latin American Studies]] |volume=32 |issue= 2|pages=461\u2013501 |doi= 10.1017/S0022216X00005812}}</ref> The founder of the Gremialist movement, lawyer [[Jaime Guzm\u00e1n]], never assumed any official position in the military dictatorship but he remained one of the closest collaborators with Pinochet, playing an important ideological role. He participated in the design of important speeches of Pinochet, and provided frequent political and doctrinal advice and consultancy.<ref name=\"archivochile\">{{cite web |author=Carlos Huneeus |publisher=Archivo Chile |title=Jaime Guzm\u00e1n no fue un defensor de los Derechos Humanos en el R\u00e9gimen de Pinochet |url=http://www.archivochile.com/Portada/8_ddhh/02_port_ddhh.pdf |date=3 April 2001 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923173556/http://www.archivochile.com/Portada/8_ddhh/02_port_ddhh.pdf |archivedate=23 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to scholar Carlos Huneeus the Gremialists and the Chicago Boys shared a long-term power strategy and were linked to each other in many ways.<ref name=Huneeus2000/>\nIn Chile, it has been very hard for the outside world to fully understand the role that everyday civilians played in keeping Pinochet's government afloat. Partly because there has been scant research into the topic, partly because those who did help the regime from 1973 to 1990 have been unwilling to explore their own part. One of the exemptions being an Univision interview with [[Osvaldo Romo|Osvaldo Romo Mena]], a civilian torturer in 1995, recounting his actions. Osvaldo Romo died while incarcerated for the murder of three political opponents. For the most part, civilian collaborators with Pinochet have not broken the [[code of silence]] held by the military of the 1970s to 1990s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raco.cat/index.php/rubrica/article/viewFile/310678/400693 |format=PDF |title=Complicity and Responsibility in the Aftermath of the Pinochet Regime: The Case of ''El Mocito'' |accessdate=2017-11-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201030451/http://www.raco.cat/index.php/rubrica/article/viewFile/310678/400693 |archivedate=2017-12-01 }}</ref>\n\n===Constitution of 1980===\n{{Main|1980 Chilean constitutional referendum}}\nEstablishing a new constitution was a core issue for the dictatorship since it provided a mean of [[legitimization]].<ref name=AngellPollack1990/> For this purpose the junta selected notable civilians willing to join the draft commission. Dissidents to the dictatorship were not represented in the commission.<ref name=Camel2000>{{cite journal|last=Cazor Aliste |first=Camel |date=2000 |title=Democracia y constitucion en Chile |url=http://mingaonline.uach.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-09502000000100003&script=sci_arttext |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518062933/http://mingaonline.uach.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-09502000000100003&script=sci_arttext |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-05-18 |journal=[[Revista de Derecho]] |publisher=[[Austral University of Chile]] |volume=IX |pages=25\u201334 |access-date=30 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nChile's new [[Constitution of Chile|constitution]] was approved in a national [[1980 Chilean constitutional referendum|plebiscite]] held on September 11, 1980.  The constitution was approved by 67% of voters under a process which has been described as \"highly irregular and undemocratic.\"<ref name=Hudson>Hudson, Rex A., ed. \"Chile: A Country Study.\" GPO for the Library of Congress. 1995. March 20, 2005 {{cite web |url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/cltoc.html |title=About this Collection &#124; Country Studies &#124; Digital Collections &#124; Library of Congress |accessdate=2012-05-24 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120524185929/lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/cltoc.html |archivedate=2012-05-24 }}</ref> Critics of the 1980 Constitution argue that the constitution was created not to build a democracy, but to consolidate power within the central government while limiting the amount of sovereignty allowed to the people with little political presence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mingaonline.uach.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-09502000000100003&script=sci_arttext|title=Revista de derecho (Valdivia) \u2013 Democracia y Constitucion en Chile|date=18 May 2015|accessdate=1 May 2018|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518062933/http://mingaonline.uach.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-09502000000100003&script=sci_arttext|archivedate=18 May 2015}}</ref> The constitution came into force on March 11, 1981.\n\n===Removal of C\u00e9sar Mendoza===\nIn 1985, due to the [[Caso Degollados]] scandal (\"case of the slit throats\"), General [[C\u00e9sar Mendoza]] resigned and was replaced by General [[Rodolfo Stange]].<ref name=\"newsbank\"/>\n\n===Youth policy===\nOne of the first measures of the dictatorship was to set up a Secretar\u00eda Nacional de la Juventud (SNJ, National Youth Office). This was done on October 28, 1973, even before the Declaration of Principles of the junta made in March 1974. This was a way of mobilizing sympathetic elements of the civil society in support for the dictatorship. SNJ was created by advise of [[Jaime Guzm\u00e1n]], being an example of the dictatorship adopting a [[Gremialismo|Gremialist]] thought.<ref name=Yanko2015>{{cite journal |last1=Gonz\u00e1lez |first1=Yanko |date=2015 |title=El \"Golpe Generacional\" y la Secretar\u00eda Nacional de la Juventud: purga, disciplinamiento y resocializaci\u00f3n de las identidades juveniles bajo Pinochet (1973\u20131980) |journal=[[Atenea]] |volume=512 |issue= 512|pages=10.4067/S0718\u201304622015000200006 |doi= 10.4067/S0718-04622015000200006|language=spanish |trans-title=The \"Generational Putsch\" and the National youth Office: Purge, disciplining and resocialization of youth identities under Pinochet (1973\u20131980) }}</ref> Some right-wing student union leaders like [[Andr\u00e9s Allamand]] were skeptical to these attempts as they were moulded from above and gathered disparate figures such as [[Miguel Kast]], [[Antonio Vodanovic]] and Jaime Guzm\u00e1n. Allamand and other young right-wingers also resented the dominance of the gremialist in SNJ, considering it a closed gremialist club.<ref>{{cite book |last=Allamnd |first=Andr\u00e9s |date=1999 |title=La Traves\u00eda del Desierto|language=Spanish |url= |location= |publisher=Editorial Alfaguara |pages=29\u201330 |isbn=978-956-239-078-1 |author-link=Andr\u00e9s Allamand }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1975 to 1980 the SNJ arranged a series of [[ritual]]ized acts in [[cerro Chacarillas]] reminiscent of [[Francoist Spain]]. The policy towards the sympathetic youth contrasted with the murder, surveillance and forced disappearances the dissident youth faced from the regime. Most of the documents of the SNJ were reportedly destroyed by the dictatorship in 1988.<ref name=Yanko2015/>\n\n===Women during the dictatorship===\nIn 1962 under the presidency of Christian Democrat Eduardo Freo Montalva, the women's section expanded pre-existing neighbourhood 'mothers' centres' (which initially helped women to purchase their own sewing machines) to help garner support for their social reforms amongst the poorer sections. By the end of the 1960s, there were 8,000 centres involving 400,000 members.<ref>Ximena Buster, 'Watch out for the little nazi man that all of have inside: The mobilization and demobilization of women in militarized Chile', Women's Studies International Forum, 11:5, p. 490.</ref>. Under Allende they were reorganised under the rubric National Confederation of Mothers' Centres (Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional de Centros de Madres, COCEMA) and leadership of his wife, Hortensia Bussi, to encourage community initiatives and implement their policies directed at women. <ref>Ximena Buster, 'Watch out for the little nazi man that all of have inside: The mobilization and demobilization of women in militarized Chile', Women's Studies International Forum, 11:5, p. 490; Fabiola Bahamondes Carrasco, 'Centros de Madres en el Chile rural. Un espacio de seguridad.' Revista Nomadias, 22, 2016, p. 89. </ref>\n\n==Opposition==\n\n=== Internal Opposition ===\n\n====Attacks on military personnel====\n{{further|Armed resistance in Chile (1973\u20131990)}}\nOne of the counter-Pinochet government organizations was named MIR, Movimiento de Izquierda Revolucionaria, and it conducted several operations against the Pinochet government until the late 1980s. MIR assassinated the head of the Army Intelligence school, Lieutenant Roger Vergara, with machine gun fire in the late 1970s. The MIR also executed an attack on the base of the Chilean Secret Police (Central Nacional de Informaciones, CNI), as well as several attempts on the lives of carabineros officials and a judge of the Supreme Court in Chile.<ref>Collier, Simon, and William F Sater. 1996. A History of Chile, 1808-1994. Cambridge Latin American Studies, 82. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</ref> Throughout the beginning years of the dictatorship the MIR was low-profile, but in August 1981 the MIR successfully killed the military leader of Santiago, General Carol Urzua Ibanez. Attacks on Chilean military official increased in the early 1980s, with the MIR killing several security forces personnel on a variety of occasions through extensive use of planted bombs in police stations or machine gun use<ref>Anderson, Sean, and Stephen Sloan. 2009. Historical Dictionary of Terrorism. 3Rd ed. Historical Dictionaries of War, Revolution, and Civil Unrest, 38. Lanham, Md.: Scarecrow Press.</ref>\n\nRepresenting a major shift in attitudes, the CPCh founded the [[Manuel Rodr\u00edguez Patriotic Front|FPMR]] in 14 December 1983, to engage in a violent armed struggle against the junta.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ensalaco |first1=Mark |title=Chile Under Pinochet : Recovering the Truth. |date=2000 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |location=Philadelphia |isbn=0812235207 |page=149}}</ref> Most notably the organisation attempted to assassinate Pinochet on the 7 September 1986 under 'Operation XX Century' but were unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite book |last1=O'Shaughnessy |first1=Hugh |title=Pinochet, the politics of torture |date=2000 |publisher=New York University Press |location=New York |isbn=0814762018 |page=121}}</ref> The group also assassinated the author of the 1980 Constitution, [[Jaime Guzm\u00e1n]] on 1 April 1991.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Roniger |first1=Luis |last2=Sznajder |first2=Mario |title=The Legacy of Human-Rights Violations in the Southern Cone: Argentina, Chile, and Uruguay |date=1999 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=9780198296157 |page=106}}</ref> They continued to operate throughout the 1990s, being designated as a terrorist organisation the [[U.S. Department of State]] and [[Mi6|MI6]], until supposedly ceasing to operate in 1999.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chile: Extremism & Counter-Extremism |url=https://www.counterextremism.com/countries/chile |website=Counter Extremism Project |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=8 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Church opposition to human rights violations====\n{{further|Vicariate of Solidarity}}The Catholic Church, which at first expressed its gratitude to the armed forces for saving the country from the horrors of a \"Marxist dictatorship\" became, under the leadership of Cardinal [[Ra\u00fal Silva Henr\u00edquez]], the most outspoken critic of the regime's social and economic policies.\n\nThe Catholic Church was symbolically and institutionally powerful within Chile. Domestically, it was the second most powerful institution, behind Pinochet's government. While the Church remained politically neutral, its opposition to the regime came in the form of human rights advocacy and through the social movements that it gave a platform to. It achieved this through the establishment of the Cooperative Committee for Peace in Chile (COPACHI) and Vicariate of Solidarity. COPACHI was founded by [[Cardinal Raul Silva Henriquez|Cardinal Raul Silve Henriquez]], Archbishop of Santiago, as an immediate response to the repression of the Pinochet regime. It was apolitical in a spirit of collaboration rather than conflict with the government. Pinochet developed suspicion of COPACHI, leading to its dissolution in late 1975. In response Silva founded the Vicariate in its place. Historian Hugo Fruhling's work highlights the multifaceted nature of Vicaria.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Corradi |first1=Juan |title=Fear at the Edge, State Terror and Resistance in Latin America |url=https://archive.org/details/fearatedgestatet00juan |url-access=registration |date=1992 |publisher=University of California Press |pages=[https://archive.org/details/fearatedgestatet00juan/page/121 121\u2013141]}}</ref> Through developments and education programs in the shantytown area of Santiago, the Vicaria had mobilised around 44,000 people to join campaigns by 1979. The Church published a newsletter called ''Solidarity'' published in Chile and abroad, and supplied the public with information through radio stations. Vicaria pursued a legal strategy of defending human rights, not a political strategy to re-democratise Chile.\n\n====Jornadas de Protesta Nacional====\n\nThe Days of National Protest ([[:es:Jornadas de Protesta Nacional|Jornadas de Protesta Nacional]]) were days of civil demonstrations that periodically took place in Chile in the 1980s against the military junta. They were characterized by street demonstrations in the downtown avenues of the city in the mornings, strikes during the day, and barricades and clashes in the periphery of the city throughout the night. The protests were faced with increased government repression from 1984, with the biggest and last protest summoned in July 1986. The protests changed the mentality of many Chileans, strengthening opposition organizations and movements in the 1988 plebiscite.\n\n=== External Opposition ===\n\n==== Solidarity Campaigns & Exiles Movements ====\nThe regime's forced exile of over 200,000 Chileans led to areas of global opposition to the Pinochet government. However, the exiles themselves were not entirely responsible for the international resistance against Pinochet, but rather were able to gain the solidarity of many members of their host countries. Exiles were dispersed across the globe, and to all continents, with different factions of leftist opposition finding refuge in like-minded host countries. For example, the militant revolutionary MIR centring their operations in Havana, Cuba. While the efforts of exiles across the globe in actually militarily or financially supporting the domestic opposition to the junta were limited in their effectiveness, the more important work of the exiles came in their efforts in mobilising support among citizens in their host countries. As such, The Chile Solidarity Campaign (CSC) in the UK was relatively successful at petitioning the labour government. This included lobbying host governments and international organisations such as the United Nations to condemn the abuses of the dictatorship. The overall effect of this was the successful creation of a global solidarity movement.\n\n==Economy and free market reforms==\n[[Image:Chile- el pueblo vencera cropped.jpg|thumb|[[Estadio Nacional de Chile]] as a [[concentration camp]] after the coup.]]\n{{Main|Economic history of Chile#1975-81}}\nAfter the military took over the government in 1973, a period of dramatic economic changes began. The Chilean economy was still faltering in the months following the coup. As the military junta itself was not particularly skilled in remedying the persistent economic difficulties, it appointed a group of Chilean economists who had been educated in the United States at the [[University of Chicago]]. Given financial and ideological support from Pinochet, the U.S., and international financial institutions, the [[Chicago Boys]] advocated ''[[laissez-faire]]'', [[free market|free-market]], [[neoliberalism|neoliberal]], and [[Conservatism#Fiscal conservatism|fiscally conservative]] policies, in stark contrast to the extensive [[nationalization]] and centrally-planned economic programs supported by Allende.<ref name=\"K. Remmer 1998 5-55\">{{cite journal\n | author = K. Remmer\n | year = 1998\n | title = '''Public Policy and Regime Consolidation: The First Five Years of the Chilean Junta'''\n | journal = Journal of the Developing Areas\n | volume =\n | issue =\n | pages = 5\u201355\n | id = \n | url =\n }}</ref> Chile was drastically transformed from an economy isolated from the rest of the world, with strong government intervention, into a liberalized, world-integrated economy, where market forces were left free to guide most of the economy's decisions.<ref name=\"K. Remmer 1998 5-55\"/>\n\nFrom an economic point of view, the era can be divided into two periods. The first, from 1975 to 1982, corresponds to the period when most of the reforms were implemented. The period ended with the international debt crisis and the collapse of the Chilean economy. At that point, unemployment was extremely high, above 20 percent, and a large proportion of the banking sector had become bankrupt. The following period was characterized by new reforms and economic recovery. Some economists argue that the recovery was due to an about-face turnaround of Pinochet's free market policy, since he nationalized many of the same industries that were nationalized under Allende and fired the Chicago Boys from their government posts.<ref>{{cite book\n| last = Valenzuela\n| first = Arturo\n| year = 2002\n| title = A Nation of Enemies\n| publisher = W. W. Norton\n| location =New York\n| id =\n}} p. 197-8</ref>\n\n===1975\u201381===\nChile's main industry, [[Chilean nationalization of copper|copper mining]], remained in government hands, with the [[Chilean constitution of 1980|1980 Constitution]] declaring them \"inalienable,\"<ref name=NLR>{{Cite journal | last = Riesco | first = Manuel | title = Is Pinochet dead? | journal = [[New Left Review]] | volume = II | issue = 47 | publisher = New Left Review | date = September\u2013October 2007 | url = http://newleftreview.org/II/47/manuel-riesco-is-pinochet-dead | ref = harv | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160124224407/http://newleftreview.org/II/47/manuel-riesco-is-pinochet-dead | archivedate = 2016-01-24 }} [http://newleftreview.org/article/download_pdf?language=es&id=2685 Spanish pdf.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308150245/https://newleftreview.org/article/download_pdf?language=es&id=2685 |date=2017-03-08 }} [http://newleftreview.org/article/download_pdf?language=it&id=2685 Italian pdf.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308142849/https://newleftreview.org/article/download_pdf?language=it&id=2685 |date=2017-03-08 }}</ref> but new mineral deposits were open to private investment.<ref name=NLR/> Capitalist involvement was increased, the [[Pensions in Chile|Chilean pension system]] and healthcare were privatized, and [[Education in Chile|Superior Education]] was also placed in private hands. One of the junta's economic moves was fixing the exchange rate in the early 1980s, leading to a boom in imports and a collapse of domestic industrial production; this together with a world recession caused a serious economic crisis in 1982, where GDP plummeted by 14%, and unemployment reached 33%. At the same time, a series of massive protests were organized, trying to cause the fall of the regime, which were efficiently repressed.\n\n===1982\u201383===\n{{Main|Crisis of 1982}}\nIn 1982-1983 Chile witnessed a severe economic crises with a surge in unemployment and a meltdown of the financial sector.<ref>Sebasti\u00e1n Edwards, Alejandra Cox Edwards: ''Monetarism and Liberalization: the Chilean Experiment.'' University of Chicago Press, 1991, S. xvii.</ref> 16 out of 50 financial institutions faced bankruptcy.<ref name=\"Fischer 329\">Karin Fischer: \"The Influence of Neoliberals in Chile before, during, and after Pinochet.\" In: P. Mirowski, D. Plehwe (Hrsg.): ''The Road from Mont P\u00e8lerin: The Making of the Neoliberal Thought Collective'', Harvard University Press, Cambridge/London 2009, S. 305\u2013346, hier S. 329.</ref> In 1982 the two biggest banks were nationalized to prevent an even worse [[credit crunch]]. In 1983 another five banks were nationalized and two banks had to be put under government supervision.<ref>Karin Fischer: \"The Influence of Neoliberals in Chile before, during, and after Pinochet\" In: P. Mirowski, D. Plehwe (Hrsg.): ''The Road from Mont P\u00e8lerin: The Making of the Neoliberal Thought Collective'', Harvard University Press, Cambridge/London 2009, p. 305\u2013346, hier S. 329.</ref> The central bank took over foreign debts. Critics ridiculed the economic policy of the [[Chicago Boys]] as \"Chicago way to socialism\".<ref>Robert G. Wesson: ''Politics, policies, and economic development in Latin America''. Hoover Press, 1984, {{ISBN|0-8179-8062-8}}, S. 8.</ref>\n\n===1984\u201390===\nAfter the economic crisis, [[Hern\u00e1n B\u00fcchi]] became Minister of Finance from 1985 to 1989, introducing a return to a free market economic policy. He allowed the peso to float and reinstated restrictions on the movement of capital in and out of the country. He deleted some [[bank regulation]]s, and simplified and reduced the corporate tax. Chile went ahead with privatizations, including public utilities and the re-privatization of companies that had briefly returned to government control during the 1982\u201383 crisis. From 1984 to 1990, Chile's gross domestic product grew by an annual average of 5.9%, the fastest on the continent. Chile developed a good export economy, including the export of fruits and vegetables to the northern hemisphere when they were out of season, and commanded high export prices.\n\n===Evaluation===\n\n[[Image:Economic growth of Chile.PNG|thumb|300px|Chilean (orange) and average Latin American (blue) rates of growth of GDP (1971\u20132007).]]\n\nInitially the economic reforms were internationally praised. [[Milton Friedman]] wrote in his ''Newsweek'' column on 25 January 1982 about the [[Miracle of Chile]]. British Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] credited Pinochet with bringing about a thriving, free-enterprise economy, while at the same time downplaying the junta's human rights record, condemning an \"organised international Left who are bent on revenge.\"\n\nWith the economic crises of 1982 the \"monetarist experiment\" was widely regarded a failure.<ref>Carlos Fortin: \"The Failure of Repressive Monetarism: Chile, 1973\u20131983\". In: ''Third World Quarterly'', vol. 6, no. 2 (Apr., 1984), p. 310\u2013326; Sebastian Edwards: \"Monetarism in Chile, 1973\u201383: Some Economic Puzzles\". In: ''Economic Development and Cultural Change'' vol. 34, no. 3 (April 1986), p. 535. Vgl. auch die Nachweise bei Jean Dr\u00e8ze, [[Amartya Sen|Amartya Kumar Sen]]: ''Hunger and Public Action''. Oxford University Press, 1991, p. 231.</ref>\n\nThe pragmatic economic policy after the crises of 1982 is appreciated for bringing constant economic growth.<ref>Enrique R. Carrasco: \"Autocratic Transitions to Liberalism: A Comparison of Chilean and Russian Structural Adjustment.\" In: ''Law and Contemporary Problems'', Bd. 5, S. 99\u2013126, hier S. 101, Fn. 5.</ref> It is questionable whether the radical reforms of the Chicago Boys contributed to post-1983 growth.<ref>J. M. Albala-Bertrand: \"Monetarism and Liberalization: The Chilean Experiment: With a New Afterword.\" In: ''The Economic Journal'', vol. 102, no. 414 (Sep., 1992), p. 1258\u20131260, p. 1259f; Jorge Nef: \"The Chilean Model Fact and Fiction.\" In: ''Latin American Perspectives.'' vol. 30, no. 5, (Sep., 2003), p. 16\u201340; Eduardo Silva: \"From Dictatorship to Democracy: The Business-State Nexus in Chile's Economic Transformation, 1975\u20131994.\" In: ''Comparative Politics'' vol. 28 (1996), p. 299\u2013320; Ricardo French-Davis: ''Economic Reforms in Chile: From Dictatorship to Democracy.'' University of Michigan Press: Ann Arbour, 2002.</ref> According to [[Ricardo Ffrench-Davis]], economist and consultant of the [[United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean]], the 1982 crises as well as the success of the pragmatic economic policy after 1982 proves that the 1975\u20131981 radical economic policy of the Chicago Boys actually harmed the Chilean economy.<ref>Helmut Wittelsb\u00fcrger, Albrecht von Hoff: [http://www.kas.de/wf/doc/kas_3585-544-1-30.pdf ''Chiles Weg zur Sozialen Marktwirtschaft.''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014172241/http://www.kas.de/wf/doc/kas_3585-544-1-30.pdf |date=2013-10-14 }} (PDF; 118&nbsp;kB); ''Konrad-Adenauer-Stiftung -Auslandsinfo.'' 1/2004, p. 97, 104.</ref>\n\n===Social consequences===\nThe economic policies espoused by the Chicago Boys and implemented by the junta initially caused several economic indicators to decline for Chile's lower classes.<ref name=\"K. Remmer 1998 3-29\">{{cite journal\n | author = K. Remmer\n | year = 1998\n | title = '''The Politics of Neoliberal Economic Reform in South America'''\n | journal =Studies in Comparative International Development\n | volume = 33\n | issue =2\n | pages = 3\u201329\n | id = Studies in Comparative International Development\n | url =\n | doi=10.1007/bf02687406\n }}</ref> Between 1970 and 1989, there were large cuts to incomes and social services.  Wages decreased by 8%.<ref name=\"Petras and Vieux 1998 57-72\">{{cite journal\n | author1 = James Petras\n | author2 = Steve Vieux\n | year = 1990\n | title = The Chilean \"Economic Miracle\": An Empirical Critique\n | journal = Critical Sociology\n | volume =\n | issue =\n | pages = 57\u201372\n | id = \n | url =\n | author1-link = James Petras\n }}</ref> Family allowances in 1989 were 28% of what they had been in 1970 and the budgets for education, health and housing had dropped by over 20% on average.<ref name=\"Petras and Vieux 1998 57-72\"/><ref>Sznajder, 1996</ref> The massive increases in [[military spending]] and cuts in funding to public services coincided with falling wages and steady rises in unemployment, which averaged 26% during the worldwide economic slump of 1982\u201385<ref name=\"Petras and Vieux 1998 57-72\"/> and eventually peaked at 30%.\n\nIn 1990, the LOCE act on education initiated the dismantlement of [[Education in Chile|public education]].<ref name=NLR/> According to Communist Party of Chile member and economist Manuel Riesco Larra\u00edn:\n\n<blockquote>Overall, the impact of neoliberal policies has reduced the total proportion of students in both public and private institutions in relation to the entire population, from 30 per cent in 1974 down to 25 per cent in 1990, and up only to 27 per cent today. If falling birth rates have made it possible today to attain full coverage at primary and secondary levels, the country has fallen seriously behind at tertiary level, where coverage, although now growing, is still only 32 per cent of the age group. The figure was twice as much in neighbouring [[Education in Argentina|Argentina]] and [[Education in Uruguay|Uruguay]], and even higher in developed countries\u2014[[Education in South Korea|South Korea]] attaining a record 98 per cent coverage. Significantly, tertiary education for the upper-income fifth of the Chilean population, many of whom study in the new private universities, also reaches above 70 per cent.<ref name=NLR/></blockquote>\n\nThe junta relied on the middle class, the oligarchy, domestic business, foreign corporations, and foreign loans to maintain itself.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=hzrwMb3UppYC&dq=Chile+under+pinochet&printsec=frontcover&source=bl&ots=-66tt8rEmg&sig=nSBX05IdsHb6lVMw141M4G7vYD0&hl=en&ei=he_tSYCpDJCgtgOD4YTjAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5] Chile under Pinochet: recovering the truth\n</ref>\nUnder Pinochet, funding of military and internal defence spending rose 120% from 1974 to 1979.<ref name=\"auto\">Remmer, 1989</ref>\nDue to the reduction in public spending, tens of thousands of employees were fired from other state-sector jobs.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\nThe oligarchy recovered most of its lost industrial and agricultural holdings, for the junta sold to private buyers most of the industries expropriated by Allende's Popular Unity government.\n\nFinancial conglomerates became major beneficiaries of the liberalized economy and the flood of foreign bank loans. Large foreign banks reinstated the credit cycle, as the Junta saw that the basic state obligations, such as resuming payment of principal and interest installments, were honored. International lending organizations such as the [[World Bank]], the [[International Monetary Fund]], and the [[Inter-American Development Bank]] lent vast sums anew.<ref name=\"Petras and Vieux 1998 57-72\"/>\nMany foreign multinational corporations such as [[International Telephone and Telegraph]] (ITT), [[Dow Chemical]], and [[Firestone Tire and Rubber Company|Firestone]], all expropriated by Allende, returned to Chile.<ref name=\"Petras and Vieux 1998 57-72\"/>\n\n==Foreign relations==\n{{Further|Foreign relations of Chile}}\nHaving risen to power on an anti-Marxist agenda, Pinochet found common cause with the military dictatorships of [[Bolivia]], [[Brazil]], [[Paraguay]], [[Uruguay]], and later, [[Argentine military junta|Argentina]]. The six countries eventually formulated a plan known as [[Operation Condor]], in which the security forces of participating states would target active Marxist subversives, guerrillas, and their alleged sympathizers in the allied countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/news/20010306/|title=Operation Condor|accessdate=25 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227063606/http://www2.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/news/20010306/|archivedate=27 February 2015}}</ref> Pinochet's government received tacit approval and material support from the United States. The exact nature and extent of this support is disputed. (''See'' [[Chilean coup of 1973#U.S. role in 1973 coup|U.S. role in 1973 Coup]], [[U.S. intervention in Chile]] and Operation Condor for more details.) It is known, however, that the American Secretary of State at the time, Henry Kissinger, practiced a policy of supporting coups in nations which the United States viewed as leaning toward Communism.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB123/chile.htm |title=Kissinger Telcons on Chile |accessdate=2007-09-19 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070912025948/http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB123/chile.htm |archivedate=2007-09-12 }} The Kissinger Telcons:\nKissinger Telcons on Chile</ref>\n\nThe new junta quickly broke diplomatic relations with [[Cuba]] and [[North Korea]], which had been established under the Allende government. Shortly after the junta came to power, several communist countries, including the [[Soviet Union]], [[North Vietnam]], [[East Germany]], [[People's Republic of Poland|Poland]], [[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic|Czechoslovakia]], [[People's Republic of Hungary|Hungary]], [[People's Republic of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]], and [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]], severed diplomatic relations with Chile however, [[Communist Romania|Romania]] and the [[China|People's Republic of China]] both continued to maintain diplomatic relations with Chile.<ref>J. Samuel Valenzuela and Arturo Valenzuela (eds.), ''Military Rule in Chile: Dictatorship and Oppositions'', p. 317</ref> Pinochet has nurtured his relationship with China.<ref>{{Cite news |title=U.S. and Others Gave Millions To Pinochet|newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=2004-12-07 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/07/business/us-and-others-gave-millions-to-pinochet.html |accessdate=2019-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=The Dictator|newspaper=[[The New Yorker]] |date=1998-10-19 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1998/10/19/the-dictator-2 |accessdate=2019-07-11}}</ref> The government broke diplomatic relations with [[Cambodia]] in January 1974<ref>''El Mercurio'', 20 January 1974</ref> and renewed ties with South Korea in October 1973{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} and with [[South Vietnam]] in March 1974.<ref>''El Mercurio'', 6 April 1975</ref> Pinochet attended the funeral of General [[Francisco Franco]], dictator of Spain from 1936\u201375, in late 1975.\n\nChile was on the brink of being invaded by Argentina, as the Argentina junta initiated [[Operation Soberania]] on 22 December 1978 because of the strategic [[Beagle Channel cartography since 1881|Picton, Lennox and Nueva]] islands at the southern tip of South America on the Beagle Canal. A full-scale war was prevented only by the call off of the operation by Argentina due to military and political reasons.<ref>See Alejandro Luis Corbacho ''\"Predicting the probability of war during brinkmanship crisis: The Beagle and the Malvinas conflicts\"'' {{cite news |title=Predicting the Probability of War During Brinkmanship Crises: The Beagle and the Malvinas Conflicts |ssrn = 1016843|date= September 2003|last1= Corbacho|first1= Alejandro}}  about the reasons of the call off (p.45): ''The newspaper Clar\u00edn explained some years later that such caution was based, in part, on military concerns. In order to achieve a victory, certain objectives had to be reached before the seventh day after the attack. Some military leaders considered this not enough time due to the difficulty involved in transportation through the passes over the Andean Mountains.'' and in cite 46: ''According to Clar\u00edn, two consequences were feared. First, those who were dubious feared a possible regionalization of the conflict. Second, as a consequence, the conflict could acquire great power proportions. In the first case decisionmakers speculated that Peru, Bolivia, Ecuador, and Brazil might intervene. Then the great powers could take sides. In this case, the resolution of the conflict would depend not on the combatants, but on the countries that supplied the weapons.''</ref> But the relations remained tense as Argentina invaded the Falklands ([[Operation Rosario]]). Chile along with [[Colombia]], were the only countries in South America to criticize the use of force by Argentina in its war with the UK over the [[Falkland Islands]]. Chile actually helped the United Kingdom during the war. The two countries (Chile and Argentina) finally agreed to papal mediation over the Beagle canal that finally ended in the [[Treaty of Peace and Friendship of 1984 between Chile and Argentina]] (''Tratado de Paz y Amistad''). Chilean sovereignty over the islands and Argentinian east of the surrounding sea is now undisputed.\n\nIn 1980, [[Philippines|Philippine]] President [[Ferdinand Marcos]] had invited the entire Junta (consisting at this point of Pinochet, Merino, Matthei, and Mendoza) to visit the country as part of a planned tour of Southeast Asia in an attempt to help improve their image and bolster military and economic relations with the Philippines, Japan, South Korea, and Hong Kong. Due to intense U.S. Pressure at the last minute (while Pinochet's plane was halfway en route over the Pacific), Marcos cancelled the visit and denied Pinochet landing rights in the country. Pinochet and the junta were further caught off guard and humiliated when they were forced to land in Fiji to refuel for the planned return to Santiago, only to be met with airport staff who refused to assist the plane in any way (the Fijian military was called in instead), invasive and prolonged customs searches, exorbitant fuel and aviation service charges, and hundreds of angry protesters who pelted his plane with eggs and tomatoes. The usually stoic and calm Pinochet became enraged, firing his Foreign Minister Hernan Cubillos, several diplomats, and expelling the Philippine Ambassador.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1980/04/02/filipino-rebuff-humiliates-pinochet/60da7bd2-b648-480f-909e-5651f5bea8ec/|title=Filipino Rebuff Humiliates Pinochet|first=Charles A.|last=Krause|date=2 April 1980|accessdate=1 May 2018|via=www.washingtonpost.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023175426/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1980/04/02/filipino-rebuff-humiliates-pinochet/60da7bd2-b648-480f-909e-5651f5bea8ec/|archivedate=23 October 2017}}</ref><ref>Helen Spooner, ''Soldiers in a narrow land: the Pinochet regime in Chile'', [https://books.google.com/books?hl=de&id=lE1G1OBhsbMC url]</ref>  Relations between the two countries were restored only in 1986 when [[Corazon Aquino]] assumed the presidency of the Philippines after Marcos was ousted in a non-violent revolution, the [[People Power Revolution]].\n\n===United States===\n{{Further|United States intervention in Chile}}\n[[File:Orlando Letelier, Washingron DC, 1976 (de Marcelo Montecino).jpg|thumb|right|[[Orlando Letelier]], a former Chilean minister, was assassinated in Washington, D.C. in 1976]]\n[[File:Nlc02585cs.jpg|thumb|Pinochet meeting with U.S. President [[Jimmy Carter]] in Washington, D.C., September 6, 1977]]\nThe U.S. government had been interfering in Chilean politics since 1961, and it spent millions trying to prevent Allende from coming to power, and subsequently undermined his presidency through financing opposition. Declassified C.I.A documents reveal U.S. knowledge and alleged involvement in the coup. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Kornbluh |first1=Peter |title=The Pinochet File |date=2013 |publisher=The New Press |location=New York |pages=1\u201378, 280\u2013281}}</ref> They provided material support to the military regime after the coup, although criticizing it in public. A document released by the U.S. [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) in 2000, titled \"CIA Activities in Chile\", revealed that the CIA actively supported the military junta during and after the overthrow of Allende and that it made many of Pinochet's officers into paid contacts of the CIA or U.S. military, even though some were known to be involved in human rights abuses.<ref name=\"NSA-2000-9-19\">Peter Kornbluh, [http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/news/20000919/ CIA Acknowledges Ties to Pinochet\u2019s Repression Report to Congress Reveals U.S. Accountability in Chile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128142216/http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/news/20000919/ |date=2006-11-28 }}, Chile Documentation Project, National Security Archive, September 19, 2000. Accessed online November 26, 2006.</ref>\nThe U.S. continued to give the ''junta'' substantial economic support between the years 1973\u201379, despite concerns from more liberal Congressmen, as seen from the results of the [[Church Committee]]. U.S. public stance did condemn the human rights violations, however declassifies documents reveal such violations were not an abstacle for members of the Nixon and Ford administrations. [[Henry Kissinger]] visited Santiago in 1976 for the annual conference of the [[Organisation of American States]]. During his visit he privately met with Pinochet and reassured the leader of internal support from the U.S. administration.<ref>{{cite web |title=memorandum of conversation, Kissinger and Pinochet |url=https://www.hsdl.org/?view&did=438484 |website=Homeland Security Digital Library |publisher=Gerald Ford Library |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> \nThe U.S. went beyond verbal condemnation in 1976, after the murder of [[Letelier case|Orlando Letelier]] in Washington D.C., when it placed an embargo on arms sales to Chile that remained in effect until the restoration of democracy in 1989. This more aggressive stance coincided with the election of [[Jimmy Carter]] who shifted the focus of U.S. foreign policy towards human rights.\n\n===United Kingdom===\nBritain's initial reaction to the overthrowing of Allende was one of caution. The Conservative government recognised the legitimacy of the new government, but didn't offer any other declarations of support.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alborada.net/watts-heath-uk-pinochet-chile-0913/|title=Business As Usual: Britain's Heath Government and Chile's 9/11|last=Watts|first=Josh|website=Alborada|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n\nUnder the [[Labour government, 1974\u20131979|Labour government of 1974-79]], Britain's relations with Chile were cordial, if not close. While [[United Kingdom|Britain]] regularly condemned the junta at the United Nations for its human rights abuses, bilateral relations between the two were not affected to the same degree.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wilkinson|first=Michael D.|date=1992|title=The Chile Solidarity Campaign and British Government Policy towards Chile, 1973-1990|journal=Revista Europea de Estudios Latinoamericanos y del Caribe / European Review of Latin American and Caribbean Studies|issue=52|pages=57\u201374|issn=0924-0608|jstor=25675537}}</ref> Britain formally withdrew its Santiago ambassador in 1974, however reinstated the position in 1980 under the [[Margaret Thatcher]] government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/1980/oct/14/chile-diplomatic-representation-and-arms|title=CHILE: DIPLOMATIC REPRESENTATION AND ARMS SALES (Hansard, 14 October 1980)|website=api.parliament.uk|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n\nChile was officially neutral during the [[Falkland War]], but the Chilean US-built Westinghouse long-range radar deployed at Punta Arenas, in southern Chile, gave the British task force early warning of Argentinian air attacks, which allowed British ships and troops in the war zone to take defensive action.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.margaretthatcher.org/speeches/displaydocument.asp?docid=108383|title=Speech on Pinochet at the Conservative Party Conference|accessdate=25 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225225857/http://www.margaretthatcher.org/speeches/displaydocument.asp?docid=108383|archivedate=25 February 2015}}</ref> Margaret Thatcher said that the day the radar was taken out of service for overdue maintenance was the day Argentinian fighter-bombers bombed the troopships ''Sir Galahad'' and ''Sir Tristram'', leaving approximately 50 dead and 150 wounded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmforces.co.uk/training/articles/1834-the-falklands-conflict-part-5---battles-of-goose-green-stanley|title=The Falklands Conflict Part 5 \u2013 Battles of Goose Green & Stanley HMFORCES.CO.UK|website=hmforces.co.uk|accessdate=1 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306095759/http://www.hmforces.co.uk/training/articles/1834-the-falklands-conflict-part-5---battles-of-goose-green-stanley|archivedate=6 March 2012}}</ref> According to Chilean Junta and former Air Force commander Fernando Matthei, Chilean support included military intelligence gathering, radar surveillance, British aircraft operating with Chilean colours and the safe return of British special forces, among other things.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.mercopress.com/2005/09/03/us-support-to-uk-in-falklands-war-was-decisive|title=US support to UK in Falklands' war was decisive|work=MercoPress|accessdate=25 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225225342/http://en.mercopress.com/2005/09/03/us-support-to-uk-in-falklands-war-was-decisive|archivedate=25 February 2015}}</ref> In April and May 1982, a squadron of mothballed RAF Hawker Hunter fighter bombers departed for Chile, arriving on 22 May and allowing the Chilean Air Force to reform the No. 9 \"Las Panteras Negras\" Squadron. A further consignment of three frontier surveillance and shipping reconnaissance Canberras left for Chile in October. Some authors suggest that Argentina might have won the war had she been allowed to employ the VIth and VIIIth Mountain Brigades, which remained guarding the Andes mountain chain.<ref>Nicholas van der Bijl and David Aldea, 5th Infantry Brigade in the Falklands , p. 28, Leo Cooper 2003</ref> Pinochet subsequently visited [[Margaret Thatcher]] for tea on more than one occasion.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6167351.stm | work=BBC News | title=Pinochet death 'saddens' Thatcher | date=December 11, 2006 | accessdate=April 28, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070615014947/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6167351.stm | archivedate=June 15, 2007 }}</ref> Pinochet's controversial relationship with Thatcher led [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] to mock Thatcher's [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] as \"the party of Pinochet\" in 1999.\n\n===France===\n{{Further|Operation Condor}}\nAlthough France received many Chilean political refugees, it also secretly collaborated with Pinochet. French journalist [[Marie-Monique Robin]] has shown how [[Val\u00e9ry Giscard d'Estaing]]'s government secretly collaborated with [[National Reorganization Process|Videla's junta]] in Argentina and with Augusto Pinochet's regime in Chile.<ref>[http://www.algeria-watch.org/fr/article/div/livres/escadrons_mort_conclusion.htm Conclusion] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303184912/http://www.algeria-watch.org/fr/article/div/livres/escadrons_mort_conclusion.htm |date=2016-03-03 }} of [[Marie-Monique Robin]]'s ''Escadrons de la mort, l'\u00e9cole fran\u00e7aise'' {{in lang|fr}}/ [http://www.mefeedia.com/entry/2926696/ Watch here film documentary] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522013436/http://www.mefeedia.com/entry/2926696/ |date=2009-05-22 }} (French, English, Spanish)</ref>\n\n[[Greens (France)|Green]] deputies [[No\u00ebl Mam\u00e8re]], [[Martine Billard]] and [[Yves Cochet]] on September 10, 2003 requested a Parliamentary Commission on the \"role of France in the support of military regimes in Latin America from 1973 to 1984\" before the Foreign Affairs Commission of the National Assembly, presided by [[Edouard Balladur]]. Apart from ''[[Le Monde]]'', newspapers remained silent about this request.<ref>[http://www.lemonde.fr/cgi-bin/ACHATS/acheter.cgi?offre=ARCHIVES&type_item=ART_ARCH_30J&objet_id=820135 MM. Giscard d'Estaing et Messmer pourraient \u00eatre entendus sur l'aide aux dictatures sud-am\u00e9ricaines], ''[[Le Monde]]'', September 25, 2003 {{in lang|fr}}</ref> However, deputy [[Roland Blum]], in charge of the Commission, refused to hear Marie-Monique Robin, and published in December 2003 a 12 pages report qualified by Robin as the summum of bad faith. It claimed that no agreement had been signed, despite the agreement found by Robin in the ''[[Quai d'Orsay]]''<ref>\u00ab S\u00e9rie B. Am\u00e9rique 1952-1963. Sous-s\u00e9rie : Argentine, n\u00b0 74. Cotes : 18.6.1. mars 52-ao\u00fbt 63 \u00bb.</ref><ref>[http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/12/rapports/r1295.asp RAPPORT FAIT AU NOM DE LA COMMISSION DES AFFAIRES \u00c9TRANG\u00c8RES SUR LA PROPOSITION DE R\u00c9SOLUTION (n\u00b0 1060), tendant \u00e0 la cr\u00e9ation d'une commission d'enqu\u00eate sur le r\u00f4le de la France dans le soutien aux r\u00e9gimes militaires d'Am\u00e9rique latine entre 1973 et 1984, PAR M. ROLAND BLUM] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150405204244/http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/12/rapports/r1295.asp |date=2015-04-05 }}, [[French National Assembly]] {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\nWhen then Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Dominique de Villepin]] traveled to Chile in February 2004, he claimed that no cooperation between France and the military regimes had occurred.<ref>[http://www.lemonde.fr/cgi-bin/ACHATS/acheter.cgi?offre=ARCHIVES&type_item=ART_ARCH_30J&objet_id=838522 Argentine : M. de Villepin d\u00e9fend les firmes fran\u00e7aises], ''[[Le Monde]]'', February 5, 2003 {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\n===Peru===\nReportedly one of [[Juan Velasco Alvarado]]'s main goal was to militarily reconquer the lands lost by Peru to Chile in the [[War of the Pacific]].<ref name=PCOLSorpresa>[http://www.caretas.com.pe/2004/1826/articulos/chile.html \"La veces que Pinochet casi Ataca al Per\u00fa de Sorpresa\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202185713/http://www.caretas.com.pe/2004/1826/articulos/chile.html |date=2008-12-02 }}. caretas.com. June 3, 2004.</ref> It is estimated that from 1970 to 1975 Peru spent up to 2 Billion USD (roughly 20 Billion USD in 2010's valuation) on Soviet armament.<ref name=utexas/> According to various sources Velasco's government bought between 600 and 1200 [[T-55]] Main Battle Tanks, [[Armoured personnel carrier|APC]]s, 60 to 90 [[Sukhoi 22]] warplanes, 500,000 assault rifles, and even considered the purchase of a British carrier [[Centaur class aircraft carrier|''Centaur''-class]] [[aircraft carrier|light fleet carrier]] [[HMS Bulwark (R08)|HMS Bulwark]].<ref name=utexas>{{cite web|url=http://www.ford.utexas.edu/library/guides/guidecollectionsa-m.asp|title=Gerald R. Ford Presidential Library and Museum|website=www.ford.utexas.edu|accessdate=1 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924014600/http://www.ford.utexas.edu/library/guides/guidecollectionsa-m.asp|archivedate=24 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe enormous amount of weaponry purchased by Peru caused a meeting between former US Secretary of State [[Henry Kissinger]] and Pinochet in 1976.<ref name=utexas/> Velasco's military plan was to launch a massive sea, air, and land invasion against Chile.<ref name=utexas/> In 1999, [[General Pinochet]] claimed that if [[Peru]] had attacked [[Chile]] during 1973 or even 1978, [[Peruvian]] forces could have penetrated deep south into Chilean territory, possibly military taking the Chilean city of [[Copiap\u00f3]] located half way to [[Santiago]].<ref name=\"PCOLSorpresa\"/> The Chilean Armed Forces considered launching a [[preventive war]] to defend itself. Though, Pinochet's Chilean Air Force General [[Fernando Matthei]] opposed a preventive war and responded that \"I can guarantee that the Peruvians would destroy the Chilean Air Force in the first five minutes of the war\".<ref name=\"PCOLSorpresa\"/> Some analysts believe the fear of attack by Chilean and US officials as largely unjustified but logical for them to experience, considering the Pinochet dictatorship had come into power with a coup against democratically elected president [[Salvador Allende]]. According to sources, the alleged invasion scheme could be seen from the Chilean's government perspective as a plan for some kind of leftist counterattack.<ref>[http://www.caretas.com.pe/2004/1826/articulos/chile.html \"La veces que Pinochet casi Ataca al Per\u00fa de Sorpresa\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202185713/http://www.caretas.com.pe/2004/1826/articulos/chile.html |date=2008-12-02 }}, ''Caretas'', June 3, 2004 {{in lang|es}}</ref> While acknowledging the Peruvian plans were revisionistic scholar Kalevi J. Holsti claim more important issues behind were the \"ideological incompatibility\" between the regimes of Velasco Alvarado and Pinochet and that Peru would have been concerned about Pinochet's [[geopolitics|geopolitical]] views on Chile's need of naval [[hegemony]] in the Southeastern Pacific.<ref name=Holsti>{{cite book |last=Holsti |first=Kalevi J.|date=1996 |title=The State, War and the State of War |url= |location= |publisher=Cambridge Studies in International Relations |page=158 |isbn=}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Chileans should stop with the bullshit or tomorrow I shall eat breakfast in Santiago.}}{{center|\u2014Juan Velasco Alvarado<ref name=\"masterson-mil-228-229\">{{cite book|title=Militarism and politics in Latin America: Peru from S\u00e1nchez Cerro to Sendero Luminoso|author=Masterson, Daniel M. |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=1991|isbn=978-0-313-27213-4|pages=228\u2013229|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YYm4wmXl2M4C&pg=PA228}}</ref>}}\n\n===Spain===\n[[Francoist Spain]] had enjoyed warm relations with Chile while Allende was in power. Pinochet admired and was very much influenced by [[Francisco Franco]], but Franco's successors had a cold attitude towards Pinochet as they did not want to be linked to him.<ref>{{cite book |last=Fermandois |first=Joaqu\u00edn |date= |title=Chile. La b\u00fasqueda de la democracia. |volume=5|issue=1960\u20132010 |chapter=Chile en el mundo |location= |page= |isbn=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Corbatta |first=Jorgelina |date= |title=Remapping the Humanities: Identity, Community, Memory, (post)modernity |volume=1 |chapter=The Pinochet Affair in London and Spain |location= |page=125 |isbn=}}</ref> When Pinochet traveled to the funeral of Francisco Franco in 1975 the President of France [[Val\u00e9ry Giscard d'Estaing]] pressured the Spanish government to refuse Pinochet to be at the crowning of [[Juan Carlos I of Spain]] by letting Spanish authorities know that Giscard would not be there if Pinochet was present. Juan Carlos I personally called Pinochet to let him know he was not welcome at his crowning.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ced\u00e9o Alvarado |first=Ernesto |date=February 4, 2008 |title=Rey Juan Carlos abochorn\u00f3 a Pinochet |url=http://www.panamaamerica.com.pa/content/rey-juan-carlos-abochorn%C3%B3-pinochet |newspaper=Panam\u00e1 Am\u00e9rica |access-date=April 4, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419125814/http://www.panamaamerica.com.pa/content/rey-juan-carlos-abochorn%C3%B3-pinochet |archivedate=April 19, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Foreign aid===\nThe previous drop in foreign aid during the Allende years was immediately reversed following Pinochet's ascension; Chile received US$ $322.8 million in loans and credits in the year following the coup.<ref>Petras & Morley, 1974</ref> There was considerable international condemnation of the military regime's human rights record, a matter that the United States expressed concern over as well after [[Orlando Letelier]]'s 1976 assassination in Washington DC.([[Kennedy Amendment]], later ''International Security Assistance and Arms Export Control Act of 1976'').\n\n===Cuban involvement===\n{{see also|Armed resistance in Chile (1973\u20131990)}}\nAfter the Chilean military coup in 1973, Fidel Castro promised Chilean revolutionaries far-reaching aid. Initially Cuban support for resistance consisted of clandestine distribution of funds to Chile, human rights campaigns at the UN to isolate the Chilean dictatorship, and efforts to undermine US-Chilean bilateral relations. Eventually Cuba's policy changed to arming and training insurgents. Once their training was completed, Cuba helped the guerrillas return to Chile, providing false passports and false identification documents.<ref>Tanya Harmer, 'The View from Havana: Chilean Exiles in Cuba and Early Resistance to Chile's Dictatorship's, Hispanic American Historical Review 1 (2016), 109-13</ref> Cuba's official newspaper, [[Granma (newspaper)|Granma]], boasted in February 1981 that the \"Chilean Resistance\" had successfully conducted more than 100 \"armed actions\" throughout Chile in 1980. By late 1980, at least 100 highly trained [[Revolutionary Left Movement (Chile)|MIR]] guerrillas had reentered Chile and the MIR began building a base for future guerrilla operations in [[Neltume]], a mountainous forest region in [[Zona Sur|southern Chile]]. In a massive operation spearheaded by Chilean Army Para-Commandos, security forces involving some 2,000 troops, were forced to deploy in the Neltume mountains from June to November 1981, where they destroyed two MIR bases, seizing large caches of munitions and killing a number of MIR commandos.\nIn 1986, Chilean security forces discovered 80 tons of munitions, including more than three thousand M-16 rifles and more than two million rounds of ammunition, at the tiny fishing harbor of [[Carrizal Bajo]], smuggled ashore from Cuban fishing trawlers off the coast of Chile.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ohmynews.com/articleview/article_view.asp?menu=c10400&no=315665&rel_no=1|title=The Day Pinochet Nearly Died |publisher= OhmyNews International|website=english.ohmynews.com|accessdate=1 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229150650/http://english.ohmynews.com/articleview/article_view.asp?menu=c10400&no=315665&rel_no=1|archivedate=29 February 2012}}</ref> The operation was overseen by Cuban naval intelligence, and also involved the Soviet Union. Cuban Special Forces had also instructed the FPMR guerrillas that ambushed President Augusto Pinochet's motorcade on 8 September 1986, killing five bodyguards and wounding 10.<ref>Castro's Secrets, Brian Latell, p. 125, Macmillan, 2013</ref>\n\n==Cultural life==\n[[Image:Charango player.jpg|right|thumb|[[Charango]], a musical instrument banned by the dictatorship.]]\n{{see also|Book burnings in Chile}}\nInfluenced by [[Antonio Gramsci]]'s work on [[cultural hegemony]], proposing that the ruling class can maintain power by controlling cultural institutions, Pinochet clamped down on cultural dissidence.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Taffet |first1=Jeffrey |title=\"My Guitar is Not for the Rich\": The New Chilean Song Movement and the Politics of Culture |journal=Journal of American Culture |date=1997 |volume=20 |issue=2 |page=92 |doi=10.1111/j.1542-734X.1997.2002_91.x |language=es}}</ref> This brought Chilean cultural life into what sociologist [[Soledad Bianchi]] has called a \"cultural blackout\".<ref name=Morris>Morris, Nancy. 1986. Canto Porque es Necesario Cantar: The New Song Movement in Chile, 1973-1983. ''[[Latin American Research Review]]'', Vol. 21, pp. 117\u2013136.</ref> The government censored non-sympathetic individuals while taking control of mass media.<ref name=Morris/> The formerly thriving [[Nueva canci\u00f3n|Nueva canci\u00f3n scene]] suffered from the exile or imprisonment of many bands and individuals.<ref name=Morris/> A key musician, [[V\u00edctor Jara]], was tortured and killed by elements of the military.<ref name=Morris/> According to [[Eduardo Carrasco]] of [[Quilapay\u00fan]] in the first week after the coup, the military organized a meeting with folk musicians where they announced that the traditional instruments [[charango]] and [[quena]] were banned.<ref name=Morris/> [[Nueva Cancion]] resurfaced in Chile once again in 1975 due to the efforts of musicians who had been active before the coup. This was music of resistance and solidarity, a style that aimed to keep the memory of the Allende years alive.\n\nThe 1980s saw an invasion of [[Argentine rock]] bands into Chile. These included [[Charly Garc\u00eda]], the [[Enanitos Verdes]], [[G.I.T.]] and [[Soda Stereo]] among others.<ref>Torres Quezada, Rodrigo Guillermo. 2007. [http://www.tesis.uchile.cl/tesis/uchile/2007/torres_r/sources/torres_r.pdf El imaginario de rebeld\u00eda y disconformidad a trav\u00e9s de la m\u00fasica rock en los a\u00f1os \u00b490. Desadaptados/as chilenos/as dejan su mensaje.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116074357/http://www.tesis.uchile.cl/tesis/uchile/2007/torres_r/sources/torres_r.pdf |date=2014-01-16 }}</ref>\nContemporary Chilean rock group [[Los Prisioneros]] complained against the ease with which Argentine Soda Stereo made appearances on Chilean TV or in Chilean magazines and the ease they could obtain musical equipment for concerts in Chile.<ref name=Fuentes>Fuentes, Jorge. [http://www.guioteca.com/los-80/la-historica-rivalidad-de-los-prisioneros-y-soda-stereo-%C2%BFquien-gano/ La hist\u00f3rica rivalidad de Los Prisioneros y Soda Stereo, \u00bfqui\u00e9n gan\u00f3?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118123450/http://www.guioteca.com/los-80/la-historica-rivalidad-de-los-prisioneros-y-soda-stereo-%C2%BFquien-gano/ |date=2015-11-18 }}, retrieved on December 12, 2012.</ref> Soda Stereo was invited to [[Vi\u00f1a del Mar International Song Festival]] while Los Prisioneros were ignored despite their popular status.<ref name=\"musicapop\"/> This situation was because Los Prisioneros were censored by media under the influence of the military dictatorship.<ref name=Fuentes/><ref name=\"musicapop\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.musicapopular.cl/3.0/index2.php?op=Artista&id=315 \n |title=Los Prisioneros \n |last=Leiva \n |first=Jorge \n |work=La enciclopedia de la m\u00fasica chilena en Internet \n |publisher=Musicapopular.cl \n |accessdate=2012-11-29 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017034327/http://www.musicapopular.cl/3.0/index2.php?op=Artista&id=315 \n |archivedate=2012-10-17 \n}}</ref> Los Prisioneros' marginalization by the media was further aggravated by their call to vote against the dictatorship on the [[1988 Chilean national plebiscite|plebiscite of 1988]].<ref name=\"musicapop\"/>\n{{quote box |width = 22em |quote = For Chile to become once again the [[land of poets]], and not the land of murderers!|source = \u2014[[Sol y Lluvia]]<ref>[[Sol y Lluvia]] on a live recording of their song \"Voy a hacer el amor\"</ref>}}\n\nExperimental theatre groups from [[Universidad de Chile]] and [[Pontifical Catholic University of Chile]] were restricted by the military regime to performing only theatre classics.<ref name=Pop>{{Citation |last=Richards |first=Keith |year=2005 |title=Pop culture Latin America!: media, arts, and lifestyle |location= |pages=121\u2013122 |url= |accessdate= }}</ref> Some established groups like ''Grupo Ictus'' were tolerated while new formations like ''Grupo Aleph'' were repressed. This last group had its members jailed and forced into exile after performing a parody on the [[1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref name=Pop/> In the 1980s a [[grassroots]] street theatre movement emerged.<ref name=Pop/>\n\nThe dictatorship promoted the figure of Nobel laureate [[Gabriela Mistral]] who was presented as a symbol of \"summission to the authority\" and \"social order\".<ref>{{cite news|date=June 7, 2003|title=Gabriela Mistral: poeta y lesbiana|url=http://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-995948|work=El Tiempo|access-date=June 23, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903031354/http://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-995948|archivedate=September 3, 2017}}</ref> \n{{clear}}\n\n==Plebiscite and the Return to Democracy==\n{{Main|Chilean return to democracy}}\n\n===1988 Plebiscite===\nFollowing the approval of the [[Constitution of Chile|1980 Constitution]], a [[1988 Chilean national plebiscite|plebiscite was scheduled for October 5, 1988]], to vote on a new eight-year presidential term for Pinochet.\n\nThe Constitution, which took effect on 11 March 1981, established a \"transition period,\" during which Pinochet would continue to exercise executive power and the Junta legislative power, for the next eight years. Before that period ended, a candidate for President was to be proposed by the Commanders-in-Chief of the Armed Forces and Carabinero Chief General for the following period of eight years. The candidate was to be ratified by registered voters in a national plebiscite. On 30 August 1988 Pinochet was declared to be the candidate.<ref>David Altma, \u201cLatin America\u201d, Referendums Around the World, 2018</ref>\n\nThe [[Constitutional Court of Chile]] ruled that the plebiscite should be carried out as stipulated by Article 64 in the Constitution. That included an \"Electoral Space\" during which all positions, in this case, two, ''S\u00ed'' (yes), and ''No'', would have two free slots of equal and uninterrupted TV time, simultaneously broadcast by all TV channels, with no political advertising outside those spots. The allotment was scheduled in two off-prime time slots: one before the afternoon news and the other before the late-night news, from 22:45 to 23:15 each night (the evening news was from 20:30 to 21:30, and prime time from 21:30 to 22:30). The opposition ''No'' campaign, headed by [[Ricardo Lagos]], produced colorful, upbeat programs, telling the Chilean people to vote against the extension of the presidential term. Lagos, in a TV interview, pointed his index finger towards the camera and directly called on Pinochet to account for all the \"disappeared\" persons. The ''S\u00ed'' campaign did not argue for the advantages of extension, but was instead negative, claiming that voting \"no\" was equivalent to voting for a return to the chaos of the UP government.\n\nPinochet lost the 1988 referendum, where 56% of the votes rejected the extension of the presidential term, against 44% for \"''S\u00ed''\", and, following the constitutional provisions, he stayed as President for one more year.  The [[1989 Chilean presidential election|presidential election]] was held in December 1989, at the same time as congressional elections that were due to take place. Pinochet left the presidency on March 11, 1990 and transferred power to political opponent [[Patricio Aylwin]], the new democratically elected president. Due to the same transitional provisions of the constitution, Pinochet remained as Commander-in-Chief of the Army, until March 1998.\n\n===1989 General Elections===\nFrom the 1989 elections onwards the military had officially left the political sphere in Chile. Pinochet did not endorse any candidate publicly. Former Pinochet economic minister [[Hern\u00e1n B\u00fcchi]] ran for president as candidate of the two right-wing parties [[National Renewal (Chile)|RN]] and [[Independent Democratic Union|UDI]]. He had little political experience and was relatively young and credited with Chile's good economic performance in the second half of the 1980s. The right-wing parties faced several problems in the elections: there was considerable infighting between RN and UDI, B\u00fcchi had only very reluctantly accepted to run for president and right-wing politicians struggled to define their position towards the Pinochet regime. In addition to this [[right-wing populist]] [[Francisco Javier Err\u00e1zuriz Talavera]] ran independently for president and made several election promises B\u00fcchi could not match.<ref name=AngellPollack1990/>\n\nThe centre-left coalition [[Concertaci\u00f3n]] was more united and coherent. Its candidate [[Patricio Aylwin]], a [[Christian Democratic Party (Chile)|Christian Democrat]], behaved as if he had won and refused a second television debate with B\u00fcchi. B\u00fcchi attacked Aylwin on a remark he had made concerning that inflation rate of 20% was not much and he also accused Aylwin of making secret agreements with the [[Communist Party of Chile]], a party that was not part of Concertaci\u00f3n.<ref name=AngellPollack1990/> Aylwin spoke with authority about the need to clarify human rights violations but did not confront the dictatorship for it; in contrast, B\u00fcchi, as a former regime minister, lacked any credibility when dealing with human right violations.<ref name=AngellPollack1990/>\n\nB\u00fcchi and Err\u00e1zuriz lost to [[Patricio Aylwin]] in the election. The electoral system meant that the largely Pinochet-sympathetic right was overrepresented in parliament in such a way that it could block any reform to the constitution. This over-representation was crucial for UDI in obtaining places in parliament and securing its political future. The far-left and the far-right performed poorly in the election.<ref name=AngellPollack1990/>\n\n===Presidential Election Results===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n! Candidate\n! Party/coalition\n! Votes\n! %\n|-\n! align=\"left\" | [[Patricio Aylwin]] || align=\"left\" | [[Christian Democrat Party of Chile|PDC]]/[[Coalition of Parties for Democracy|CPD]] || 3,850,571 || 55.17\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[Hern\u00e1n B\u00fcchi]] || align=\"left\" | [[Independent (politics)|Independent]]/[[Alliance (Chile)|D&P]] || 2,052,116 || 29.40\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[Francisco Javier Err\u00e1zuriz Talavera|Francisco Javier Err\u00e1zuriz]] || align=\"left\" | Independent || 1,077,172 || 15.43\n|- style=\"font-weight: bold; background: #ececec;\"\n| align=\"left\" colspan=\"2\" | Valid votes || 6,979,859 || 100.00\n|-\n| align=\"left\" colspan=\"2\" | Null votes || 103,631 || 1.45 \n|-\n| align=\"left\" colspan=\"2\" | Blank votes || 75,237 || 1.05\n|- style=\"font-weight: bold; background: #ececec;\"\n| align=\"left\" colspan=\"2\" | Total votes || 7,158,727 || 100.00\n|-\n| align=\"left\" colspan=\"2\" | Registered voters/turnout || 7,557,537 || 94.72\n|-\n| align=\"left\" colspan=\"4\" | <small>Source: [http://historico.servel.cl/SitioHistorico/index1989_pres.htm Tricel via Servel]</small>\n|}\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Memorial Detenidos Desaparecidos R\u00e9gimen Militar Chile.jpg|thumb|Memorial to the people who were [[Forced disappearance|disappeared]] during the Pinochet's regime]] \nFollowing the restoration of Chilean democracy and during the successive administrations that followed Pinochet, the Chilean economy has prospered, and today the country is considered a Latin American success story. Unemployment stands at 7% as of 2007, with poverty estimated at 18.2% for the same year, both relatively low for the region.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ci.html#Econ |title=The World Factbook |publisher=Cia.gov |accessdate=2014-08-18 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923081816/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ci.html#Econ |archivedate=2017-09-23 }}</ref> However, in 2019 the Chilean government faced public scrutiny for its economic policies. In particular, for the long-term effects of Pinochet\u2019s neoliberal policies. <ref>[https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/11/05/chile-ongoing-protests-pinochet-dictatorship-looms-large/ Ongoing Protests Show That Pinochet\u2019s Dictatorship Still Looms Large in Chilean Politics<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Mass protests broke out throughout Santiago, due to increasing prices of the metro ticket.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-50106743 Chile protests: Unrest in Santiago over metro fare increase - BBC News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> For many Chileans this highlighted the disproportionate distribution of wealth amongst Chile.  \n\nThe \"Chilean Variation\" has been seen as a potential model for nations that fail to achieve significant economic growth.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=I7VgAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Chilean+Variation%22&dq=%22Chilean+Variation%22 |title=Australian Slavonic and East European Studies: Journal of the Australian and ...  |via=Books.google.com |date=2008-04-23 |accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref> The latest is Russia, for whom [[David Christian (historian)|David Christian]] warned in 1991 that \"dictatorial government presiding over a transition to capitalism seems one of the more plausible scenarios, even if it does so at a high cost in human rights violations.\"<ref>Christian, 1992</ref>\n\nA survey published by pollster CERC on the eve of the 40th anniversary commemorations of the coup gave some idea of how Chileans perceived the dictatorship. According to the poll, 55% of Chileans regarded the 17 years of dictatorship as either bad or very bad, while 9% said they were good or very good.<ref>(https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-24014501)</ref> In 2013, the newspaper El Mercurio asked Chileans if the state had done enough to compensate victims of the dictatorship for the atrocities they suffered; 30% said yes, 36% said no, and the rest were undecided.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-24014501 |title = Chile still split over Pinochet legacy|work = BBC News|date = 2013-09-09|last1 = Long|first1 = Gideon}}</ref> In order to keep the memories of the victims and the disappeared alive, memorial sites have been constructed throughout Chile, as a symbol of the country\u2019s past. Some notable examples include Villa Grimaldi, Londres 38, Paine Memorial and the Museum of Memory and Human Rights. <ref>Katrien Klep: Tracing collective memory: Chilean truth commissions and memorial sites, in: Memory Studies 3 (2012), p. 259-269 </ref> These memorials were built by family members of the victims, the government and ex-prisoners of the dictatorship. These have become popular tourist destinations and have provided a visual narrative of the atrocities of the dictatorship. These memorials have aided in Chile\u2019s reconciliation process, however, there is still debate amongst Chile as to whether these memorials do enough to bring the country together. \n\nThe relative economic success of the Pinochet dictatorship has brought about some political support for the former dictatorship. In 1998, then-Brazilian congressman and retired military officer [[Jair Bolsonaro]] praised Pinochet, saying his regime \"should have killed more people\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Jair Bolsonaro: The would-be dictator who might soon rule Brazil |url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/world/2018/10/jair-bolsonaro-the-would-be-dictator-who-might-soon-rule-brazil.html |work=[[Newshub]] |date=8 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nEvery year on the anniversary of the coup, Chile becomes more polarised and protests can be seen throughout the country.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2013/09/11/world/americas/chile-coup-anniversary/index.html On 40th anniversary of Chile coup, divisions remain - CNN<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Leftist supporters use this day to honour the victims of the dictatorship and highlight the atrocities for which the perpetrators still haven\u2019t been brought to justice. \n\nThe indictment and arrest of Pinochet occurred on 10 October 1998 in London. He returned to Chile in March 2000 but was not charged with the crimes against him. On his 91st birthday on 25 November 2006, in a public statement to supporters, Pinochet for the first time claimed to accept \"political responsibility\" for what happened in Chile under his regime, though he still defended the [[Chilean coup of 1973|1973 coup]] against Salvador Allende. In a statement read by his wife Lucia Hiriart, he said, ''Today, near the end of my days, I want to say that I harbour no rancour against anybody, that I love my fatherland above all. ... I take political responsibility for everything that was done''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/6184696.stm|title=Pinochet 'takes responsibility'|publisher=BBC News \u2013 Americas|accessdate=25 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225182728/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/6184696.stm|archivedate=25 February 2015|date=2006-11-25}}</ref> Despite this statement, Pinochet always [[Augusto Pinochet's arrest and trial|refused to be confronted to Chilean justice]], claiming that he was senile. He died two weeks later while indicted on human rights and corruption charges, but without having been sentenced.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* [[John R. Bawden|Bawden, JR.]] (2016). ''The Pinochet Generation: The Chilean Military in the Twentieth Century'', Tuscaloosa: University of Alabama Press.\n* [[David Christian (historian)|Christian, D.]] (1992). \"Perestroika and World History\", ''Australian Slavonic and East European studies'', 6(1), pp.&nbsp;1\u201328.\n* [[Mark Falcoff|Falcoff, M.]] (2003). \"Cuba: The Morning After\", p.&nbsp;26. AEI Press, 2003.\n* [[James Petras|Petras, J.]], & Vieux, S. (1990). \"The Chilean 'Economic Miracle': An Empirical Critique\", ''Critical Sociology'', 17, pp.&nbsp;57\u201372.\n* Roberts, K.M. (1995). \"From the Barricades to the Ballot Box: Redemocratization and Political Realignment in the Chilean Left\", ''Politics & Society'', 23, pp.&nbsp;495\u2013519.\n* Schatan, J. (1990). \"The Deceitful Nature of Socio-Economic Indicators\". ''Development'', 3-4, pp.&nbsp;69\u201375.\n* Sznajder, M. (1996). \"Dilemmas of economic and political modernisation in Chile: A jaguar that wants to be a puma\", ''Third World Quarterly'', 17, pp.&nbsp;725\u2013736.\n* Valdes, J.G. (1995). ''Pinochet's economists: The Chicago School in Chile'', Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.\n* Steve Anderson [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928020337/http://www.tcgnews.com/santiagotimes/index.php?nav=story&story_id=8732&topic_id=1 Body of Chile's Former President Frei May Be Exumed], ''The Santiago Times'', April 5, 2005\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.vitalpoetics.com/wounds-of-humanity-in-diamela-eltits-the-sacred-cow-and-the-fourth-world Literature and Torture in Pinochet's Chile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091004110250/http://www.memoriaviva.com/culpables/criminales%20p/pinochet.htm Criminals of the military dictatorship : Augusto Pinochet]\n\n{{1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat}}\n{{Augusto Pinochet}}\n{{Chile topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Military Government Of Chile (1973-90)}}\n[[Category:Military dictatorship of Chile (1973\u20131990)| ]]\n[[Category:1970s in Chile]]\n[[Category:1980s in Chile]]\n[[Category:1973 establishments in Chile]]\n[[Category:1990 disestablishments in Chile]]\n[[Category:Augusto Pinochet]]\n[[Category:Former polities of the Cold War]]\n[[Category:Military dictatorships|Chile]]\n[[Category:Political history of Chile]]\n[[Category:Former member states of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1973]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1990]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Former Country\n|native_name          = ''Rep\u00fablica de Chile''\n|conventional_long_name = Republic of Chile\n|common_name          = Chile\n|era                  = Cold War\n|event_start          = [[1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat|Coup d'et\u00e1t]]\n|year_start           = 1973\n|date_start           = September 11,\n|event1               = [[Constitution of Chile|Constitution]]\n|date_event1          = March 11, 1981\n|event2               = [[1988 Chilean national plebiscite|Plebiscite]]\n|date_event2          = October 5, 1988\n|event_end            = [[Chilean transition to democracy|Transition to democracy]]\n|year_end             = 1990\n|date_end             = March 11,\n|p1                   = Presidential Republic (1925\u201373)\n|flag_p1              = Flag of Chile.svg\n|s1                   = Chilean transition to democracy\n|flag_s1              = Flag of Chile.svg\n|image_flag           = Flag of Chile.svg\n|image_coat           = Coat of arms of Chile.svg\n|image_map            = CHL_orthographic_(%2Ball_claims).svg\n|national_motto       = ''[[List of national mottos|Por la raz\u00f3n o la fuerza]]''<br />{{small|(\"Through Reason Or By Force\")}}\n|national_anthem      = ''[[Himno Nacional de Chile]]''<br />{{small|(\"National Anthem of Chile\")}}\n|common_languages     = [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n|government_type      = [[Unitary state|Unitary]] [[Authoritarianism|authoritarian]] [[military dictatorship]]\n|capital              = [[Santiago]]\n|leader1              = Augusto Pinochet\n|year_leader1         = 1974\u201390\n|title_leader         = [[President of Chile|President]]\n|representative1      = Augusto Pinochet\n|representative2      = Jose Toribio Merino\n|year_representative1 = 1974\u201381\n|year_representative2 = 1981\u201390\n|title_representative = [[Government Junta of Chile (1973)|President of the Junta]]\n|legislature          = [[Government Junta of Chile (1973)|Government Junta]]\n|stat_pop1            = 10,095,485\n|stat_year1           = 1973\n|stat_pop2            = 11,178,817\n|stat_year2           = 1980\n|stat_pop3            = 13,187,821\n|stat_year3           = 1990\n|currency             = {{nowrap|[[Chilean escudo]] {{small|(1973\u201375)}}<br />[[Chilean peso]] {{small|(1975\u201390)}}}}\n|demonym=|area_km2=756,096.3|area_rank=37th|GDP_PPP=|GDP_PPP_year=|HDI=0.640|HDI_year=1980}}\n{{History of Chile}}\nThe '''military dictatorship of Chile''' ({{lang-es|dictadura militar de Chile}}) was an authoritarian military regime that ruled [[Chile]] for seventeen years, between September 11, 1973 and March 11, 1990. The dictatorship was established after the [[Presidency of Salvador Allende|democratically-elected socialist government]] of [[Salvador Allende]] was overthrown in a [[1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]] on 11 September 1973. During this time, the country was ruled by a [[Government Junta of Chile (1973)|military junta]] headed by General [[Augusto Pinochet]]. The military used the alleged breakdown of democracy and the economic crisis that took place during Allende's presidency to justify its seizure of power. The dictatorship presented its mission as a \"national reconstruction.\" The coup was the result of multiple forces, including pressure from conservative and women\u2019s groups, certain political parties, union strikes and other domestic unrest, as well as international factors. According to an article written by lifelong CIA operative [[Jack Devine]], although it was widely reported that the CIA was directly involved in orchestrating and carrying out the coup, subsequently released sources suggest a much reduced role of the US government.<ref>Jack Devine & Peter Kornbluh, 'Showdown in Santiago: What Really Happened in Chile?', Foreign Affairs 93 (2014), 168-174.</ref>\n\nThe regime was characterized by the systematic suppression of political parties and the persecution of dissidents to an extent unprecedented in the [[history of Chile]]. Overall, the regime left over 3,000 dead or missing, tortured tens of thousands of prisoners,<ref name=\"BBC-Chile\">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/country_profiles/1222764.stm |title=Country profile: Chile |work=BBC News |date=16 December 2009 |accessdate=31 December 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114035710/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/country_profiles/1222764.stm |archivedate=14 January 2010 }}</ref> and drove an estimated 200,000 Chileans into exile.<ref>{{Citation\n| last1            = Wright\n| first1           = T.C.\n| last2            = O\u00f1ate\n| first2           = R.\n| contribution     = Chilean Diaspora\n| editor-last1     = Ember\n| editor-first1    = M.\n| editor-last2     = Ember\n| editor-first2    = C.R.\n| editor-last3     = Skoggard\n| editor-first3    = I.\n| title            = Encyclopedia of Diasporas: Immigrant and Refugee Cultures Around the World\n| volume           = II\n| pages            = 57\u201365\n| place            = \n| date = 2005\n| contribution-url = \n}}</ref> The dictatorship's effects on Chilean political and economic life continue to be felt. Two years after its ascension radical [[neoliberal]] economic reforms were implemented, in sharp contrast to Allende's leftist policies, advised by a team of free-market economists educated in US universities known as the [[Chicago Boys]]. Later, in 1980, the regime replaced the [[Chilean Constitution of 1925]] with a [[Constitution of Chile|new constitution]]. This established a series of provisions that would eventually lead to the [[1988 Chilean national plebiscite]] on October 5 of that year.\n\nIn that referendum, the Chilean people denied Pinochet a new mandate, opening the way for the [[Chilean transition to democracy|reestablishment of democracy in 1990]]. Consequently, democratic presidential elections were held the following year. The military dictatorship ended in 1990 with the election of [[Christian Democratic Party (Chile)|Christian-Democrat]] candidate [[Patricio Aylwin]]. However, the military remained out of civilian control for several years after the junta itself had lost power.<ref name=AngellPollack1990>{{cite journal |last=Angell |first=Alan |last2=Pollack |first2=Benny |date=1990 |title=The Chilean Elections of 1989 |journal=[[Bulletin of Latin American Research]] |publisher=Society for Latin American Studies |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201323 |doi= 10.2307/3338214|jstor=3338214 }}</ref>\n\n==Rise to power==\n{{main|1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat}}\n\nThere has been a large amount of debate over the extent of US government involvement in destabilising the Allende government.<ref>{{Citation|last=Harmer|first=Tanya|chapter=Rebellion|date=2011-10-10|pages=73\u2013106|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|isbn=9780807834954|doi=10.5149/9780807869246_harmer.8|title=Allende's Chile and the Inter-American Cold War}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=The Pinochet File: A Declassified Dossier on Atrocity and Accountability|doi = 10.1163/2468-1733_shafr_sim180020010}}</ref> Recently declassified documents show evidence of communication between the Chilean military and US officials, suggesting covert US involvement in assisting the military\u2019s rise to power. Some key figures in the [[Presidency of Richard Nixon|Nixon administration]], such as [[Henry Kissinger]], used the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) to mount a major destabilization campaign.<ref name=autogenerated1>Citation error. See inline comment how to fix. {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/888821672 by a bug in VisualEditor and later identified by a bot. The original cite can be found around Special:Permalink/888821482 (or in a rev close to it) as cite #6 - find and verify the cite and replace this template with it (2). [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> As the CIA revealed in 2000, \"In the 1960s and the early 1970s, as part of the US Government policy to try to influence events in Chile, the CIA undertook specific covert action projects in Chile ... to discredit Marxist-leaning political leaders, especially Dr. Salvador Allende, and to strengthen and encourage their civilian and military opponents to prevent them from assuming power.\"<ref>Citation error. See inline comment how to fix. {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/888821672 by a bug in VisualEditor and later identified by a bot. The original cite can be found around Special:Permalink/888821482 (or in a rev close to it) as cite #7 - find and verify the cite and replace this template with it (2). [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> The CIA worked with right-wing Chilean politicians, military personnel, and journalists to undermine socialism in Chile.<ref>Citation error. See inline comment how to fix. {{verify source |date=September 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted Special:Diff/888821672 by a bug in VisualEditor and later identified by a bot. The original cite can be found around Special:Permalink/888821482 (or in a rev close to it) as cite #8 - find and verify the cite and replace this template with it (2). [[User:GreenC_bot/Job_18]]}}</ref> One reason for this was financial, as many US businesses had investments in Chile, and Allende\u2019s socialist policies included the nationalisation of Chile\u2019s major industries. Another reason was the propagandized fear of the spread of communism, which was particularly important in the context of the Cold War. The rationale was that US feared that Allende would promote the spreading of Soviet influence in their \u2018backyard\u2019.<ref>{{Citation|last=Harmer|first=Tanya|chapter=Rebellion|date=2011-10-10|volume=|pages=258\u2013259|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|isbn=9780807834954|doi=10.5149/9780807869246_harmer.8|title=Allende's Chile and the Inter-American Cold War}}</ref> However, the fact that Allende's peaceful path was toward Socialism\u2014not Communism\u2014and because of the vested interests of the U.S. copper industry in Chile, the rationale had more to do with U.S. financial interests. As early as 1963, the U.S. via the CIA and U.S. multinationals such as ITT intervened in Chilean politics using a variety of tactics and millions of dollars to interfere with elections, ultimately helping plan the coup against Allende.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nieto |first1=Clara |title=Masters of War: Latin America and U.S. Aggression |date=2003 |publisher=Seven Stories Press |location=New York |pages=295\u2013299}}</ref><ref name=\"Kornbluh\">{{cite book |last1=Kornbluh |first1=Peter |title=The Pinochet File: A Declassified Dossier on Atrocity and Accountability |date=2013 |publisher=The New Press |location=New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Walkowitz |first1=Daniel J. |title=\"Foreign Policy Failures and Dilemmas\" in Social History of the United States |publisher=ABC-CLIO |pages=364\u2013381}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April 1973, workers from the [[El Teniente]] mining camp had ceased working, demanding higher wages. The strike lasted 76 days and cost the government severely in lost revenues. One of the strikers, Luis Bravo Morales, was shot dead in [[Rancagua]] city. On June 29, the Blindados No. 2 tank regiment under the command of Colonel [[Roberto Souper]], attacked [[La Moneda]], Chile's presidential palace. Instigated by the anti-Marxist militia [[Patria y Libertad]] (\"''country and freedom''\"), the armoured cavalry soldiers hoped other units would be inspired to join them. Instead, armed units led by generals [[Carlos Prats]] and [[Augusto Pinochet]] quickly put down the coup attempt. In late July, 40,000 truckers, squeezed by price controls and rising costs, tied up transportation in a nationwide strike that lasted 37 days, costing the government $6 million USD a day.<ref>''Historical Dictionary of Chile'', Salvatore Bizzarro, p. 34, Scarecrow Press, 2005</ref> Two weeks before the coup, public dissatisfaction with rising prices and food shortages led to protests like the one at the Plaza de la Constituci\u00f3n which had been dispersed with tear gas.<ref>\"[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,907929-8,00.html The Bloody End of a Marxist Dream] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111111142339/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,907929-8,00.html |date=2011-11-11 }}\". ''Time Magazine''. 24 September 1973.</ref> Allende also clashed with Chile's largest circulation newspaper ''[[El Mercurio]]''. Tax-evasion charges were trumped up against the newspaper and its director arrested.<ref>''Authoritarian Regimes in Latin America: Dictators, Despots, and Tyrants'', Paul H. Lewis, p. 204, Rowman & Littlefield, 2006</ref> The Allende government found it impossible to control inflation, which grew to more than 300 percent by September,<ref>''Latin America in the Era of the Cuban Revolution'', Thomas C. Wright, p. 139, Greenwood Publishing Group, 2001</ref> further dividing Chileans over the Allende government and its policies.\n\nUpper- and middle-class right-wing women also played an important role in destabilising the Allende government. They co-ordinated two prominent opposition groups called ''[[:es:Poder Femenino|El Poder Feminino]]'' (\"''female power''\"), and ''Solidaridad, Orden y Liberdad'' (\"''solidarity, order, and freedom''\").<ref>{{Cite journal|last=de los Angeles Crummett|first=Mar\u00eda|date=October 1977|title=El Poder Feminino: the Mobilization of Women Against Socialism in Chile|journal=Latin American Perspectives|volume=4|issue=4|pages=103\u2013113|doi=10.1177/0094582x7700400407|issn=0094-582X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|date=October 2003|title=<sc>Margaret Power</sc>. <italic>Right-Wing Women in Chile: Feminine Power and the Struggle against Allende 1964\u20131973</italic>. University Park, Penn.: Pennsylvania State University Press. 2002. Pp. xxii, 311. Cloth $65.00, paper $25.00|journal=The American Historical Review|doi=10.1086/ahr/108.4.1192|issn=1937-5239}}</ref> These women who opposed Allende felt as though their fundamental values of family and motherhood were being threatened by Marxism. Furthermore, the economic chaos that Allende\u2019s regime was seeing meant that there were struggles to buy food and thus look after their families. Allende\u2019s regime therefore threatened the most important aspect of a woman\u2019s role. These women used many tactics to destabilise the Allende regime. They carried out the \u2018[https://www.encyclopedia.com/humanities/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/march-empty-pots March of the Empty Pots and Pans]\u2019 in December 1971, and emasculated the military. These women criticised the military for being \u2018cowards\u2019 for not getting rid of Allende, arguing that they were not carrying out their role of protecting Chilean women.\n\nOn August 22, 1973, the [[Chamber of Deputies of Chile|Chamber of Deputies]] passed, by a vote of 81 to 47, a resolution calling for President Allende to respect the constitution. The measure failed to obtain the two-thirds majority in the [[Senate of Chile|Senate]] constitutionally required to convict the president of abuse of power, but the resolution still represented a challenge to Allende's legitimacy. The military were staunch supporters of the constitution and therefore believed that Allende had lost legitimacy as Chile\u2019s leader.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=PASSMORE|first=LEITH|date=August 2018|title=John R. Bawden, The Pinochet Generation: The Chilean Military in the Twentieth Century (Tuscaloosa, AL: University of Alabama Press, 2016), pp. x + 288, $49.95, $49.95 E-book|journal=Journal of Latin American Studies|volume=50|issue=3|pages=746\u2013747|doi=10.1017/s0022216x18000469|issn=0022-216X}}</ref> As a result, reacting to widespread public demand for intervention, the military began planning for a military coup which would ultimately take place on September 11, 1973. Contrary to popular belief, Pinochet was not the mastermind behind the coup. It was, in fact, naval officers who first decided that military intervention was necessary to remove President Allende from power.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Chile: The Pinochet Decade|last=O\u2019Brien|first=Phillip|last2=Roddick|first2=Jacqueline|date=January 1983|publisher=Latin America Bureau|isbn=9780906156186|location=Rugby, Warwickshire, United Kingdom|doi=10.3362/9781909013599|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/chilepinochetdec0000obri}}</ref> Army generals were unsure of Pinochet\u2019s allegiances, as he had given no prior indication of disloyalty to Allende, and thus was only informed of these plans on the evening of 8 September, just three days before the coup took place.<ref>{{Citation|last=O\u2019Shaugnessy|first=Hugh|chapter=3. Treason and Terror|date=January 2000|pages=49\u2013118|publisher=Latin America Bureau|isbn=9781899365418|doi=10.3362/9781909013384.003|title=Pinochet}}</ref> On 11 September 1973, the military launched a coup, with troops surrounding La Moneda Palace. Allende died that day of [[Death of Salvador Allende|suspected suicide]].\n\nThe military installed themselves in power as a [[Government Junta of Chile (1973)|Military Government Junta]], composed of the heads of the Army, Navy, Air Force and Carabineros (police). Once the Junta was in power, General [[Augusto Pinochet]] soon consolidated his control over the government. Since he was the commander-in-chief of the oldest branch of the military forces (the Army), he was made the titular head of the junta, and soon after [[President of Chile]]. Once the junta had taken over, the United States immediately recognized the new regime and helped it consolidate power.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n==Dictatorship violence==\n\n===Suppression of political activity===\n[[Image:Quema de libros.jpg|thumb|[[Book burnings in Chile|Book burning in Chile]] following the [[1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat|1973 coup]] that installed the Pinochet regime.]]\n\nOn September 13, the junta dissolved the Congress and outlawed or suspended all political activities in addition to suspending the [[Chilean Constitution of 1925|1925 constitution]]. All political activity was declared \"in recess\". The Government Junta immediately banned the socialist, Marxist and other [[left-wing politics|leftist]] parties that had constituted former President Allende's [[Popular Unity (Chile)|Popular Unity]] coalition<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leychile.cl/Navegar?idNorma=5730|title=DL-77 13-OCT-1973 Ministerio del Interior |publisher= Ley Chile \u2013 Biblioteca del Congreso Nacional|work=leychile.cl|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029200802/http://www.leychile.cl/Navegar?idNorma=5730|archivedate=2013-10-29|date=1973-10-13 }}</ref> and began a systemic campaign of imprisonment, torture, harassment and/or murder against the perceived opposition. [[Eduardo Frei Montalva|Eduardo Frei]], Allende's predecessor as president, initially supported the coup along with his Christian Democratic colleagues. However, they later assumed the role of a loyal opposition to the military rulers. Though they soon lost most of their influence they were subjected to the same treatment that the UP members had been before them.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}} During 1976-77, this repression even reached independent and Christian Democrat labour leaders who had supported the coup, several were exiled.<ref>{{Citation|chapter=Introduction|date=2004|pages=1\u201313|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0-8223-3309-8|doi=10.1215/9780822385851-001|title=Victims of the Chilean Miracle}}</ref> Christian Democrats like [[Radomiro Tomic]] were jailed or forced into exile.<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/666903512.html?dids=666903512:666903512&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&date=Dec+12%2C+1982&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Pinochet+Forms+Panel+to+Consider+Return+of+Chileans+Sent+Into+Exile&pqatl=google] Pinochet Forms Panel to Consider Return of Chileans Sent Into Exile</ref><ref>[http://www.elpais.com/articulo/agenda/CHILE/Radomiro/Tomic/politico/chileno/elpepigen/19920104elpepiage_1/Tes] Radomiro Tomic, pol\u00edtico chileno</ref>  Retired military personnel were named rectors of universities and they carried out vast purges of suspected left-wing sympathisers.<ref>{{Citation|last=Power|first=Jonathan|title=Ending War Crimes, Chasing the War Criminals|chapter=The Pinochet Case|date=2017-01-01|publisher=Brill {{!}} Nijhoff|isbn=978-90-04-34634-5|doi=10.1163/9789004346345_010}}</ref> With such strong repression, the Catholic church became the only public voice allowed within Chile. By 1974, the Commission of Peace had established a large network to provide information to numerous organisations regarding human rights abuses in Chile. As a result of this, Manuel Contreras, Director of DINA, threatened Cardinal Silva Henriquez that his safety could be at risk if the Church continued to interfere which in turn resulted in death threats and intimidation from agents of the regime.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aguilar|first=Mario I.|date=2003|title=Cardinal Raul Silva Henriquez, the Catholic Church, and the Pinochet Regime, 1973-1980: Public Responses to a National Security State|journal=The Catholic Historical Review|volume=89|issue=4|pages=712\u2013731|doi=10.1353/cat.2003.0183|issn=1534-0708}}</ref>  \n\nA key provision of the new constitution of 1980 aimed at eliminating leftist factions, \u201coutlawed the propagation of doctrines that attack the family or put forward a concept of society based on the class struggle\u201d. Pinochet maintained strict command over the armed forces thus he could depend on them to censor the media, arrest opposition leaders and repress demonstrations. This was accompanied by a complete shutting down of civil society with curfews, prohibition of public assembly, press blackouts, draconian censorship and universities were purged.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pratt|first=M. L.|date=1996-01-01|title=Overwriting Pinochet: Undoing the Culture of Fear in Chile|journal=Modern Language Quarterly|volume=57|issue=2|pages=151\u2013163|doi=10.1215/00267929-57-2-151|issn=0026-7929}}</ref> \n\n===Human rights violations===\n{{Further|Human rights in Chile|Human rights violations in Pinochet's Chile}}\n\nThe military rule was characterized by systematic suppression of all political dissidence. Scholars later described this as a \"[[politicide]]\" (or \"political genocide\").<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=xzW2-dMwfCMC&pg=PA303&lpg=PA303&dq=Sznajder,+1996+chile&source=bl&ots=cbMoAau_kv&sig=cgl1Tmvq9pffECAO1zlujDv5Z7I&hl=en&ei=1entSdbaIo-SMuLC8QM&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1] The legacy of human-rights violations in the Southern Cone</ref> Steve J. Stern spoke of a politicide to describe \"a systematic project to destroy an entire way of doing and understanding politics and governance.\"<ref name=Stern>{{cite book\n  | last = Stern\n  | first = Steve J.\n  | title = Remembering Pinochet's Chile\n  | publisher = Duke University Press\n  | year = 2004\n  | pages = 32, 90, 101, 180\u2013181\n  | isbn = 978-0822333548}}</ref>\n\nEstimates of figures for victims of state violence vary and are highly contested. [[Rudolph Rummel]] estimates 10,000 killed during Pinochet's regime, with 30,000 being the highest possible number.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mega.nu:8080/ampp/rummel/postwwii.tab.gif|title=Table 4: Democide Rank Ordered (1970\u20131979)|last=RJ|first=Rummel|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215847/http://www.mega.nu:8080/ampp/rummel/postwwii.tab.gif|archivedate=2013-10-04|url-status=live}}</ref> Rummel notes an estimate by Sivard that 3,000 miners were killed by the Chilean army in a dispute in 1987.<ref>[http://www.hawaii.edu/powerkills/SOD.TAB15.1A.GIF Table 15.1A] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005061447/http://www.hawaii.edu/powerkills/SOD.TAB15.1A.GIF|date=2012-10-05}} in {{cite book|url=http://www.hawaii.edu/powerkills/NOTE5.HTM|title=Statistics of Democide|last=Rummel|first=RJ|publisher=School of Law, University of Virginia|year=1997|location=Charlottesville|accessdate=23 March 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313062609/http://www.hawaii.edu/powerkills/NOTE5.HTM|archivedate=13 March 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Other sources place the number of all the victims of the dictatorship as high as 15,000 killed and 2,000 disappeared.<ref>Graham, 1990; cited in Johnson 2006, p. 85</ref> In 1996, human rights activists announced they had presented another 899 cases of people who had disappeared or been killed during the dictatorship, taking the total of known victims to 3,197, of whom 2,095 were reported killed and 1,102 missing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sun_sentinel/doc/388555201.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug%2023,%201996&author=Sun-Sentinel%20wire%20services&pub=South%20Florida%20Sun%20-%20Sentinel&edition=&startpage=&desc=GUNMEN%20THREATEN%20MEDIA|title=Gunmen Threaten Media|publisher=Sun-Sentinel (Archives)|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225224936/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/sun_sentinel/doc/388555201.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug%2023,%201996&author=Sun-Sentinel%20wire%20services&pub=South%20Florida%20Sun%20-%20Sentinel&edition=&startpage=&desc=GUNMEN%20THREATEN%20MEDIA|archivedate=25 February 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=25 February 2015}}</ref> Following the return to democracy with the Concertacion government, the [[Rettig Commission]], a multipartisan effort by the Aylwin administration to discover the truth about the human-rights violations, listed a number of torture and detention centers (such as [[Colonia Dignidad]], [[Esmeralda (BE-43)|the ship ''Esmeralda'']] or [[V\u00edctor Jara Stadium]]), and found that at least 3,200 people were killed or disappeared by the regime. Later, the 2004 [[Valech Report]] confirmed the figure of 3,200 deaths but reduced the estimated number of disappearances. It tells of some 28,000 arrests in which the majority of those detained were incarcerated and in a great many cases tortured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minvu.cl/ingles/opensite_20070320074217.aspx|title=Valech Report |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322143320/http://www.minvu.cl/ingles/opensite_20070320074217.aspx|archivedate=2015-03-22|url-status=live|accessdate=2014-08-26}}</ref> In 2011, the Chilean government officially recognized 36,948 survivors of torture and political imprisonment, as well as 3,095 people killed or disappeared at the hands of the military government.<ref>[http://www.omaha.com/article/20110818/AP15/308189901 Controversial victims on Chile's official list, by Eva Vergara, Omaha World-Herald, August 18, 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20131002040217/http://www.omaha.com/article/20110818/AP15/308189901|date=October 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe worst violence occurred within the first three months of the coup, with the number of suspected leftists killed or \"[[Forced disappearance|disappeared]]\" (''desaparecidos'') reaching several thousand.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/1109861.stm|title=Finding Chile's disappeared|date=2001-01-10|accessdate=2010-01-05|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217123536/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/1109861.stm|archivedate=2009-02-17|url-status=live}} BBC: Finding Chile's disappeared</ref> In the days immediately following the coup, the Assistant Secretary of State for Inter-American Affairs informed [[Henry Kissinger]] that the [[Estadio Nacional de Chile|National Stadium]] was being used to hold 5,000 prisoners. Between the day of the coup and November 1973, as many as 40,000 political prisoners were held there<ref>{{cite journal|last=G\u00f3mez-Barris|first=Macarena|year=2010|title=Witness Citizenship: The Place of Villa Grimaldi in Chilean Memory|journal=Sociological Forum|volume=25|issue=1|page=34|doi=10.1111/j.1573-7861.2009.01155.x}}</ref><ref name=\"ElPaisStadium\">{{cite news|url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/deportes/campo/concentracion/Pinochet/cumple/anos/elpepudep/20081203elpepudep_19/Tes|title=El campo de concentraci\u00f3n de Pinochet cumple 70 a\u00f1os|author=|date=3 December 2008|newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]]}}</ref> and as late as 1975, the CIA was still reporting that up to 3,811 were imprisoned there.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4-RfeEIeKRkC&pg=PA38&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Thinking about Terrorism|last1=Tigar|first1=Michael E.|year=2007|isbn=9781590318423|accessdate=25 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225182326/http://books.google.es/books?id=4-RfeEIeKRkC&pg=PA38&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|archivedate=25 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> 1,850 of them were killed, another 1,300 are still missing to this day.<ref name=\"ElPaisStadium\" /> Some of the most famous cases of ''desaparecidos'' are [[Charles Horman]], a U.S. citizen who was killed during the coup itself,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB33/index.html|title=New Information on the Murders of U.S. Citizens Charles Horman and Frank Teruggi by the Chilean Military|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111019205138/http://www.gwu.edu/%7Ensarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB33/index.html|archivedate=2011-10-19|url-status=live|accessdate=2011-11-19}} New Information on the Murders of U.S. Citizens Charles Horman and Frank Teruggi by the Chilean Military</ref> Chilean songwriter [[V\u00edctor Jara]], and the October 1973 [[Caravan of Death]] (''Caravana de la Muerte'') where at least 70 persons were killed.\n\nLeftist guerrilla groups and their sympathizers were also hit hard during the military regime. The MIR commander, [[Andr\u00e9s Pascal Allende]], has stated that the Marxist guerrillas lost 1,500\u20132,000 fighters killed or disappeared.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bJ2-wUrZn8IC&pg=PA155&dq=|title=Los Allende|last1=Wessel|first1=G\u00fcnther|year=2004|isbn=9788473602020|accessdate=25 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130915020906/http://books.google.es/books?id=bJ2-wUrZn8IC&pg=PA155&dq=|archivedate=15 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Among the killed and disappeared during the military regime were at least 663 MIR guerrillas.<ref name=\"archivochile.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.archivochile.com/Derechos_humanos/doc_gen_ddhh/hhdddocgen0002.pdf|title=Caidos del Mir en Diferente Periodis|author=Centro de Estuiios Miguel Enriquez (CEME)|website=archivochile.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413053224/http://www.archivochile.com/Derechos_humanos/doc_gen_ddhh/hhdddocgen0002.pdf|archivedate=13 April 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref> The Manuel Rodr\u00edguez Patriotic Front stated that 49 FPMR guerrillas were killed and hundreds tortured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fpmr.org/heroes8.html|title=Frente Patri\u00f3tico Manuel Rodr\u00edguez|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051104044728/http://fpmr.org/heroes8.html|archivedate=4 November 2005|url-status=dead|accessdate=25 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Latin American Institute on Mental Health and Human Rights, 200,000 people were affected by \"extreme trauma\"; this figure includes individuals executed, tortured, forcibly exiled, or having their immediate relatives put under detention.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Vasallo|first=Mark|year=2002|title=Truth and Reconciliation Commissions: General Considerations and a Critical Comparison of the Commissions of Chile and El Salvador|journal=The University of Miami Inter-American Law Review|volume=33|issue=1|page=163}}</ref> 316 women have reported to have subject to rape by soldiers and agents of the dictatorship, however the number is believed to much larger due to the preference of many women to avoid talking about this. Twenty pregnant women have declared to have suffered abortion due to torture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radio.uchile.cl/2013/09/03/violencia-sexual-contra-mujeres-en-dictadura-un-crimen-invisibilizado|title=Violencia sexual contra mujeres en dictadura: un crimen invisibilizado \u00ab Diario y Radio U Chile|website=radio.uchile.cl|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008103150/http://radio.uchile.cl/2013/09/03/violencia-sexual-contra-mujeres-en-dictadura-un-crimen-invisibilizado|archivedate=8 October 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref> In the words of [[Alejandra Matus]] detained women were doubly punished, first for being \"leftists\" and second for not conforming to their ideal of women usually being called \"perra\" (lit. \"bitch\").<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tVjdRz8LevE Cultura Verdadera Programa Completo del Lunes 14 de Diciembre de 2015] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202023740/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tVjdRz8LevE|date=2017-02-02}}, minute 3:20.</ref>\n\nIn addition to the violence experienced within Chile, many people fled the regime; some 30,000 Chileans were exiled,<ref>Augusto Pinochet's Chile, Diana Childress, p. 92, Twenty First century Books, 2009</ref><ref name=\"Jaime Gazmuri p. 121\">Chile en el umbral de los noventa: quince a\u00f1os que condicionan el futuro, Jaime Gazmuri & Felipe Ag\u00fcero, p. 121, Planeta, 1988</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|date=22 August 1983|title=Chile: One Carrot, Many Sticks|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,926095,00.html|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828011629/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,926095,00.html|archivedate=28 August 2013|accessdate=25 February 2015|magazine=Time.com}}</ref> particularly to [[Argentina]], however, [[Operation Condor]], which linked South American dictatorships together against political opponents, meant that even these exiles could be subject to violence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB125/index.htm|title=Lifting of Pinochet's Immunity Renews Focus on Operation Condor|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140919124055/http://www2.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB125/index.htm|archivedate=2014-09-19|url-status=live|accessdate=2014-08-26}}</ref> Some 20,000\u201340,000 Chilean exiles were holders of passports stamped with the letter \"L\" (which stood for ''lista nacional''), identifying them as ''persona non grata'' and had to seek permission before entering the country.<ref>\"Chile since the coup: ten years of repression\", Cynthia G. Brown, pp. 88\u201389, ''Americas Watch'', 1983.</ref> According to a study in [[Latin American Perspectives]],<ref name=\"ExileStudy\">{{cite journal|last1=Wright|first1=Thomas C.|last2=O\u00f1ate Z\u00fa\u00f1iga|first2=Rody|year=2007|title=Chilean political exile|journal=[[Latin American Perspectives]]|volume=34|issue=4|page=31|doi=10.1177/0094582x07302902}}</ref> at least 200,000 Chileans (about 2% of Chile's 1973 population) were forced into exile. Additionally, hundreds of thousands left the country in the wake of the economic crises that followed the military coup during the 1970s and 1980s.<ref name=\"ExileStudy\" /> In 2003, an article published by the [[International Committee of the Fourth International]] claimed that \"Of a population of barely 11 million, more than 4,000 were executed or 'disappeared,' hundreds of thousands were detained and tortured, and almost a million fled the country.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2003/09/chil-s17.html|title=The lessons of Chile \u2013 30 years on|author=Mauricio Saavedra|date=17 September 2003|publisher=World Socialist Web Site|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226001119/http://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2003/09/chil-s17.html|archivedate=26 February 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=25 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box |quote   =He shut down parliament, suffocated political life, banned trade unions, and made Chile his sultanate. His government disappeared 3,200 opponents, arrested 30,000 (torturing thousands of them) ... Pinochet's name will forever be linked to the [[Forced disappearance|''Desaparecidos'']], the [[Caravan of Death]], and the institutionalized torture that took place in the [[Villa Grimaldi]] complex.| [[Thor Halvorssen Mendoza|Thor Halvorssen]], president of the [[Human Rights Foundation]], ''[[National Review]]''<ref>[http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=NDQxNTJlM2M4OTRhOGJhNTMzNTkyNDQ2YmYzMTU3ZTU= Pinochet is history: But how will it remember him?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070615015027/http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=NDQxNTJlM2M4OTRhOGJhNTMzNTkyNDQ2YmYzMTU3ZTU%3D |date=2007-06-15 }} ''[[National Review]]'' Symposium, December 11, 2006</ref>}}\n\n<br />\n\n[[File:Casa de detenci\u00f3n clandestina en Jos\u00e9 Domingo Ca\u00f1as 01.JPG|thumb|[[Direcci\u00f3n de Inteligencia Nacional|DINA]]'s torture center at Jos\u00e9 Domingo Ca\u00f1as 1367]]\nThere were also internal exiles who due to a lack of resources could not escape abroad.<ref name=marin>{{cite journal |last1=Mar\u00edn Lleuc\u00fan |first1=Alejandro |date=2015 |title= Puerto Gala y Puerto Gaviota (1985-1993): Una mirada desde el tri\u00e1ngulo de la violencia|trans-title=Port of Gala and Port of Gaviota (1985-1993): A look from the triangle of violence |url=https://scielo.conicyt.cl/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&pid=S0718-22442015000200004 |journal=[[Magallania]] |volume=43 |issue=2 |pages= |doi= |access-date=January 10, 2019|language=Spanish }}</ref> In the 1980s a few left-wing sympathisers hid in [[Puerto Gala]] and [[Puerto Gaviota]], Patagonian fishing communities with a reputation of lawlessness. There they were joined by delinquents who feared torture or death by the authorities.<ref name=marin/>\n\n[[File:Ejecutados pinochet.jpg|thumb|left|Some funeral urns of political activists executed by the Chilean military dictatorship, from 1973 to 1990, in the cemetery of Santiago]]Several scholars including Paul Zwier,<ref name=\"Zwier2013\">{{cite book|last=Zwier|first=Paul J.|title=Principled Negotiation and Mediation in the International Arena: Talking with Evil|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W57hIyEOSUsC&pg=PA235|accessdate=22 March 2014|year=2013|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1107026872|pages=235\u2013}}</ref> Peter Winn<ref>[https://books.google.cl/books?id=YLBVjRCW6uMC&pg=PA14&lpg=PA14&dq=estado+policial+pinochet&source=bl&ots=eaFke6YsUG&sig=qZVQuZ7JPFtsxhrrcL_HScUe6No&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HXGdVN-xF4LYgwT8h4LIAw&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=estado%20policial%20pinochet&f=false] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225225310/https://books.google.cl/books?id=YLBVjRCW6uMC&pg=PA14&lpg=PA14&dq=estado+policial+pinochet&source=bl&ots=eaFke6YsUG&sig=qZVQuZ7JPFtsxhrrcL_HScUe6No&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HXGdVN-xF4LYgwT8h4LIAw&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBw |date=2015-02-25 }}</ref> and human rights organizations<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmostrador.cl/pais/2008/08/06/organismos-de-ddhh-denuncian-un-estado-policial-similar-al-de-pinochet/|title=Organismos de DDHH denuncian un estado policial 'similar' al de Pinochet|work=El Mostrador|accessdate=25 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225182240/http://www.elmostrador.cl/pais/2008/08/06/organismos-de-ddhh-denuncian-un-estado-policial-similar-al-de-pinochet/|archivedate=25 February 2015|date=2008-08-06}}</ref> have characterized the dictatorship as a [[police state]] exhibiting \"repression of public liberties, the elimination of political exchange, limiting freedom of speech, abolishing the right to strike, freezing wages.\"<ref name=\"Casanova1993\">{{cite book|last=Casanova|first=Pablo Gonz\u00e1lez|title=Latin America Today|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VNUNB2s5pcoC&pg=PA233|accessdate=22 March 2014|year=1993|publisher=United Nations University Press|isbn=9789280808193|pages=233\u2013}}</ref>\n\n===Fake combats===\nStarting in the late 1970s the regime began to use a tactic of faking combats, usually known by its Spanish name: \"falsos enfrentamientos\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://resumen.cl/2015/02/nuevos-condenados-por-falso-enfrentamiento-en-dictadura/|title=Nuevos condenados por falso enfrentamiento en dictadura |website=resumen.cl|accessdate=1 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201081335/https://resumen.cl/2015/02/nuevos-condenados-por-falso-enfrentamiento-en-dictadura/|archivedate=1 December 2017}}</ref> This meant that dissidents who were murdered outright had their deaths reported in media as if they had occurred in a mutual exchange of gunfire. This was done with support of journalists who \"reported\" the supposed events; in some cases, the fake combats were also staged. The faked combat tactic ameliorated criticism of the regime implicitly putting culpability on the victim. It is thought that the killing of the [[Revolutionary Left Movement (Chile)|MIR]] leader [[Miguel Enr\u00edquez (politician)|Miguel Enr\u00edquez]] in 1974 could be an early case of a faked combat. The faked combats reinforced the dictatorship narrative on the existence of an \"internal war\" which it used to justify its existence.<ref>{{cite thesis |last=Silva Hidalgo |first=Robinson Humberto |date=2014 |title=Resistencia pol\u00edtica y origen del movimiento social anti dictatorial en Chile (1973\u20131988) |type=Ph.D. |publisher=[[Universitat de Barcelona]] |url=http://diposit.ub.edu/dspace/bitstream/2445/55488/1/RHSH_TESIS.pdf |page=341\u2013349 |language=Spanish |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216184935/http://diposit.ub.edu/dspace/bitstream/2445/55488/1/RHSH_TESIS.pdf |archivedate=2016-02-16 }}</ref> A particular fake combat event, lasting from September 8 to 9 1983, occurred when forces of the CNI lobbed grenades into a house, detonating the structure and killing the two men and a woman who were in the building. The agents would later state, with help from the Chilean press, that the people in the house had fired on them previously from their cars and had escaped to the house. The official story became that the three suspects had caused the explosion themselves by trying to burn and destroy incriminating evidence. Such actions had the effect of justifying the existence of heavily armed forces in Chile. And by extension, justified the dictatorship's conduct against such \"violent\" offenders.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.archivochile.com/Derechos_humanos/janefuenove/ddhhjanefuov0001.pdf |title=Los Muertos en Falsos Enfrentamientos: Janequeo y Fuenteovejuna |accessdate=2017-11-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060507125801/http://www.archivochile.com/Derechos_humanos/janefuenove/ddhhjanefuov0001.pdf |archivedate=2006-05-07 }}</ref>\n\n==Politics and power within the dictatorship==\n\n===Pinochet\u2013Leigh conflict===\nIn the 1970s junta members [[Gustavo Leigh]] and Augusto Pinochet clashed on several occasions beginning in the day of the [[1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat]]. Leigh criticized Pinochet for having joined the coup very late and then pretending to keep all power for himself. In December 1974 Leigh opposed the proposal to name Pinochet president of Chile. Leigh recalls about that moment that, \"Pinochet was furious, he hit the board, broke the glass, injured his hand a little and bled. Then, Merino and Mendoza told me I should sign, because if not the junta would split. I signed.\". Leigh's primary concern was Pinochet's consolidating of the legislative and executive branches of government under the new government. In particular, Pinochet's decision to enact a plebiscite without formally alerting the other junta members.<ref name=\"auto1\">Ensalaco, Mark. 2000. Chile Under Pinochet : Recovering the Truth. Pennsylvania Studies in Human Rights. Philadelphia: University of Pennsylvania Press.</ref> Leigh, although a fervent supporter of the regime and hater of marxist ideology, had already taken steps to separate the executive and legislative branches. Pinochet is said to have been angered by Leigh's continued founding of a structure to divide the executive and legislative branches, eventually leading to Pinochet consolidating power and Leigh being dumped from the regime.<ref>Barros, Robert. La Junta militar: Pinochet y la Constituci\u00f3n de 1980. Sudamericana, 2005.</ref> Leigh tried to fight his dismissal from the military and government junta but on July 24, 1978 his office was blocked by paratroopers. In accordance with legal rights established by the junta government, its members could not be dismissed without evidence of impairment. So the Pinochet and junta members had Leigh declared unfit.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>\nCarmen Gardeweg: ''El general Leigh: pensamiento y sentimiento 48 horas despu\u00e9s de ser destituido en 1978''. La Segunda, 30 de septiembre de 1999, p\u00e1gina 8.</ref> Airforce General [[Fernando Matthei]] replaced Leigh as junta member.<ref name=newsbank>[http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BG&p_theme=bg&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EADED93AF54A141&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM 25 Chilean Soldiers Arrested in Burning of US Resident]</ref>\n\nAnother dictatorship member critical of Pinochet, [[Arturo Yovane]], was removed from his post as [[Ministry of Mining (Chile)|minister of mining]] in 1974 and appointed ambassador at the new Chilean embassy in [[Tehran]].<ref name=Gonzalez2009>{{cite web |url=http://ciperchile.cl/2009/08/06/el-dia-en-que-manuel-contreras-le-ofrecio-al-sha-de-iran-matar-a-%E2%80%9Cel-chacal%E2%80%9D/ |title=El d\u00eda en que Manuel Contreras le ofreci\u00f3 al Sha de Ir\u00e1n matar a \"Carlos, El Chacal\" |last1=Gonz\u00e1lez |first1=M\u00f3nica |date=August 6, 2009 |website=ciperchile.cl |publisher=CIPER |access-date=August 11, 2015 |language=Spanish |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909054340/http://ciperchile.cl/2009/08/06/el-dia-en-que-manuel-contreras-le-ofrecio-al-sha-de-iran-matar-a-%E2%80%9Cel-chacal%E2%80%9D/ |archivedate=September 9, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Civilian collaborators===\nOver time the dictatorship incorporated civilians into the government. Many of the [[Chicago boys]] joined the government, and Pinochet was largely sympathetic to them. This sympathy, scholar Peter Winn explains, was indebted to the fact that the Chicago boys were [[technocrat]]s and thus fitted Pinochet's self-image of being \"above politics\".<ref name=Winn2627>Winn, Peter (ed.). ''Victims of the Chilean miracle'', pp. 26\u201327.</ref> Pinochet was impressed by their assertiveness as well as by their links to the financial world of the United States.<ref name=Winn2627/>\n\nAnother group of civilians that collaborated extensively with the regime were the [[Gremialismo|Gremialists]], whose movement started in 1966 in the [[Pontifical Catholic University of Chile]].<ref name=Huneeus2000>{{cite journal |last=Huneeus |first=Carlos |date=2000 |title=Technocrats and politicians in an authoritarian regime. The 'ODEPLAN Boys' and the 'Gremialists' in Pinochet's Chile |jstor=158572 |journal=[[Journal of Latin American Studies]] |volume=32 |issue= 2|pages=461\u2013501 |doi= 10.1017/S0022216X00005812}}</ref> The founder of the Gremialist movement, lawyer [[Jaime Guzm\u00e1n]], never assumed any official position in the military dictatorship but he remained one of the closest collaborators with Pinochet, playing an important ideological role. He participated in the design of important speeches of Pinochet, and provided frequent political and doctrinal advice and consultancy.<ref name=\"archivochile\">{{cite web |author=Carlos Huneeus |publisher=Archivo Chile |title=Jaime Guzm\u00e1n no fue un defensor de los Derechos Humanos en el R\u00e9gimen de Pinochet |url=http://www.archivochile.com/Portada/8_ddhh/02_port_ddhh.pdf |date=3 April 2001 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923173556/http://www.archivochile.com/Portada/8_ddhh/02_port_ddhh.pdf |archivedate=23 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to scholar Carlos Huneeus the Gremialists and the Chicago Boys shared a long-term power strategy and were linked to each other in many ways.<ref name=Huneeus2000/>\nIn Chile, it has been very hard for the outside world to fully understand the role that everyday civilians played in keeping Pinochet's government afloat. Partly because there has been scant research into the topic, partly because those who did help the regime from 1973 to 1990 have been unwilling to explore their own part. One of the exemptions being an Univision interview with [[Osvaldo Romo|Osvaldo Romo Mena]], a civilian torturer in 1995, recounting his actions. Osvaldo Romo died while incarcerated for the murder of three political opponents. For the most part, civilian collaborators with Pinochet have not broken the [[code of silence]] held by the military of the 1970s to 1990s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raco.cat/index.php/rubrica/article/viewFile/310678/400693 |format=PDF |title=Complicity and Responsibility in the Aftermath of the Pinochet Regime: The Case of ''El Mocito'' |accessdate=2017-11-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201030451/http://www.raco.cat/index.php/rubrica/article/viewFile/310678/400693 |archivedate=2017-12-01 }}</ref>\n\n===Constitution of 1980===\n{{Main|1980 Chilean constitutional referendum}}\nEstablishing a new constitution was a core issue for the dictatorship since it provided a mean of [[legitimization]].<ref name=AngellPollack1990/> For this purpose the junta selected notable civilians willing to join the draft commission. Dissidents to the dictatorship were not represented in the commission.<ref name=Camel2000>{{cite journal|last=Cazor Aliste |first=Camel |date=2000 |title=Democracia y constitucion en Chile |url=http://mingaonline.uach.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-09502000000100003&script=sci_arttext |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518062933/http://mingaonline.uach.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-09502000000100003&script=sci_arttext |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-05-18 |journal=[[Revista de Derecho]] |publisher=[[Austral University of Chile]] |volume=IX |pages=25\u201334 |access-date=30 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nChile's new [[Constitution of Chile|constitution]] was approved in a national [[1980 Chilean constitutional referendum|plebiscite]] held on September 11, 1980.  The constitution was approved by 67% of voters under a process which has been described as \"highly irregular and undemocratic.\"<ref name=Hudson>Hudson, Rex A., ed. \"Chile: A Country Study.\" GPO for the Library of Congress. 1995. March 20, 2005 {{cite web |url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/cltoc.html |title=About this Collection &#124; Country Studies &#124; Digital Collections &#124; Library of Congress |accessdate=2012-05-24 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120524185929/lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/cltoc.html |archivedate=2012-05-24 }}</ref> Critics of the 1980 Constitution argue that the constitution was created not to build a democracy, but to consolidate power within the central government while limiting the amount of sovereignty allowed to the people with little political presence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mingaonline.uach.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-09502000000100003&script=sci_arttext|title=Revista de derecho (Valdivia) \u2013 Democracia y Constitucion en Chile|date=18 May 2015|accessdate=1 May 2018|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518062933/http://mingaonline.uach.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-09502000000100003&script=sci_arttext|archivedate=18 May 2015}}</ref> The constitution came into force on March 11, 1981.\n\n===Removal of C\u00e9sar Mendoza===\nIn 1985, due to the [[Caso Degollados]] scandal (\"case of the slit throats\"), General [[C\u00e9sar Mendoza]] resigned and was replaced by General [[Rodolfo Stange]].<ref name=\"newsbank\"/>\n\n===Youth policy===\nOne of the first measures of the dictatorship was to set up a Secretar\u00eda Nacional de la Juventud (SNJ, National Youth Office). This was done on October 28, 1973, even before the Declaration of Principles of the junta made in March 1974. This was a way of mobilizing sympathetic elements of the civil society in support for the dictatorship. SNJ was created by advise of [[Jaime Guzm\u00e1n]], being an example of the dictatorship adopting a [[Gremialismo|Gremialist]] thought.<ref name=Yanko2015>{{cite journal |last1=Gonz\u00e1lez |first1=Yanko |date=2015 |title=El \"Golpe Generacional\" y la Secretar\u00eda Nacional de la Juventud: purga, disciplinamiento y resocializaci\u00f3n de las identidades juveniles bajo Pinochet (1973\u20131980) |journal=[[Atenea]] |volume=512 |issue= 512|pages=10.4067/S0718\u201304622015000200006 |doi= 10.4067/S0718-04622015000200006|language=spanish |trans-title=The \"Generational Putsch\" and the National youth Office: Purge, disciplining and resocialization of youth identities under Pinochet (1973\u20131980) }}</ref> Some right-wing student union leaders like [[Andr\u00e9s Allamand]] were skeptical to these attempts as they were moulded from above and gathered disparate figures such as [[Miguel Kast]], [[Antonio Vodanovic]] and Jaime Guzm\u00e1n. Allamand and other young right-wingers also resented the dominance of the gremialist in SNJ, considering it a closed gremialist club.<ref>{{cite book |last=Allamnd |first=Andr\u00e9s |date=1999 |title=La Traves\u00eda del Desierto|language=Spanish |url= |location= |publisher=Editorial Alfaguara |pages=29\u201330 |isbn=978-956-239-078-1 |author-link=Andr\u00e9s Allamand }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1975 to 1980 the SNJ arranged a series of [[ritual]]ized acts in [[cerro Chacarillas]] reminiscent of [[Francoist Spain]]. The policy towards the sympathetic youth contrasted with the murder, surveillance and forced disappearances the dissident youth faced from the regime. Most of the documents of the SNJ were reportedly destroyed by the dictatorship in 1988.<ref name=Yanko2015/>\n\n===Women during the dictatorship===\nIn 1962 under the presidency of Christian Democrat Eduardo Freo Montalva, the women's section expanded pre-existing neighbourhood 'mothers' centres' (which initially helped women to purchase their own sewing machines) to help garner support for their social reforms amongst the poorer sections. By the end of the 1960s, there were 8,000 centres involving 400,000 members.<ref>Ximena Buster, 'Watch out for the little nazi man that all of have inside: The mobilization and demobilization of women in militarized Chile', Women's Studies International Forum, 11:5, p. 490.</ref>. Under Allende they were reorganised under the rubric National Confederation of Mothers' Centres (Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional de Centros de Madres, COCEMA) and leadership of his wife, Hortensia Bussi, to encourage community initiatives and implement their policies directed at women. <ref>Ximena Buster, 'Watch out for the little nazi man that all of have inside: The mobilization and demobilization of women in militarized Chile', Women's Studies International Forum, 11:5, p. 490; Fabiola Bahamondes Carrasco, 'Centros de Madres en el Chile rural. Un espacio de seguridad.' Revista Nomadias, 22, 2016, p. 89. </ref>\n\n==Opposition==\n\n=== Internal Opposition ===\n\n====Attacks on military personnel====\n{{further|Armed resistance in Chile (1973\u20131990)}}\nOne of the counter-Pinochet government organizations was named MIR, Movimiento de Izquierda Revolucionaria, and it conducted several operations against the Pinochet government until the late 1980s. MIR assassinated the head of the Army Intelligence school, Lieutenant Roger Vergara, with machine gun fire in the late 1970s. The MIR also executed an attack on the base of the Chilean Secret Police (Central Nacional de Informaciones, CNI), as well as several attempts on the lives of carabineros officials and a judge of the Supreme Court in Chile.<ref>Collier, Simon, and William F Sater. 1996. A History of Chile, 1808-1994. Cambridge Latin American Studies, 82. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</ref> Throughout the beginning years of the dictatorship the MIR was low-profile, but in August 1981 the MIR successfully killed the military leader of Santiago, General Carol Urzua Ibanez. Attacks on Chilean military official increased in the early 1980s, with the MIR killing several security forces personnel on a variety of occasions through extensive use of planted bombs in police stations or machine gun use<ref>Anderson, Sean, and Stephen Sloan. 2009. Historical Dictionary of Terrorism. 3Rd ed. Historical Dictionaries of War, Revolution, and Civil Unrest, 38. Lanham, Md.: Scarecrow Press.</ref>\n\nRepresenting a major shift in attitudes, the CPCh founded the [[Manuel Rodr\u00edguez Patriotic Front|FPMR]] in 14 December 1983, to engage in a violent armed struggle against the junta.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ensalaco |first1=Mark |title=Chile Under Pinochet : Recovering the Truth. |date=2000 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |location=Philadelphia |isbn=0812235207 |page=149}}</ref> Most notably the organisation attempted to assassinate Pinochet on the 7 September 1986 under 'Operation XX Century' but were unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite book |last1=O'Shaughnessy |first1=Hugh |title=Pinochet, the politics of torture |date=2000 |publisher=New York University Press |location=New York |isbn=0814762018 |page=121}}</ref> The group also assassinated the author of the 1980 Constitution, [[Jaime Guzm\u00e1n]] on 1 April 1991.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Roniger |first1=Luis |last2=Sznajder |first2=Mario |title=The Legacy of Human-Rights Violations in the Southern Cone: Argentina, Chile, and Uruguay |date=1999 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=9780198296157 |page=106}}</ref> They continued to operate throughout the 1990s, being designated as a terrorist organisation the [[U.S. Department of State]] and [[Mi6|MI6]], until supposedly ceasing to operate in 1999.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chile: Extremism & Counter-Extremism |url=https://www.counterextremism.com/countries/chile |website=Counter Extremism Project |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=8 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Church opposition to human rights violations====\n{{further|Vicariate of Solidarity}}The Catholic Church, which at first expressed its gratitude to the armed forces for saving the country from the horrors of a \"Marxist dictatorship\" became, under the leadership of Cardinal [[Ra\u00fal Silva Henr\u00edquez]], the most outspoken critic of the regime's social and economic policies.\n\nThe Catholic Church was symbolically and institutionally powerful within Chile. Domestically, it was the second most powerful institution, behind Pinochet's government. While the Church remained politically neutral, its opposition to the regime came in the form of human rights advocacy and through the social movements that it gave a platform to. It achieved this through the establishment of the Cooperative Committee for Peace in Chile (COPACHI) and Vicariate of Solidarity. COPACHI was founded by [[Cardinal Raul Silva Henriquez|Cardinal Raul Silve Henriquez]], Archbishop of Santiago, as an immediate response to the repression of the Pinochet regime. It was apolitical in a spirit of collaboration rather than conflict with the government. Pinochet developed suspicion of COPACHI, leading to its dissolution in late 1975. In response Silva founded the Vicariate in its place. Historian Hugo Fruhling's work highlights the multifaceted nature of Vicaria.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Corradi |first1=Juan |title=Fear at the Edge, State Terror and Resistance in Latin America |url=https://archive.org/details/fearatedgestatet00juan |url-access=registration |date=1992 |publisher=University of California Press |pages=[https://archive.org/details/fearatedgestatet00juan/page/121 121\u2013141]}}</ref> Through developments and education programs in the shantytown area of Santiago, the Vicaria had mobilised around 44,000 people to join campaigns by 1979. The Church published a newsletter called ''Solidarity'' published in Chile and abroad, and supplied the public with information through radio stations. Vicaria pursued a legal strategy of defending human rights, not a political strategy to re-democratise Chile.\n\n====Jornadas de Protesta Nacional====\n\nThe Days of National Protest ([[:es:Jornadas de Protesta Nacional|Jornadas de Protesta Nacional]]) were days of civil demonstrations that periodically took place in Chile in the 1980s against the military junta. They were characterized by street demonstrations in the downtown avenues of the city in the mornings, strikes during the day, and barricades and clashes in the periphery of the city throughout the night. The protests were faced with increased government repression from 1984, with the biggest and last protest summoned in July 1986. The protests changed the mentality of many Chileans, strengthening opposition organizations and movements in the 1988 plebiscite.\n\n=== External Opposition ===\n\n==== Solidarity Campaigns & Exiles Movements ====\nThe regime's forced exile of over 200,000 Chileans led to areas of global opposition to the Pinochet government. However, the exiles themselves were not entirely responsible for the international resistance against Pinochet, but rather were able to gain the solidarity of many members of their host countries. Exiles were dispersed across the globe, and to all continents, with different factions of leftist opposition finding refuge in like-minded host countries. For example, the militant revolutionary MIR centring their operations in Havana, Cuba. While the efforts of exiles across the globe in actually militarily or financially supporting the domestic opposition to the junta were limited in their effectiveness, the more important work of the exiles came in their efforts in mobilising support among citizens in their host countries. As such, The Chile Solidarity Campaign (CSC) in the UK was relatively successful at petitioning the labour government. This included lobbying host governments and international organisations such as the United Nations to condemn the abuses of the dictatorship. The overall effect of this was the successful creation of a global solidarity movement.\n\n==Economy and free market reforms==\n[[Image:Chile- el pueblo vencera cropped.jpg|thumb|[[Estadio Nacional de Chile]] as a [[concentration camp]] after the coup.]]\n{{Main|Economic history of Chile#1975-81}}\nAfter the military took over the government in 1973, a period of dramatic economic changes began. The Chilean economy was still faltering in the months following the coup. As the military junta itself was not particularly skilled in remedying the persistent economic difficulties, it appointed a group of Chilean economists who had been educated in the United States at the [[University of Chicago]]. Given financial and ideological support from Pinochet, the U.S., and international financial institutions, the [[Chicago Boys]] advocated ''[[laissez-faire]]'', [[free market|free-market]], [[neoliberalism|neoliberal]], and [[Conservatism#Fiscal conservatism|fiscally conservative]] policies, in stark contrast to the extensive [[nationalization]] and centrally-planned economic programs supported by Allende.<ref name=\"K. Remmer 1998 5-55\">{{cite journal\n | author = K. Remmer\n | year = 1998\n | title = '''Public Policy and Regime Consolidation: The First Five Years of the Chilean Junta'''\n | journal = Journal of the Developing Areas\n | volume =\n | issue =\n | pages = 5\u201355\n | id = \n | url =\n }}</ref> Chile was drastically transformed from an economy isolated from the rest of the world, with strong government intervention, into a liberalized, world-integrated economy, where market forces were left free to guide most of the economy's decisions.<ref name=\"K. Remmer 1998 5-55\"/>\n\nFrom an economic point of view, the era can be divided into two periods. The first, from 1975 to 1982, corresponds to the period when most of the reforms were implemented. The period ended with the international debt crisis and the collapse of the Chilean economy. At that point, unemployment was extremely high, above 20 percent, and a large proportion of the banking sector had become bankrupt. The following period was characterized by new reforms and economic recovery. Some economists argue that the recovery was due to an about-face turnaround of Pinochet's free market policy, since he nationalized many of the same industries that were nationalized under Allende and fired the Chicago Boys from their government posts.<ref>{{cite book\n| last = Valenzuela\n| first = Arturo\n| year = 2002\n| title = A Nation of Enemies\n| publisher = W. W. Norton\n| location =New York\n| id =\n}} p. 197-8</ref>\n\n===1975\u201381===\nChile's main industry, [[Chilean nationalization of copper|copper mining]], remained in government hands, with the [[Chilean constitution of 1980|1980 Constitution]] declaring them \"inalienable,\"<ref name=NLR>{{Cite journal | last = Riesco | first = Manuel | title = Is Pinochet dead? | journal = [[New Left Review]] | volume = II | issue = 47 | publisher = New Left Review | date = September\u2013October 2007 | url = http://newleftreview.org/II/47/manuel-riesco-is-pinochet-dead | ref = harv | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160124224407/http://newleftreview.org/II/47/manuel-riesco-is-pinochet-dead | archivedate = 2016-01-24 }} [http://newleftreview.org/article/download_pdf?language=es&id=2685 Spanish pdf.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308150245/https://newleftreview.org/article/download_pdf?language=es&id=2685 |date=2017-03-08 }} [http://newleftreview.org/article/download_pdf?language=it&id=2685 Italian pdf.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308142849/https://newleftreview.org/article/download_pdf?language=it&id=2685 |date=2017-03-08 }}</ref> but new mineral deposits were open to private investment.<ref name=NLR/> Capitalist involvement was increased, the [[Pensions in Chile|Chilean pension system]] and healthcare were privatized, and [[Education in Chile|Superior Education]] was also placed in private hands. One of the junta's economic moves was fixing the exchange rate in the early 1980s, leading to a boom in imports and a collapse of domestic industrial production; this together with a world recession caused a serious economic crisis in 1982, where GDP plummeted by 14%, and unemployment reached 33%. At the same time, a series of massive protests were organized, trying to cause the fall of the regime, which were efficiently repressed.\n\n===1982\u201383===\n{{Main|Crisis of 1982}}\nIn 1982-1983 Chile witnessed a severe economic crises with a surge in unemployment and a meltdown of the financial sector.<ref>Sebasti\u00e1n Edwards, Alejandra Cox Edwards: ''Monetarism and Liberalization: the Chilean Experiment.'' University of Chicago Press, 1991, S. xvii.</ref> 16 out of 50 financial institutions faced bankruptcy.<ref name=\"Fischer 329\">Karin Fischer: \"The Influence of Neoliberals in Chile before, during, and after Pinochet.\" In: P. Mirowski, D. Plehwe (Hrsg.): ''The Road from Mont P\u00e8lerin: The Making of the Neoliberal Thought Collective'', Harvard University Press, Cambridge/London 2009, S. 305\u2013346, hier S. 329.</ref> In 1982 the two biggest banks were nationalized to prevent an even worse [[credit crunch]]. In 1983 another five banks were nationalized and two banks had to be put under government supervision.<ref>Karin Fischer: \"The Influence of Neoliberals in Chile before, during, and after Pinochet\" In: P. Mirowski, D. Plehwe (Hrsg.): ''The Road from Mont P\u00e8lerin: The Making of the Neoliberal Thought Collective'', Harvard University Press, Cambridge/London 2009, p. 305\u2013346, hier S. 329.</ref> The central bank took over foreign debts. Critics ridiculed the economic policy of the [[Chicago Boys]] as \"Chicago way to socialism\".<ref>Robert G. Wesson: ''Politics, policies, and economic development in Latin America''. Hoover Press, 1984, {{ISBN|0-8179-8062-8}}, S. 8.</ref>\n\n===1984\u201390===\nAfter the economic crisis, [[Hern\u00e1n B\u00fcchi]] became Minister of Finance from 1985 to 1989, introducing a return to a free market economic policy. He allowed the peso to float and reinstated restrictions on the movement of capital in and out of the country. He deleted some [[bank regulation]]s, and simplified and reduced the corporate tax. Chile went ahead with privatizations, including public utilities and the re-privatization of companies that had briefly returned to government control during the 1982\u201383 crisis. From 1984 to 1990, Chile's gross domestic product grew by an annual average of 5.9%, the fastest on the continent. Chile developed a good export economy, including the export of fruits and vegetables to the northern hemisphere when they were out of season, and commanded high export prices.\n\n===Evaluation===\n\n[[Image:Economic growth of Chile.PNG|thumb|300px|Chilean (orange) and average Latin American (blue) rates of growth of GDP (1971\u20132007).]]\n\nInitially the economic reforms were internationally praised. [[Milton Friedman]] wrote in his ''Newsweek'' column on 25 January 1982 about the [[Miracle of Chile]]. British Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] credited Pinochet with bringing about a thriving, free-enterprise economy, while at the same time downplaying the junta's human rights record, condemning an \"organised international Left who are bent on revenge.\"\n\nWith the economic crises of 1982 the \"monetarist experiment\" was widely regarded a failure.<ref>Carlos Fortin: \"The Failure of Repressive Monetarism: Chile, 1973\u20131983\". In: ''Third World Quarterly'', vol. 6, no. 2 (Apr., 1984), p. 310\u2013326; Sebastian Edwards: \"Monetarism in Chile, 1973\u201383: Some Economic Puzzles\". In: ''Economic Development and Cultural Change'' vol. 34, no. 3 (April 1986), p. 535. Vgl. auch die Nachweise bei Jean Dr\u00e8ze, [[Amartya Sen|Amartya Kumar Sen]]: ''Hunger and Public Action''. Oxford University Press, 1991, p. 231.</ref>\n\nThe pragmatic economic policy after the crises of 1982 is appreciated for bringing constant economic growth.<ref>Enrique R. Carrasco: \"Autocratic Transitions to Liberalism: A Comparison of Chilean and Russian Structural Adjustment.\" In: ''Law and Contemporary Problems'', Bd. 5, S. 99\u2013126, hier S. 101, Fn. 5.</ref> It is questionable whether the radical reforms of the Chicago Boys contributed to post-1983 growth.<ref>J. M. Albala-Bertrand: \"Monetarism and Liberalization: The Chilean Experiment: With a New Afterword.\" In: ''The Economic Journal'', vol. 102, no. 414 (Sep., 1992), p. 1258\u20131260, p. 1259f; Jorge Nef: \"The Chilean Model Fact and Fiction.\" In: ''Latin American Perspectives.'' vol. 30, no. 5, (Sep., 2003), p. 16\u201340; Eduardo Silva: \"From Dictatorship to Democracy: The Business-State Nexus in Chile's Economic Transformation, 1975\u20131994.\" In: ''Comparative Politics'' vol. 28 (1996), p. 299\u2013320; Ricardo French-Davis: ''Economic Reforms in Chile: From Dictatorship to Democracy.'' University of Michigan Press: Ann Arbour, 2002.</ref> According to [[Ricardo Ffrench-Davis]], economist and consultant of the [[United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean]], the 1982 crises as well as the success of the pragmatic economic policy after 1982 proves that the 1975\u20131981 radical economic policy of the Chicago Boys actually harmed the Chilean economy.<ref>Helmut Wittelsb\u00fcrger, Albrecht von Hoff: [http://www.kas.de/wf/doc/kas_3585-544-1-30.pdf ''Chiles Weg zur Sozialen Marktwirtschaft.''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014172241/http://www.kas.de/wf/doc/kas_3585-544-1-30.pdf |date=2013-10-14 }} (PDF; 118&nbsp;kB); ''Konrad-Adenauer-Stiftung -Auslandsinfo.'' 1/2004, p. 97, 104.</ref>\n\n===Social consequences===\nThe economic policies espoused by the Chicago Boys and implemented by the junta initially caused several economic indicators to decline for Chile's lower classes.<ref name=\"K. Remmer 1998 3-29\">{{cite journal\n | author = K. Remmer\n | year = 1998\n | title = '''The Politics of Neoliberal Economic Reform in South America'''\n | journal =Studies in Comparative International Development\n | volume = 33\n | issue =2\n | pages = 3\u201329\n | id = Studies in Comparative International Development\n | url =\n | doi=10.1007/bf02687406\n }}</ref> Between 1970 and 1989, there were large cuts to incomes and social services.  Wages decreased by 8%.<ref name=\"Petras and Vieux 1998 57-72\">{{cite journal\n | author1 = James Petras\n | author2 = Steve Vieux\n | year = 1990\n | title = The Chilean \"Economic Miracle\": An Empirical Critique\n | journal = Critical Sociology\n | volume =\n | issue =\n | pages = 57\u201372\n | id = \n | url =\n | author1-link = James Petras\n }}</ref> Family allowances in 1989 were 28% of what they had been in 1970 and the budgets for education, health and housing had dropped by over 20% on average.<ref name=\"Petras and Vieux 1998 57-72\"/><ref>Sznajder, 1996</ref> The massive increases in [[military spending]] and cuts in funding to public services coincided with falling wages and steady rises in unemployment, which averaged 26% during the worldwide economic slump of 1982\u201385<ref name=\"Petras and Vieux 1998 57-72\"/> and eventually peaked at 30%.\n\nIn 1990, the LOCE act on education initiated the dismantlement of [[Education in Chile|public education]].<ref name=NLR/> According to Communist Party of Chile member and economist Manuel Riesco Larra\u00edn:\n\n<blockquote>Overall, the impact of neoliberal policies has reduced the total proportion of students in both public and private institutions in relation to the entire population, from 30 per cent in 1974 down to 25 per cent in 1990, and up only to 27 per cent today. If falling birth rates have made it possible today to attain full coverage at primary and secondary levels, the country has fallen seriously behind at tertiary level, where coverage, although now growing, is still only 32 per cent of the age group. The figure was twice as much in neighbouring [[Education in Argentina|Argentina]] and [[Education in Uruguay|Uruguay]], and even higher in developed countries\u2014[[Education in South Korea|South Korea]] attaining a record 98 per cent coverage. Significantly, tertiary education for the upper-income fifth of the Chilean population, many of whom study in the new private universities, also reaches above 70 per cent.<ref name=NLR/></blockquote>\n\nThe junta relied on the middle class, the oligarchy, domestic business, foreign corporations, and foreign loans to maintain itself.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=hzrwMb3UppYC&dq=Chile+under+pinochet&printsec=frontcover&source=bl&ots=-66tt8rEmg&sig=nSBX05IdsHb6lVMw141M4G7vYD0&hl=en&ei=he_tSYCpDJCgtgOD4YTjAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5] Chile under Pinochet: recovering the truth\n</ref>\nUnder Pinochet, funding of military and internal defence spending rose 120% from 1974 to 1979.<ref name=\"auto\">Remmer, 1989</ref>\nDue to the reduction in public spending, tens of thousands of employees were fired from other state-sector jobs.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\nThe oligarchy recovered most of its lost industrial and agricultural holdings, for the junta sold to private buyers most of the industries expropriated by Allende's Popular Unity government.\n\nFinancial conglomerates became major beneficiaries of the liberalized economy and the flood of foreign bank loans. Large foreign banks reinstated the credit cycle, as the Junta saw that the basic state obligations, such as resuming payment of principal and interest installments, were honored. International lending organizations such as the [[World Bank]], the [[International Monetary Fund]], and the [[Inter-American Development Bank]] lent vast sums anew.<ref name=\"Petras and Vieux 1998 57-72\"/>\nMany foreign multinational corporations such as [[International Telephone and Telegraph]] (ITT), [[Dow Chemical]], and [[Firestone Tire and Rubber Company|Firestone]], all expropriated by Allende, returned to Chile.<ref name=\"Petras and Vieux 1998 57-72\"/>\n\n==Foreign relations==\n{{Further|Foreign relations of Chile}}\nHaving risen to power on an anti-Marxist agenda, Pinochet found common cause with the military dictatorships of [[Bolivia]], [[Brazil]], [[Paraguay]], [[Uruguay]], and later, [[Argentine military junta|Argentina]]. The six countries eventually formulated a plan known as [[Operation Condor]], in which the security forces of participating states would target active Marxist subversives, guerrillas, and their alleged sympathizers in the allied countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/news/20010306/|title=Operation Condor|accessdate=25 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227063606/http://www2.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/news/20010306/|archivedate=27 February 2015}}</ref> Pinochet's government received tacit approval and material support from the United States. The exact nature and extent of this support is disputed. (''See'' [[Chilean coup of 1973#U.S. role in 1973 coup|U.S. role in 1973 Coup]], [[U.S. intervention in Chile]] and Operation Condor for more details.) It is known, however, that the American Secretary of State at the time, Henry Kissinger, practiced a policy of supporting coups in nations which the United States viewed as leaning toward Communism.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB123/chile.htm |title=Kissinger Telcons on Chile |accessdate=2007-09-19 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070912025948/http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB123/chile.htm |archivedate=2007-09-12 }} The Kissinger Telcons:\nKissinger Telcons on Chile</ref>\n\nThe new junta quickly broke diplomatic relations with [[Cuba]] and [[North Korea]], which had been established under the Allende government. Shortly after the junta came to power, several communist countries, including the [[Soviet Union]], [[North Vietnam]], [[East Germany]], [[People's Republic of Poland|Poland]], [[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic|Czechoslovakia]], [[People's Republic of Hungary|Hungary]], [[People's Republic of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]], and [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]], severed diplomatic relations with Chile however, [[Communist Romania|Romania]] and the [[China|People's Republic of China]] both continued to maintain diplomatic relations with Chile.<ref>J. Samuel Valenzuela and Arturo Valenzuela (eds.), ''Military Rule in Chile: Dictatorship and Oppositions'', p. 317</ref> Pinochet has nurtured his relationship with China.<ref>{{Cite news |title=U.S. and Others Gave Millions To Pinochet|newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=2004-12-07 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/07/business/us-and-others-gave-millions-to-pinochet.html |accessdate=2019-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=The Dictator|newspaper=[[The New Yorker]] |date=1998-10-19 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1998/10/19/the-dictator-2 |accessdate=2019-07-11}}</ref> The government broke diplomatic relations with [[Cambodia]] in January 1974<ref>''El Mercurio'', 20 January 1974</ref> and renewed ties with South Korea in October 1973{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} and with [[South Vietnam]] in March 1974.<ref>''El Mercurio'', 6 April 1975</ref> Pinochet attended the funeral of General [[Francisco Franco]], dictator of Spain from 1936\u201375, in late 1975.\n\nChile was on the brink of being invaded by Argentina, as the Argentina junta initiated [[Operation Soberania]] on 22 December 1978 because of the strategic [[Beagle Channel cartography since 1881|Picton, Lennox and Nueva]] islands at the southern tip of South America on the Beagle Canal. A full-scale war was prevented only by the call off of the operation by Argentina due to military and political reasons.<ref>See Alejandro Luis Corbacho ''\"Predicting the probability of war during brinkmanship crisis: The Beagle and the Malvinas conflicts\"'' {{cite news |title=Predicting the Probability of War During Brinkmanship Crises: The Beagle and the Malvinas Conflicts |ssrn = 1016843|date= September 2003|last1= Corbacho|first1= Alejandro}}  about the reasons of the call off (p.45): ''The newspaper Clar\u00edn explained some years later that such caution was based, in part, on military concerns. In order to achieve a victory, certain objectives had to be reached before the seventh day after the attack. Some military leaders considered this not enough time due to the difficulty involved in transportation through the passes over the Andean Mountains.'' and in cite 46: ''According to Clar\u00edn, two consequences were feared. First, those who were dubious feared a possible regionalization of the conflict. Second, as a consequence, the conflict could acquire great power proportions. In the first case decisionmakers speculated that Peru, Bolivia, Ecuador, and Brazil might intervene. Then the great powers could take sides. In this case, the resolution of the conflict would depend not on the combatants, but on the countries that supplied the weapons.''</ref> But the relations remained tense as Argentina invaded the Falklands ([[Operation Rosario]]). Chile along with [[Colombia]], were the only countries in South America to criticize the use of force by Argentina in its war with the UK over the [[Falkland Islands]]. Chile actually helped the United Kingdom during the war. The two countries (Chile and Argentina) finally agreed to papal mediation over the Beagle canal that finally ended in the [[Treaty of Peace and Friendship of 1984 between Chile and Argentina]] (''Tratado de Paz y Amistad''). Chilean sovereignty over the islands and Argentinian east of the surrounding sea is now undisputed.\n\nIn 1980, [[Philippines|Philippine]] President [[Ferdinand Marcos]] had invited the entire Junta (consisting at this point of Pinochet, Merino, Matthei, and Mendoza) to visit the country as part of a planned tour of Southeast Asia in an attempt to help improve their image and bolster military and economic relations with the Philippines, Japan, South Korea, and Hong Kong. Due to intense U.S. Pressure at the last minute (while Pinochet's plane was halfway en route over the Pacific), Marcos cancelled the visit and denied Pinochet landing rights in the country. Pinochet and the junta were further caught off guard and humiliated when they were forced to land in Fiji to refuel for the planned return to Santiago, only to be met with airport staff who refused to assist the plane in any way (the Fijian military was called in instead), invasive and prolonged customs searches, exorbitant fuel and aviation service charges, and hundreds of angry protesters who pelted his plane with eggs and tomatoes. The usually stoic and calm Pinochet became enraged, firing his Foreign Minister Hernan Cubillos, several diplomats, and expelling the Philippine Ambassador.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1980/04/02/filipino-rebuff-humiliates-pinochet/60da7bd2-b648-480f-909e-5651f5bea8ec/|title=Filipino Rebuff Humiliates Pinochet|first=Charles A.|last=Krause|date=2 April 1980|accessdate=1 May 2018|via=www.washingtonpost.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023175426/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1980/04/02/filipino-rebuff-humiliates-pinochet/60da7bd2-b648-480f-909e-5651f5bea8ec/|archivedate=23 October 2017}}</ref><ref>Helen Spooner, ''Soldiers in a narrow land: the Pinochet regime in Chile'', [https://books.google.com/books?hl=de&id=lE1G1OBhsbMC url]</ref>  Relations between the two countries were restored only in 1986 when [[Corazon Aquino]] assumed the presidency of the Philippines after Marcos was ousted in a non-violent revolution, the [[People Power Revolution]].\n\n===United States===\n{{Further|United States intervention in Chile}}\n[[File:Orlando Letelier, Washingron DC, 1976 (de Marcelo Montecino).jpg|thumb|right|[[Orlando Letelier]], a former Chilean minister, was assassinated in Washington, D.C. in 1976]]\n[[File:Nlc02585cs.jpg|thumb|Pinochet meeting with U.S. President [[Jimmy Carter]] in Washington, D.C., September 6, 1977]]\nThe U.S. government had been interfering in Chilean politics since 1961, and it spent millions trying to prevent Allende from coming to power, and subsequently undermined his presidency through financing opposition. Declassified C.I.A documents reveal U.S. knowledge and alleged involvement in the coup. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Kornbluh |first1=Peter |title=The Pinochet File |date=2013 |publisher=The New Press |location=New York |pages=1\u201378, 280\u2013281}}</ref> They provided material support to the military regime after the coup, although criticizing it in public. A document released by the U.S. [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) in 2000, titled \"CIA Activities in Chile\", revealed that the CIA actively supported the military junta during and after the overthrow of Allende and that it made many of Pinochet's officers into paid contacts of the CIA or U.S. military, even though some were known to be involved in human rights abuses.<ref name=\"NSA-2000-9-19\">Peter Kornbluh, [http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/news/20000919/ CIA Acknowledges Ties to Pinochet\u2019s Repression Report to Congress Reveals U.S. Accountability in Chile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128142216/http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/news/20000919/ |date=2006-11-28 }}, Chile Documentation Project, National Security Archive, September 19, 2000. Accessed online November 26, 2006.</ref>\nThe U.S. continued to give the ''junta'' substantial economic support between the years 1973\u201379, despite concerns from more liberal Congressmen, as seen from the results of the [[Church Committee]]. U.S. public stance did condemn the human rights violations, however declassifies documents reveal such violations were not an abstacle for members of the Nixon and Ford administrations. [[Henry Kissinger]] visited Santiago in 1976 for the annual conference of the [[Organisation of American States]]. During his visit he privately met with Pinochet and reassured the leader of internal support from the U.S. administration.<ref>{{cite web |title=memorandum of conversation, Kissinger and Pinochet |url=https://www.hsdl.org/?view&did=438484 |website=Homeland Security Digital Library |publisher=Gerald Ford Library |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> \nThe U.S. went beyond verbal condemnation in 1976, after the murder of [[Letelier case|Orlando Letelier]] in Washington D.C., when it placed an embargo on arms sales to Chile that remained in effect until the restoration of democracy in 1989. This more aggressive stance coincided with the election of [[Jimmy Carter]] who shifted the focus of U.S. foreign policy towards human rights.\n\n===United Kingdom===\nBritain's initial reaction to the overthrowing of Allende was one of caution. The Conservative government recognised the legitimacy of the new government, but didn't offer any other declarations of support.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alborada.net/watts-heath-uk-pinochet-chile-0913/|title=Business As Usual: Britain's Heath Government and Chile's 9/11|last=Watts|first=Josh|website=Alborada|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n\nUnder the [[Labour government, 1974\u20131979|Labour government of 1974-79]], Britain's relations with Chile were cordial, if not close. While [[United Kingdom|Britain]] regularly condemned the junta at the United Nations for its human rights abuses, bilateral relations between the two were not affected to the same degree.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wilkinson|first=Michael D.|date=1992|title=The Chile Solidarity Campaign and British Government Policy towards Chile, 1973-1990|journal=Revista Europea de Estudios Latinoamericanos y del Caribe / European Review of Latin American and Caribbean Studies|issue=52|pages=57\u201374|issn=0924-0608|jstor=25675537}}</ref> Britain formally withdrew its Santiago ambassador in 1974, however reinstated the position in 1980 under the [[Margaret Thatcher]] government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/1980/oct/14/chile-diplomatic-representation-and-arms|title=CHILE: DIPLOMATIC REPRESENTATION AND ARMS SALES (Hansard, 14 October 1980)|website=api.parliament.uk|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n\nChile was officially neutral during the [[Falkland War]], but the Chilean US-built Westinghouse long-range radar deployed at Punta Arenas, in southern Chile, gave the British task force early warning of Argentinian air attacks, which allowed British ships and troops in the war zone to take defensive action.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.margaretthatcher.org/speeches/displaydocument.asp?docid=108383|title=Speech on Pinochet at the Conservative Party Conference|accessdate=25 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225225857/http://www.margaretthatcher.org/speeches/displaydocument.asp?docid=108383|archivedate=25 February 2015}}</ref> Margaret Thatcher said that the day the radar was taken out of service for overdue maintenance was the day Argentinian fighter-bombers bombed the troopships ''Sir Galahad'' and ''Sir Tristram'', leaving approximately 50 dead and 150 wounded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmforces.co.uk/training/articles/1834-the-falklands-conflict-part-5---battles-of-goose-green-stanley|title=The Falklands Conflict Part 5 \u2013 Battles of Goose Green & Stanley HMFORCES.CO.UK|website=hmforces.co.uk|accessdate=1 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306095759/http://www.hmforces.co.uk/training/articles/1834-the-falklands-conflict-part-5---battles-of-goose-green-stanley|archivedate=6 March 2012}}</ref> According to Chilean Junta and former Air Force commander Fernando Matthei, Chilean support included military intelligence gathering, radar surveillance, British aircraft operating with Chilean colours and the safe return of British special forces, among other things.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.mercopress.com/2005/09/03/us-support-to-uk-in-falklands-war-was-decisive|title=US support to UK in Falklands' war was decisive|work=MercoPress|accessdate=25 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225225342/http://en.mercopress.com/2005/09/03/us-support-to-uk-in-falklands-war-was-decisive|archivedate=25 February 2015}}</ref> In April and May 1982, a squadron of mothballed RAF Hawker Hunter fighter bombers departed for Chile, arriving on 22 May and allowing the Chilean Air Force to reform the No. 9 \"Las Panteras Negras\" Squadron. A further consignment of three frontier surveillance and shipping reconnaissance Canberras left for Chile in October. Some authors suggest that Argentina might have won the war had she been allowed to employ the VIth and VIIIth Mountain Brigades, which remained guarding the Andes mountain chain.<ref>Nicholas van der Bijl and David Aldea, 5th Infantry Brigade in the Falklands , p. 28, Leo Cooper 2003</ref> Pinochet subsequently visited [[Margaret Thatcher]] for tea on more than one occasion.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6167351.stm | work=BBC News | title=Pinochet death 'saddens' Thatcher | date=December 11, 2006 | accessdate=April 28, 2010 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070615014947/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6167351.stm | archivedate=June 15, 2007 }}</ref> Pinochet's controversial relationship with Thatcher led [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] to mock Thatcher's [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] as \"the party of Pinochet\" in 1999.\n\n===France===\n{{Further|Operation Condor}}\nAlthough France received many Chilean political refugees, it also secretly collaborated with Pinochet. French journalist [[Marie-Monique Robin]] has shown how [[Val\u00e9ry Giscard d'Estaing]]'s government secretly collaborated with [[National Reorganization Process|Videla's junta]] in Argentina and with Augusto Pinochet's regime in Chile.<ref>[http://www.algeria-watch.org/fr/article/div/livres/escadrons_mort_conclusion.htm Conclusion] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303184912/http://www.algeria-watch.org/fr/article/div/livres/escadrons_mort_conclusion.htm |date=2016-03-03 }} of [[Marie-Monique Robin]]'s ''Escadrons de la mort, l'\u00e9cole fran\u00e7aise'' {{in lang|fr}}/ [http://www.mefeedia.com/entry/2926696/ Watch here film documentary] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522013436/http://www.mefeedia.com/entry/2926696/ |date=2009-05-22 }} (French, English, Spanish)</ref>\n\n[[Greens (France)|Green]] deputies [[No\u00ebl Mam\u00e8re]], [[Martine Billard]] and [[Yves Cochet]] on September 10, 2003 requested a Parliamentary Commission on the \"role of France in the support of military regimes in Latin America from 1973 to 1984\" before the Foreign Affairs Commission of the National Assembly, presided by [[Edouard Balladur]]. Apart from ''[[Le Monde]]'', newspapers remained silent about this request.<ref>[http://www.lemonde.fr/cgi-bin/ACHATS/acheter.cgi?offre=ARCHIVES&type_item=ART_ARCH_30J&objet_id=820135 MM. Giscard d'Estaing et Messmer pourraient \u00eatre entendus sur l'aide aux dictatures sud-am\u00e9ricaines], ''[[Le Monde]]'', September 25, 2003 {{in lang|fr}}</ref> However, deputy [[Roland Blum]], in charge of the Commission, refused to hear Marie-Monique Robin, and published in December 2003 a 12 pages report qualified by Robin as the summum of bad faith. It claimed that no agreement had been signed, despite the agreement found by Robin in the ''[[Quai d'Orsay]]''<ref>\u00ab S\u00e9rie B. Am\u00e9rique 1952-1963. Sous-s\u00e9rie : Argentine, n\u00b0 74. Cotes : 18.6.1. mars 52-ao\u00fbt 63 \u00bb.</ref><ref>[http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/12/rapports/r1295.asp RAPPORT FAIT AU NOM DE LA COMMISSION DES AFFAIRES \u00c9TRANG\u00c8RES SUR LA PROPOSITION DE R\u00c9SOLUTION (n\u00b0 1060), tendant \u00e0 la cr\u00e9ation d'une commission d'enqu\u00eate sur le r\u00f4le de la France dans le soutien aux r\u00e9gimes militaires d'Am\u00e9rique latine entre 1973 et 1984, PAR M. ROLAND BLUM] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150405204244/http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/12/rapports/r1295.asp |date=2015-04-05 }}, [[French National Assembly]] {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\nWhen then Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Dominique de Villepin]] traveled to Chile in February 2004, he claimed that no cooperation between France and the military regimes had occurred.<ref>[http://www.lemonde.fr/cgi-bin/ACHATS/acheter.cgi?offre=ARCHIVES&type_item=ART_ARCH_30J&objet_id=838522 Argentine : M. de Villepin d\u00e9fend les firmes fran\u00e7aises], ''[[Le Monde]]'', February 5, 2003 {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\n===Peru===\nReportedly one of [[Juan Velasco Alvarado]]'s main goal was to militarily reconquer the lands lost by Peru to Chile in the [[War of the Pacific]].<ref name=PCOLSorpresa>[http://www.caretas.com.pe/2004/1826/articulos/chile.html \"La veces que Pinochet casi Ataca al Per\u00fa de Sorpresa\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202185713/http://www.caretas.com.pe/2004/1826/articulos/chile.html |date=2008-12-02 }}. caretas.com. June 3, 2004.</ref> It is estimated that from 1970 to 1975 Peru spent up to 2 Billion USD (roughly 20 Billion USD in 2010's valuation) on Soviet armament.<ref name=utexas/> According to various sources Velasco's government bought between 600 and 1200 [[T-55]] Main Battle Tanks, [[Armoured personnel carrier|APC]]s, 60 to 90 [[Sukhoi 22]] warplanes, 500,000 assault rifles, and even considered the purchase of a British carrier [[Centaur class aircraft carrier|''Centaur''-class]] [[aircraft carrier|light fleet carrier]] [[HMS Bulwark (R08)|HMS Bulwark]].<ref name=utexas>{{cite web|url=http://www.ford.utexas.edu/library/guides/guidecollectionsa-m.asp|title=Gerald R. Ford Presidential Library and Museum|website=www.ford.utexas.edu|accessdate=1 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924014600/http://www.ford.utexas.edu/library/guides/guidecollectionsa-m.asp|archivedate=24 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe enormous amount of weaponry purchased by Peru caused a meeting between former US Secretary of State [[Henry Kissinger]] and Pinochet in 1976.<ref name=utexas/> Velasco's military plan was to launch a massive sea, air, and land invasion against Chile.<ref name=utexas/> In 1999, [[General Pinochet]] claimed that if [[Peru]] had attacked [[Chile]] during 1973 or even 1978, [[Peruvian]] forces could have penetrated deep south into Chilean territory, possibly military taking the Chilean city of [[Copiap\u00f3]] located half way to [[Santiago]].<ref name=\"PCOLSorpresa\"/> The Chilean Armed Forces considered launching a [[preventive war]] to defend itself. Though, Pinochet's Chilean Air Force General [[Fernando Matthei]] opposed a preventive war and responded that \"I can guarantee that the Peruvians would destroy the Chilean Air Force in the first five minutes of the war\".<ref name=\"PCOLSorpresa\"/> Some analysts believe the fear of attack by Chilean and US officials as largely unjustified but logical for them to experience, considering the Pinochet dictatorship had come into power with a coup against democratically elected president [[Salvador Allende]]. According to sources, the alleged invasion scheme could be seen from the Chilean's government perspective as a plan for some kind of leftist counterattack.<ref>[http://www.caretas.com.pe/2004/1826/articulos/chile.html \"La veces que Pinochet casi Ataca al Per\u00fa de Sorpresa\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202185713/http://www.caretas.com.pe/2004/1826/articulos/chile.html |date=2008-12-02 }}, ''Caretas'', June 3, 2004 {{in lang|es}}</ref> While acknowledging the Peruvian plans were revisionistic scholar Kalevi J. Holsti claim more important issues behind were the \"ideological incompatibility\" between the regimes of Velasco Alvarado and Pinochet and that Peru would have been concerned about Pinochet's [[geopolitics|geopolitical]] views on Chile's need of naval [[hegemony]] in the Southeastern Pacific.<ref name=Holsti>{{cite book |last=Holsti |first=Kalevi J.|date=1996 |title=The State, War and the State of War |url= |location= |publisher=Cambridge Studies in International Relations |page=158 |isbn=}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Chileans should stop with the bullshit or tomorrow I shall eat breakfast in Santiago.}}{{center|\u2014Juan Velasco Alvarado<ref name=\"masterson-mil-228-229\">{{cite book|title=Militarism and politics in Latin America: Peru from S\u00e1nchez Cerro to Sendero Luminoso|author=Masterson, Daniel M. |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=1991|isbn=978-0-313-27213-4|pages=228\u2013229|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YYm4wmXl2M4C&pg=PA228}}</ref>}}\n\n===Spain===\n[[Francoist Spain]] had enjoyed warm relations with Chile while Allende was in power. Pinochet admired and was very much influenced by [[Francisco Franco]], but Franco's successors had a cold attitude towards Pinochet as they did not want to be linked to him.<ref>{{cite book |last=Fermandois |first=Joaqu\u00edn |date= |title=Chile. La b\u00fasqueda de la democracia. |volume=5|issue=1960\u20132010 |chapter=Chile en el mundo |location= |page= |isbn=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Corbatta |first=Jorgelina |date= |title=Remapping the Humanities: Identity, Community, Memory, (post)modernity |volume=1 |chapter=The Pinochet Affair in London and Spain |location= |page=125 |isbn=}}</ref> When Pinochet traveled to the funeral of Francisco Franco in 1975 the President of France [[Val\u00e9ry Giscard d'Estaing]] pressured the Spanish government to refuse Pinochet to be at the crowning of [[Juan Carlos I of Spain]] by letting Spanish authorities know that Giscard would not be there if Pinochet was present. Juan Carlos I personally called Pinochet to let him know he was not welcome at his crowning.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ced\u00e9o Alvarado |first=Ernesto |date=February 4, 2008 |title=Rey Juan Carlos abochorn\u00f3 a Pinochet |url=http://www.panamaamerica.com.pa/content/rey-juan-carlos-abochorn%C3%B3-pinochet |newspaper=Panam\u00e1 Am\u00e9rica |access-date=April 4, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419125814/http://www.panamaamerica.com.pa/content/rey-juan-carlos-abochorn%C3%B3-pinochet |archivedate=April 19, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Foreign aid===\nThe previous drop in foreign aid during the Allende years was immediately reversed following Pinochet's ascension; Chile received US$ $322.8 million in loans and credits in the year following the coup.<ref>Petras & Morley, 1974</ref> There was considerable international condemnation of the military regime's human rights record, a matter that the United States expressed concern over as well after [[Orlando Letelier]]'s 1976 assassination in Washington DC.([[Kennedy Amendment]], later ''International Security Assistance and Arms Export Control Act of 1976'').\n\n===Cuban involvement===\n{{see also|Armed resistance in Chile (1973\u20131990)}}\nAfter the Chilean military coup in 1973, Fidel Castro promised Chilean revolutionaries far-reaching aid. Initially Cuban support for resistance consisted of clandestine distribution of funds to Chile, human rights campaigns at the UN to isolate the Chilean dictatorship, and efforts to undermine US-Chilean bilateral relations. Eventually Cuba's policy changed to arming and training insurgents. Once their training was completed, Cuba helped the guerrillas return to Chile, providing false passports and false identification documents.<ref>Tanya Harmer, 'The View from Havana: Chilean Exiles in Cuba and Early Resistance to Chile's Dictatorship's, Hispanic American Historical Review 1 (2016), 109-13</ref> Cuba's official newspaper, [[Granma (newspaper)|Granma]], boasted in February 1981 that the \"Chilean Resistance\" had successfully conducted more than 100 \"armed actions\" throughout Chile in 1980. By late 1980, at least 100 highly trained [[Revolutionary Left Movement (Chile)|MIR]] guerrillas had reentered Chile and the MIR began building a base for future guerrilla operations in [[Neltume]], a mountainous forest region in [[Zona Sur|southern Chile]]. In a massive operation spearheaded by Chilean Army Para-Commandos, security forces involving some 2,000 troops, were forced to deploy in the Neltume mountains from June to November 1981, where they destroyed two MIR bases, seizing large caches of munitions and killing a number of MIR commandos.\nIn 1986, Chilean security forces discovered 80 tons of munitions, including more than three thousand M-16 rifles and more than two million rounds of ammunition, at the tiny fishing harbor of [[Carrizal Bajo]], smuggled ashore from Cuban fishing trawlers off the coast of Chile.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ohmynews.com/articleview/article_view.asp?menu=c10400&no=315665&rel_no=1|title=The Day Pinochet Nearly Died |publisher= OhmyNews International|website=english.ohmynews.com|accessdate=1 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229150650/http://english.ohmynews.com/articleview/article_view.asp?menu=c10400&no=315665&rel_no=1|archivedate=29 February 2012}}</ref> The operation was overseen by Cuban naval intelligence, and also involved the Soviet Union. Cuban Special Forces had also instructed the FPMR guerrillas that ambushed President Augusto Pinochet's motorcade on 8 September 1986, killing five bodyguards and wounding 10.<ref>Castro's Secrets, Brian Latell, p. 125, Macmillan, 2013</ref>\n\n==Cultural life==\n[[Image:Charango player.jpg|right|thumb|[[Charango]], a musical instrument banned by the dictatorship.]]\n{{see also|Book burnings in Chile}}\nInfluenced by [[Antonio Gramsci]]'s work on [[cultural hegemony]], proposing that the ruling class can maintain power by controlling cultural institutions, Pinochet clamped down on cultural dissidence.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Taffet |first1=Jeffrey |title=\"My Guitar is Not for the Rich\": The New Chilean Song Movement and the Politics of Culture |journal=Journal of American Culture |date=1997 |volume=20 |issue=2 |page=92 |doi=10.1111/j.1542-734X.1997.2002_91.x |language=es}}</ref> This brought Chilean cultural life into what sociologist [[Soledad Bianchi]] has called a \"cultural blackout\".<ref name=Morris>Morris, Nancy. 1986. Canto Porque es Necesario Cantar: The New Song Movement in Chile, 1973-1983. ''[[Latin American Research Review]]'', Vol. 21, pp. 117\u2013136.</ref> The government censored non-sympathetic individuals while taking control of mass media.<ref name=Morris/> The formerly thriving [[Nueva canci\u00f3n|Nueva canci\u00f3n scene]] suffered from the exile or imprisonment of many bands and individuals.<ref name=Morris/> A key musician, [[V\u00edctor Jara]], was tortured and killed by elements of the military.<ref name=Morris/> According to [[Eduardo Carrasco]] of [[Quilapay\u00fan]] in the first week after the coup, the military organized a meeting with folk musicians where they announced that the traditional instruments [[charango]] and [[quena]] were banned.<ref name=Morris/> [[Nueva Cancion]] resurfaced in Chile once again in 1975 due to the efforts of musicians who had been active before the coup. This was music of resistance and solidarity, a style that aimed to keep the memory of the Allende years alive.\n\nThe 1980s saw an invasion of [[Argentine rock]] bands into Chile. These included [[Charly Garc\u00eda]], the [[Enanitos Verdes]], [[G.I.T.]] and [[Soda Stereo]] among others.<ref>Torres Quezada, Rodrigo Guillermo. 2007. [http://www.tesis.uchile.cl/tesis/uchile/2007/torres_r/sources/torres_r.pdf El imaginario de rebeld\u00eda y disconformidad a trav\u00e9s de la m\u00fasica rock en los a\u00f1os \u00b490. Desadaptados/as chilenos/as dejan su mensaje.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116074357/http://www.tesis.uchile.cl/tesis/uchile/2007/torres_r/sources/torres_r.pdf |date=2014-01-16 }}</ref>\nContemporary Chilean rock group [[Los Prisioneros]] complained against the ease with which Argentine Soda Stereo made appearances on Chilean TV or in Chilean magazines and the ease they could obtain musical equipment for concerts in Chile.<ref name=Fuentes>Fuentes, Jorge. [http://www.guioteca.com/los-80/la-historica-rivalidad-de-los-prisioneros-y-soda-stereo-%C2%BFquien-gano/ La hist\u00f3rica rivalidad de Los Prisioneros y Soda Stereo, \u00bfqui\u00e9n gan\u00f3?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118123450/http://www.guioteca.com/los-80/la-historica-rivalidad-de-los-prisioneros-y-soda-stereo-%C2%BFquien-gano/ |date=2015-11-18 }}, retrieved on December 12, 2012.</ref> Soda Stereo was invited to [[Vi\u00f1a del Mar International Song Festival]] while Los Prisioneros were ignored despite their popular status.<ref name=\"musicapop\"/> This situation was because Los Prisioneros were censored by media under the influence of the military dictatorship.<ref name=Fuentes/><ref name=\"musicapop\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.musicapopular.cl/3.0/index2.php?op=Artista&id=315 \n |title=Los Prisioneros \n |last=Leiva \n |first=Jorge \n |work=La enciclopedia de la m\u00fasica chilena en Internet \n |publisher=Musicapopular.cl \n |accessdate=2012-11-29 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017034327/http://www.musicapopular.cl/3.0/index2.php?op=Artista&id=315 \n |archivedate=2012-10-17 \n}}</ref> Los Prisioneros' marginalization by the media was further aggravated by their call to vote against the dictatorship on the [[1988 Chilean national plebiscite|plebiscite of 1988]].<ref name=\"musicapop\"/>\n{{quote box |width = 22em |quote = For Chile to become once again the [[land of poets]], and not the land of murderers!|source = \u2014[[Sol y Lluvia]]<ref>[[Sol y Lluvia]] on a live recording of their song \"Voy a hacer el amor\"</ref>}}\n\nExperimental theatre groups from [[Universidad de Chile]] and [[Pontifical Catholic University of Chile]] were restricted by the military regime to performing only theatre classics.<ref name=Pop>{{Citation |last=Richards |first=Keith |year=2005 |title=Pop culture Latin America!: media, arts, and lifestyle |location= |pages=121\u2013122 |url= |accessdate= }}</ref> Some established groups like ''Grupo Ictus'' were tolerated while new formations like ''Grupo Aleph'' were repressed. This last group had its members jailed and forced into exile after performing a parody on the [[1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref name=Pop/> In the 1980s a [[grassroots]] street theatre movement emerged.<ref name=Pop/>\n\nThe dictatorship promoted the figure of Nobel laureate [[Gabriela Mistral]] who was presented as a symbol of \"summission to the authority\" and \"social order\".<ref>{{cite news|date=June 7, 2003|title=Gabriela Mistral: poeta y lesbiana|url=http://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-995948|work=El Tiempo|access-date=June 23, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903031354/http://www.eltiempo.com/archivo/documento/MAM-995948|archivedate=September 3, 2017}}</ref> \n{{clear}}\n\n==Plebiscite and the Return to Democracy==\n{{Main|Chilean return to democracy}}\n\n===1988 Plebiscite===\nFollowing the approval of the [[Constitution of Chile|1980 Constitution]], a [[1988 Chilean national plebiscite|plebiscite was scheduled for October 5, 1988]], to vote on a new eight-year presidential term for Pinochet.\n\nThe Constitution, which took effect on 11 March 1981, established a \"transition period,\" during which Pinochet would continue to exercise executive power and the Junta legislative power, for the next eight years. Before that period ended, a candidate for President was to be proposed by the Commanders-in-Chief of the Armed Forces and Carabinero Chief General for the following period of eight years. The candidate was to be ratified by registered voters in a national plebiscite. On 30 August 1988 Pinochet was declared to be the candidate.<ref>David Altma, \u201cLatin America\u201d, Referendums Around the World, 2018</ref>\n\nThe [[Constitutional Court of Chile]] ruled that the plebiscite should be carried out as stipulated by Article 64 in the Constitution. That included an \"Electoral Space\" during which all positions, in this case, two, ''S\u00ed'' (yes), and ''No'', would have two free slots of equal and uninterrupted TV time, simultaneously broadcast by all TV channels, with no political advertising outside those spots. The allotment was scheduled in two off-prime time slots: one before the afternoon news and the other before the late-night news, from 22:45 to 23:15 each night (the evening news was from 20:30 to 21:30, and prime time from 21:30 to 22:30). The opposition ''No'' campaign, headed by [[Ricardo Lagos]], produced colorful, upbeat programs, telling the Chilean people to vote against the extension of the presidential term. Lagos, in a TV interview, pointed his index finger towards the camera and directly called on Pinochet to account for all the \"disappeared\" persons. The ''S\u00ed'' campaign did not argue for the advantages of extension, but was instead negative, claiming that voting \"no\" was equivalent to voting for a return to the chaos of the UP government.\n\nPinochet lost the 1988 referendum, where 56% of the votes rejected the extension of the presidential term, against 44% for \"''S\u00ed''\", and, following the constitutional provisions, he stayed as President for one more year.  The [[1989 Chilean presidential election|presidential election]] was held in December 1989, at the same time as congressional elections that were due to take place. Pinochet left the presidency on March 11, 1990 and transferred power to political opponent [[Patricio Aylwin]], the new democratically elected president. Due to the same transitional provisions of the constitution, Pinochet remained as Commander-in-Chief of the Army, until March 1998.\n\n===1989 General Elections===\nFrom the 1989 elections onwards the military had officially left the political sphere in Chile. Pinochet did not endorse any candidate publicly. Former Pinochet economic minister [[Hern\u00e1n B\u00fcchi]] ran for president as candidate of the two right-wing parties [[National Renewal (Chile)|RN]] and [[Independent Democratic Union|UDI]]. He had little political experience and was relatively young and credited with Chile's good economic performance in the second half of the 1980s. The right-wing parties faced several problems in the elections: there was considerable infighting between RN and UDI, B\u00fcchi had only very reluctantly accepted to run for president and right-wing politicians struggled to define their position towards the Pinochet regime. In addition to this [[right-wing populist]] [[Francisco Javier Err\u00e1zuriz Talavera]] ran independently for president and made several election promises B\u00fcchi could not match.<ref name=AngellPollack1990/>\n\nThe centre-left coalition [[Concertaci\u00f3n]] was more united and coherent. Its candidate [[Patricio Aylwin]], a [[Christian Democratic Party (Chile)|Christian Democrat]], behaved as if he had won and refused a second television debate with B\u00fcchi. B\u00fcchi attacked Aylwin on a remark he had made concerning that inflation rate of 20% was not much and he also accused Aylwin of making secret agreements with the [[Communist Party of Chile]], a party that was not part of Concertaci\u00f3n.<ref name=AngellPollack1990/> Aylwin spoke with authority about the need to clarify human rights violations but did not confront the dictatorship for it; in contrast, B\u00fcchi, as a former regime minister, lacked any credibility when dealing with human right violations.<ref name=AngellPollack1990/>\n\nB\u00fcchi and Err\u00e1zuriz lost to [[Patricio Aylwin]] in the election. The electoral system meant that the largely Pinochet-sympathetic right was overrepresented in parliament in such a way that it could block any reform to the constitution. This over-representation was crucial for UDI in obtaining places in parliament and securing its political future. The far-left and the far-right performed poorly in the election.<ref name=AngellPollack1990/>\n\n===Presidential Election Results===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n! Candidate\n! Party/coalition\n! Votes\n! %\n|-\n! align=\"left\" | [[Patricio Aylwin]] || align=\"left\" | [[Christian Democrat Party of Chile|PDC]]/[[Coalition of Parties for Democracy|CPD]] || 3,850,571 || 55.17\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[Hern\u00e1n B\u00fcchi]] || align=\"left\" | [[Independent (politics)|Independent]]/[[Alliance (Chile)|D&P]] || 2,052,116 || 29.40\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[Francisco Javier Err\u00e1zuriz Talavera|Francisco Javier Err\u00e1zuriz]] || align=\"left\" | Independent || 1,077,172 || 15.43\n|- style=\"font-weight: bold; background: #ececec;\"\n| align=\"left\" colspan=\"2\" | Valid votes || 6,979,859 || 100.00\n|-\n| align=\"left\" colspan=\"2\" | Null votes || 103,631 || 1.45 \n|-\n| align=\"left\" colspan=\"2\" | Blank votes || 75,237 || 1.05\n|- style=\"font-weight: bold; background: #ececec;\"\n| align=\"left\" colspan=\"2\" | Total votes || 7,158,727 || 100.00\n|-\n| align=\"left\" colspan=\"2\" | Registered voters/turnout || 7,557,537 || 94.72\n|-\n| align=\"left\" colspan=\"4\" | <small>Source: [http://historico.servel.cl/SitioHistorico/index1989_pres.htm Tricel via Servel]</small>\n|}\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Memorial Detenidos Desaparecidos R\u00e9gimen Militar Chile.jpg|thumb|Memorial to the people who were [[Forced disappearance|disappeared]] during the Pinochet's regime]] \nFollowing the restoration of Chilean democracy and during the successive administrations that followed Pinochet, the Chilean economy has prospered, and today the country is considered a Latin American success story. Unemployment stands at 7% as of 2007, with poverty estimated at 18.2% for the same year, both relatively low for the region.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ci.html#Econ |title=The World Factbook |publisher=Cia.gov |accessdate=2014-08-18 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923081816/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ci.html#Econ |archivedate=2017-09-23 }}</ref> However, in 2019 the Chilean government faced public scrutiny for its economic policies. In particular, for the long-term effects of Pinochet\u2019s neoliberal policies. <ref>[https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/11/05/chile-ongoing-protests-pinochet-dictatorship-looms-large/ Ongoing Protests Show That Pinochet\u2019s Dictatorship Still Looms Large in Chilean Politics<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Mass protests broke out throughout Santiago, due to increasing prices of the metro ticket.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-50106743 Chile protests: Unrest in Santiago over metro fare increase - BBC News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> For many Chileans this highlighted the disproportionate distribution of wealth amongst Chile.  \n\nThe \"Chilean Variation\" has been seen as a potential model for nations that fail to achieve significant economic growth.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=I7VgAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Chilean+Variation%22&dq=%22Chilean+Variation%22 |title=Australian Slavonic and East European Studies: Journal of the Australian and ...  |via=Books.google.com |date=2008-04-23 |accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref> The latest is Russia, for whom [[David Christian (historian)|David Christian]] warned in 1991 that \"dictatorial government presiding over a transition to capitalism seems one of the more plausible scenarios, even if it does so at a high cost in human rights violations.\"<ref>Christian, 1992</ref>\n\nA survey published by pollster CERC on the eve of the 40th anniversary commemorations of the coup gave some idea of how Chileans perceived the dictatorship. According to the poll, 55% of Chileans regarded the 17 years of dictatorship as either bad or very bad, while 9% said they were good or very good.<ref>(https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-24014501)</ref> In 2013, the newspaper El Mercurio asked Chileans if the state had done enough to compensate victims of the dictatorship for the atrocities they suffered; 30% said yes, 36% said no, and the rest were undecided.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-24014501 |title = Chile still split over Pinochet legacy|work = BBC News|date = 2013-09-09|last1 = Long|first1 = Gideon}}</ref> In order to keep the memories of the victims and the disappeared alive, memorial sites have been constructed throughout Chile, as a symbol of the country\u2019s past. Some notable examples include Villa Grimaldi, Londres 38, Paine Memorial and the Museum of Memory and Human Rights. <ref>Katrien Klep: Tracing collective memory: Chilean truth commissions and memorial sites, in: Memory Studies 3 (2012), p. 259-269 </ref> These memorials were built by family members of the victims, the government and ex-prisoners of the dictatorship. These have become popular tourist destinations and have provided a visual narrative of the atrocities of the dictatorship. These memorials have aided in Chile\u2019s reconciliation process, however, there is still debate amongst Chile as to whether these memorials do enough to bring the country together. \n\nThe relative economic success of the Pinochet dictatorship has brought about some political support for the former dictatorship. In 1998, then-Brazilian congressman and retired military officer [[Jair Bolsonaro]] praised Pinochet, saying his regime \"should have killed more people\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Jair Bolsonaro: The would-be dictator who might soon rule Brazil |url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/world/2018/10/jair-bolsonaro-the-would-be-dictator-who-might-soon-rule-brazil.html |work=[[Newshub]] |date=8 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nEvery year on the anniversary of the coup, Chile becomes more polarised and protests can be seen throughout the country.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2013/09/11/world/americas/chile-coup-anniversary/index.html On 40th anniversary of Chile coup, divisions remain - CNN<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Leftist supporters use this day to honour the victims of the dictatorship and highlight the atrocities for which the perpetrators still haven\u2019t been brought to justice. \n\nThe indictment and arrest of Pinochet occurred on 10 October 1998 in London. He returned to Chile in March 2000 but was not charged with the crimes against him. On his 91st birthday on 25 November 2006, in a public statement to supporters, Pinochet for the first time claimed to accept \"political responsibility\" for what happened in Chile under his regime, though he still defended the [[Chilean coup of 1973|1973 coup]] against Salvador Allende. In a statement read by his wife Lucia Hiriart, he said, ''Today, near the end of my days, I want to say that I harbour no rancour against anybody, that I love my fatherland above all. ... I take political responsibility for everything that was done''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/6184696.stm|title=Pinochet 'takes responsibility'|publisher=BBC News \u2013 Americas|accessdate=25 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225182728/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/6184696.stm|archivedate=25 February 2015|date=2006-11-25}}</ref> Despite this statement, Pinochet always [[Augusto Pinochet's arrest and trial|refused to be confronted to Chilean justice]], claiming that he was senile. He died two weeks later while indicted on human rights and corruption charges, but without having been sentenced.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* [[John R. Bawden|Bawden, JR.]] (2016). ''The Pinochet Generation: The Chilean Military in the Twentieth Century'', Tuscaloosa: University of Alabama Press.\n* [[David Christian (historian)|Christian, D.]] (1992). \"Perestroika and World History\", ''Australian Slavonic and East European studies'', 6(1), pp.&nbsp;1\u201328.\n* [[Mark Falcoff|Falcoff, M.]] (2003). \"Cuba: The Morning After\", p.&nbsp;26. AEI Press, 2003.\n* [[James Petras|Petras, J.]], & Vieux, S. (1990). \"The Chilean 'Economic Miracle': An Empirical Critique\", ''Critical Sociology'', 17, pp.&nbsp;57\u201372.\n* Roberts, K.M. (1995). \"From the Barricades to the Ballot Box: Redemocratization and Political Realignment in the Chilean Left\", ''Politics & Society'', 23, pp.&nbsp;495\u2013519.\n* Schatan, J. (1990). \"The Deceitful Nature of Socio-Economic Indicators\". ''Development'', 3-4, pp.&nbsp;69\u201375.\n* Sznajder, M. (1996). \"Dilemmas of economic and political modernisation in Chile: A jaguar that wants to be a puma\", ''Third World Quarterly'', 17, pp.&nbsp;725\u2013736.\n* Valdes, J.G. (1995). ''Pinochet's economists: The Chicago School in Chile'', Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.\n* Steve Anderson [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928020337/http://www.tcgnews.com/santiagotimes/index.php?nav=story&story_id=8732&topic_id=1 Body of Chile's Former President Frei May Be Exumed], ''The Santiago Times'', April 5, 2005\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.vitalpoetics.com/wounds-of-humanity-in-diamela-eltits-the-sacred-cow-and-the-fourth-world Literature and Torture in Pinochet's Chile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091004110250/http://www.memoriaviva.com/culpables/criminales%20p/pinochet.htm Criminals of the military dictatorship : Augusto Pinochet]\n\n{{1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat}}\n{{Augusto Pinochet}}\n{{Chile topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Military Government Of Chile (1973-90)}}\n[[Category:Military dictatorship of Chile (1973\u20131990)| ]]\n[[Category:1970s in Chile]]\n[[Category:1980s in Chile]]\n[[Category:1973 establishments in Chile]]\n[[Category:1990 disestablishments in Chile]]\n[[Category:Augusto Pinochet]]\n[[Category:Former polities of the Cold War]]\n[[Category:Military dictatorships|Chile]]\n[[Category:Political history of Chile]]\n[[Category:Former member states of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1973]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1990]]\n", "name_user": "Vacant0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Military_dictatorship_of_Chile_(1973%E2%80%931990)"}
{"title_page": "Scott Hamner", "text_new": "{{short description|American television writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n'''Scott Hamner''', is an [[United States|American]] [[television]] [[writer]]. He was nominated for a [[WGA Award]] in 2006 for his work on [[CBS Daytime|CBS']]''[[The Young and the Restless]]''.<ref name=imdb>{{cite web|title=Scott Hamner|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1000124/|publisher=imdb.com|accessdate=11 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=tv>{{cite web|title=Scott Hamner|url=http://www.tv.com/people/scott-hamner/|publisher=tv.com|accessdate=11 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=soap>{{cite web|title=\u2018Y&R\u2019 Wins 2013 Writers Guild Award|url=http://www.soapoperanetwork.com/topic/scott-hamner|publisher=soapoperanetwork.com|accessdate=11 October 2013}}</ref> He is the son of [[Earl Hamner]].\n\n==Positions held==\n*''The Homecoming: A Christmas Story'' (Actor: 1971) \n*''[[Berrenger's]]'' ([[Story Editor]]: 1985)\n*''[[Boone (TV series)|Boone]]''\n*''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]'' (Story Editor: 1986\u201387)\n*''[[Falcon Crest]]'' (Writer: 1982\u201384)\n*''[[Knots Landing]]''\n**Writer: 1980s\n**Story Editor: 1990\u201391\n*''[[The Waltons]]'' \n*''[[Second Chances (American TV series)|Second Chances]]'' (Executive Story Editor: 1993\u201394)\n*''[[Zoe Busiek: Wild Card]]''\n*''[[As the World Turns]]'' (Script Writer: 1994\u201397)\n*''[[Port Charles]]''\n**Co-Head Writer: 1997\u201399\n**[[Head Writer]]: 1999\u20132000\n*''[[The Young and the Restless]]''\n**Story Consultant: July\u2013September 2006\n**Breakdown Writer: July\u2013October 2006\n**[[Head Writer|Co-Head Writer]]: October 2006\u2013December 2007, April\u2013May 2008, August 2008\u2013November 2012\n**Associate Head Writer: May\u2013August 2008\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nHamner has been nominated for several [[Daytime Emmys]]. In 1996, his nomination for ''Outstanding Writing In A Drama Series'' was shared with [[Juliet Law Packer]], [[Richard Culliton]], [[Garin Wolf]], [[Don C