g In A Drama Series'' was shared with [[Juliet Law Packer]], [[Richard Culliton]], [[Garin Wolf]], [[Don Chastain]], [[Christina Covino]], [[Caroline Franz]], [[Patti Dizenzo]], [[Susan Kirshenbaum]], [[John Kuntz]], [[Meredith Post]], [[Mary Ryan (writer)|Mary Ryan]], [[Addie Walsh]], [[Lorin Wertheimer]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cbs.com/daytime/yr CBS Daytime: Y&R]\n*[http://www.knotslanding.net/interviews/scotthamner.html Hamner 2006 Interview]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|\n before=[[Lynn Marie Latham]]|\n title=[[Head Writer]] of ''[[Port Charles]]''|\n after=[[Karen Harris (writer)|Karen Harris]]<br>Jonathon Estrin |\n years=early 1999 - December 1999\n}}\n{{succession box|\n before= [[Lynn Marie Latham]] <br> [[Kay Alden]] <br> [[John F. Smith]]|\n title=[[Head Writer|Co-Head Writer]] of [[The Young and the Restless]] <br>(with [[Lynn Marie Latham]]: 10/26/06-12/22/07) <br> (with [[Kay Alden]]: 10/26/06-12/22/06)<br>(with [[John F. Smith]]: 10/26/06-11/10/06)|\n after= [[Josh Griffith]]<br>[[Maria Arena Bell]]|\n years=October 26, 2006 - December 22, 2007\n}}\n{{succession box|\n before= [[Josh Griffith]]<br>[[Maria Arena Bell]]|\n title=[[Head Writer|Co-Head Writer]] of [[The Young and the Restless]] <br>(with [[Maria Arena Bell]])<br>(with [[Josh Griffith]]: 04/15/08-04/21/08)|\n after= [[Maria Arena Bell]]|\n years=April 15 - May 8, 2008\n}}\n{{succession box|\n before= [[Maria Arena Bell]]<br>[[Hogan Sheffer]]|\n title=[[Head Writer|Co-Head Writer]] of [[The Young and the Restless]] <br>(with [[Hogan Sheffer]])<br>(with [[Maria Arena Bell]]:8/11/08-10/22/12)<br>(with [[Josh Griffith]]: 10/22/12-11/2/12)|\n after= [[Josh Griffith]]<br>[[Hogan Sheffer]]|\n years=August 11, 2008 - November 2, 2012\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamner, Scott}}\n[[Category:American soap opera writers]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Soap opera producers]]\n[[Category:American television producers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n\n\n{{US-tv-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePositions held:copy edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scott_Hamner"}
{"title_page": "Brunswick Heritage Museum", "text_new": "{{Infobox museum\n| name                = Brunswick Heritage Museum\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| image               = File:Brunswick Heritage Museum logo.png.jpg\n| caption             = Museum Logo\n| alt                 = Old-Fashioned Steam Locomotive Logo\n| map_type            = USA Maryland\n| map_caption         = Location within Maryland\n| coordinates         = {{coord|39.3129637|-77.6280838|display=inline}}\n| map dot label        = Brunswick Heritage Museum\n| established         = c. 1966, 1974\n| dissolved           = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| former_name = Brunswick Railroad Museum\n| location            = 40 West Potomac Street, [[Brunswick, Maryland]] 21716, USA\n| type                = [[Railroad museum|Railroad]] and [[History museum|history]]\n| accreditation       = \n| key_holdings        = [[HO scale|Model railroad]]\n| collections         = \n| collection_size     = \n| visitors            = \n| founder             = \n| director            = \n| president           = \n| curator             = Rebecca O\u2019Leary\n| owner               = [[Brunswick Potomac Foundation]]\n| publictransit       = [[Brunswick (MARC station)]]\n| car_park            = \n| parking             =\n| network             = \n| website             = {{URL|brunswickmuseum.org}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Brunswick Heritage Museum''' is a [[railway museum|railroad]] and history museum in [[Brunswick, Maryland]].\n\n==History==\nThe Brunswick Potomac Foundation was founded during the town's 75th Anniversary Diamond Jubilee and originally focused on hosting local events including Railroad Days, an annual street festival held during the first full weekend in October.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brunswickmd.gov/tourism/|title=Come and Visit Brunswick\u2026|publisher=[[Brunswick, Maryland#Tourism|City of Brunswick]]|accessdate=25 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025115909/https://www.brunswickmd.gov/tourism/|archivedate=25 October 2014}}</ref> In 1974, the group purchased a building from a fraternal lodge to host a museum.  Founded as the '''Brunswick Railroad Museum''', the museum originally focused exclusively on railroads. In 2013, the name was changed to '''Brunswick Heritage Museum''' and the mission of the museum expanded to include the history of Brunswick, a [[company town]] of the [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Doyle | first = Kim | coauthors = | title = New name for museum | newspaper = Brunswick Citizen | location = Brunswick, MD | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = 2013-03-21 | url = | accessdate = }}</ref>\n\n==Collection==\nThe first floor has a younger children's play and dress up area. The second floor focuses on life in Brunswick during different time periods, and on the [[C&O Canal]]. The third floor consists of an [[HO scale]] model railroad layout depicting the B&O Railroad's [[Metropolitan Subdivision|Metropolitan line]] (the MET) from [[Washington, DC]] to Brunswick, Maryland in the late 1950s. The model also includes the Brunswick [[classification yard]]s, which were completed in 1907 and measured {{convert|5|mi|km}} long, the largest and most modern in the nation to serve only one railroad company at that time.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\n==Brunswick Visitor Center==\nThe Brunswick Visitor Center is also on the first floor and is maintained by the [[National Park Service]] as a tenant.<Ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/choh/planyourvisit/brunswickvisitorcenter.htm |title=Brunswick Visitor Center |last= |first= |date= |publisher=[[National Park Service]] |accessdate=25 October 2014}}</Ref>  This is a unit of the [[Chesapeake and Ohio Canal National Historical Park]].\n\n==Building==\nThe museum is housed in the former [[Improved Order of Red Men]] fraternal lodge. The three-story brick building or \"wigwam\" was built in 1904 by the Delaware Tribe No. 43 who occupied the building until 1945.<Ref>{{cite book |last=Rubin |first=Mary H. |date=2007 |title=Brunswick |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ym4zAoUMgq4C&pg=PA100&lpg#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=[[Mount Pleasant, South Carolina]] |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |page=99 |isbn=9780738536590 |accessdate=2014-10-24 }}</Ref> The [[Fraternal Order of Eagles]] Aerie No. 1136 took over the lodge and removed the [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] statue from the entrance. That statue is now on the second floor of the museum. The museum chose the building because it is located less than a block from the [[Brunswick Line]] [[MARC Train|MARC]] commuter line and four tracks of the [[CSX Transportation|CSX]] mainline.\n\n==References==\n[[File:BrunswickTrainM3.jpg|left|thumb|250px|Model of the [[Point of Rocks (MARC station)|Point of Rocks Station]]]]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.brunswickmuseum.org/ The Brunswick Heritage Museum]\n\n{{Maryland museums}}\n\n{{Coord|39.3129637|-77.6280838|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Railroad museums in Maryland]]\n[[Category:History museums in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Museums in Frederick County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Model railway shows and exhibitions]]\n[[Category:Improved Order of Red Men]]\n[[Category:Miniature railroads in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox museum\n| name                = Brunswick Heritage Museum\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| image               = File:Brunswick Heritage Museum logo.png.jpg\n| caption             = Museum Logo\n| alt                 = Old-Fashioned Steam Locomotive Logo\n| map_type            = USA Maryland\n| map_caption         = Location within Maryland\n| coordinates         = {{coord|39.3129637|-77.6280838|display=inline}}\n| map dot label        = Brunswick Heritage Museum\n| established         = c. 1966, 1974\n| dissolved           = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| former_name = Brunswick Railroad Museum\n| location            = 40 West Potomac Street, [[Brunswick, Maryland]] 21716, USA\n| type                = [[Railroad museum|Railroad]] and [[History museum|history]]\n| accreditation       = \n| key_holdings        = [[HO scale|Model railroad]]\n| collections         = \n| collection_size     = \n| visitors            = \n| founder             = \n| director            = \n| president           = \n| curator             = Rebecca O\u2019Leary\n| owner               = [[Brunswick Potomac Foundation]]\n| publictransit       = [[Brunswick (MARC station)]]\n| car_park            = \n| parking             =\n| network             = \n| website             = {{URL|brunswickmuseum.org}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Brunswick Heritage Museum''' is a [[railway museum|railroad]] and history museum in [[Brunswick, Maryland]].\n\n==History==\nThe Brunswick Potomac Foundation was founded during the town's 75th Anniversary Diamond Jubilee and originally focused on hosting local events including Railroad Days, an annual street festival held during the first full weekend in October.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brunswickmd.gov/tourism/|title=Come and Visit Brunswick\u2026|publisher=[[Brunswick, Maryland#Tourism|City of Brunswick]]|accessdate=25 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025115909/https://www.brunswickmd.gov/tourism/|archivedate=25 October 2014}}</ref> In 1974, the group purchased a building from a fraternal lodge to host a museum.  Founded as the '''Brunswick Railroad Museum''', the museum originally focused exclusively on railroads. In 2013, the name was changed to '''Brunswick Heritage Museum''' and the mission of the museum expanded to include the history of Brunswick, a [[company town]] of the [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]]. <ref>{{cite news | last = Doyle | first = Kim | coauthors = | title = New name for museum | newspaper = Brunswick Citizen | location = Brunswick, MD | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = 2013-03-21 | url = | accessdate = }}</ref>\n\n==Collection==\nThe first floor has a younger children's play and dress up area. The second floor focuses on life in Brunswick during different time periods, and on the [[C&O Canal]]. The third floor consists of an [[HO scale]] model railroad layout depicting the B&O Railroad's [[Metropolitan Subdivision|Metropolitan line]] (the MET) from [[Washington, DC]] to Brunswick, Maryland in the late 1950s. The model also includes the Brunswick [[classification yard]]s, which were completed in 1907 and measured {{convert|5|mi|km}} long, the largest and most modern in the nation to serve only one railroad company at that time.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\n==Brunswick Visitor Center==\nThe Brunswick Visitor Center is also on the first floor and is maintained by the [[National Park Service]] as a tenant.<Ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/choh/planyourvisit/brunswickvisitorcenter.htm |title=Brunswick Visitor Center |last= |first= |date= |publisher=[[National Park Service]] |accessdate=25 October 2014}}</Ref>  This is a unit of the [[Chesapeake and Ohio Canal National Historical Park]].\n\n==Building==\nThe museum is housed in the former [[Improved Order of Red Men]] fraternal lodge. The three-story brick building or \"wigwam\" was built in 1904 by the Delaware Tribe No. 43 who occupied the building until 1945.<Ref>{{cite book |last=Rubin |first=Mary H. |date=2007 |title=Brunswick |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ym4zAoUMgq4C&pg=PA100&lpg#v=onepage&q&f=false |location=[[Mount Pleasant, South Carolina]] |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |page=99 |isbn=9780738536590 |accessdate=2014-10-24 }}</Ref> The [[Fraternal Order of Eagles]] Aerie No. 1136 took over the lodge and removed the [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] statue from the entrance. That statue is now on the second floor of the museum. The museum chose the building because it is located less than a block from the [[Brunswick Line]] [[MARC Train|MARC]] commuter line and four tracks of the [[CSX Transportation|CSX]] mainline.\n\n==References==\n[[File:BrunswickTrainM3.jpg|left|thumb|250px|Model of the [[Point of Rocks (MARC station)|Point of Rocks Station]]]]\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.brunswickmuseum.org/ The Brunswick Heritage Museum]\n\n{{Maryland museums}}\n\n{{Coord|39.3129637|-77.6280838|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Railroad museums in Maryland]]\n[[Category:History museums in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Museums in Frederick County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Model railway shows and exhibitions]]\n[[Category:Improved Order of Red Men]]\n[[Category:Miniature railroads in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "ColinBear", "label": "safe", "comment": "Space wasn\u2019t needed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brunswick_Heritage_Museum"}
